WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:09.280
[Amit Varma]: The other day someone asked me, give me an example of the seen and the unseen.

00:00:09.280 --> 00:00:13.440
[Amit Varma]: Now everything is an example because there is so much unseen in everything.

00:00:13.440 --> 00:00:15.680
[Amit Varma]: But one perfect example is this.

00:00:15.680 --> 00:00:16.680
[Amit Varma]: Men and women.

00:00:16.680 --> 00:00:21.880
[Amit Varma]: We live in a world designed by men, for men and that world is the seen world.

00:00:21.880 --> 00:00:26.080
[Amit Varma]: Women have to fit themselves into this world and all that they do to fit in, all that they

00:00:26.080 --> 00:00:30.640
[Amit Varma]: go through inside is unseen by men and often by women themselves.

00:00:30.640 --> 00:00:33.080
[Amit Varma]: We tell ourselves the world is what it is.

00:00:33.080 --> 00:00:36.000
[Amit Varma]: We normalize as many oppressions and injustices.

00:00:36.000 --> 00:00:39.920
[Amit Varma]: The cost of this is a psychological cost that cannot be measured.

00:00:39.920 --> 00:00:44.600
[Amit Varma]: The cost of this is also an economic cost that we can try to measure and that is more

00:00:44.600 --> 00:00:45.860
[Amit Varma]: than just a number.

00:00:45.860 --> 00:00:49.840
[Amit Varma]: If we care about the world we live in, we have to try and peel away the layers of this

00:00:49.840 --> 00:00:55.280
[Amit Varma]: unseen world of the Indian woman who is lonely in the kitchen, lonely in her bedroom, lonely

00:00:55.280 --> 00:00:56.680
[Amit Varma]: at the workplace.

00:00:56.680 --> 00:01:02.960
[Amit Varma]: If we want to solve this problem, first we have to try to understand it.

00:01:02.960 --> 00:01:08.400
[Unknown]: Welcome to The Seen and the Unseen, our weekly podcast on economics, politics and behavioral

00:01:08.400 --> 00:01:09.400
[Unknown]: science.

00:01:09.400 --> 00:01:15.360
[Unknown]: Please welcome your host, Amit Verma.

00:01:15.360 --> 00:01:16.760
[Amit Varma]: Welcome to The Seen and the Unseen.

00:01:16.760 --> 00:01:20.840
[Amit Varma]: My guest today is Shreyana Bhattacharya, an economist at the World Bank and the author

00:01:20.840 --> 00:01:25.560
[Amit Varma]: of a brilliant new book called Desperately Seeking Shahrukh, India's Lonely Young Women

00:01:25.560 --> 00:01:28.360
[Amit Varma]: and the Search for Intimacy and Independence.

00:01:28.360 --> 00:01:30.560
[Amit Varma]: This is not a book on Shahrukh Khan or cinema.

00:01:30.560 --> 00:01:33.080
[Amit Varma]: This is a book on the loneliness of the Indian woman.

00:01:33.080 --> 00:01:36.360
[Amit Varma]: And it is a book that is constructed on a mind-boggling scale.

00:01:36.360 --> 00:01:41.040
[Amit Varma]: This is a book that contains anthropology, sociology and economics, disciplines that

00:01:41.040 --> 00:01:42.920
[Amit Varma]: often don't come together.

00:01:42.920 --> 00:01:46.320
[Amit Varma]: And it is told with storytelling that stands with the best of literature.

00:01:46.320 --> 00:01:51.360
[Amit Varma]: We see the interior lives of women across different classes and castes and regions and

00:01:51.360 --> 00:01:57.000
[Amit Varma]: circumstances, in the bedroom and in the kitchen, in barren fields and concrete offices, united

00:01:57.000 --> 00:02:01.400
[Amit Varma]: by crippling solitude, which Shreyana explores through the device of their common love for

00:02:01.400 --> 00:02:02.520
[Amit Varma]: Shahrukh Khan.

00:02:02.520 --> 00:02:07.200
[Amit Varma]: This is also reflected in numbers, in the many movements within the labor market, in

00:02:07.200 --> 00:02:11.080
[Amit Varma]: an impact on our economy that is more tangible than feelings.

00:02:11.080 --> 00:02:14.400
[Amit Varma]: And this is what is so amazing about this book and about Shreyana's gaze.

00:02:14.400 --> 00:02:17.760
[Amit Varma]: She is as good at zooming in as she is at zooming out.

00:02:17.760 --> 00:02:22.000
[Amit Varma]: We get inside the heads of different young women across the country.

00:02:22.000 --> 00:02:25.120
[Amit Varma]: And we also get a sense of the bigger picture.

00:02:25.120 --> 00:02:29.480
[Amit Varma]: Economists and sociologists and anthropologists and novelists will often see different parts

00:02:29.480 --> 00:02:30.480
[Amit Varma]: of the elephant.

00:02:30.480 --> 00:02:35.840
[Amit Varma]: Shreyana sees them all equally well and shows us, well, the elephant in the room.

00:02:35.840 --> 00:02:38.200
[Amit Varma]: That makes a book the best kind of scholarship.

00:02:38.200 --> 00:02:40.480
[Amit Varma]: And it makes Shreyana the best kind of scholar.

00:02:40.480 --> 00:02:45.240
[Amit Varma]: I hope young people listening to this and reading a book will find themselves inspired

00:02:45.240 --> 00:02:46.560
[Amit Varma]: and energized.

00:02:46.560 --> 00:02:50.400
