[Amit Varma]: about Indian society that can really open your eyes into how this country works in so

00:05:13.140 --> 00:05:18.060
[Amit Varma]: many different ways and economics is just a part of it. But you know, before the book

00:05:18.060 --> 00:05:22.180
[Amit Varma]: and before Shah Rukh, tell me a bit about yourself. So where did you grow up? What kind

00:05:22.180 --> 00:05:25.220
[Amit Varma]: of kid were you? Do you remember watching your first Shah Rukh film?

00:05:25.220 --> 00:05:30.980
[Guest]: I mean, I must actually say I don't have, I struggle to recall my childhood. So it's

00:05:30.980 --> 00:05:38.700
[Guest]: not extremely lucid for me. I was born in Calcutta, then moved to Durgapur. So dad was

00:05:38.700 --> 00:05:46.380
[Guest]: a steel, Tata steel man, worked in human resources. And I have very vivid memories of how stressful

00:05:46.380 --> 00:05:53.180
[Guest]: that was for him because he used to manage negotiations with labor unions and workers,

00:05:53.180 --> 00:05:57.860
[Guest]: which created a lot of, it's a difficult space to be because essentially he was constantly

00:05:57.860 --> 00:06:03.060
[Guest]: bargaining while they were fighting for their rights. And so I think this notion of unions

00:06:03.060 --> 00:06:07.660
[Guest]: and labor and what it means to be workers and what it means to manage large organizations

00:06:07.660 --> 00:06:14.180
[Guest]: and keep people happy. I think seeing him struggle with that, I remember that very clearly.

00:06:14.180 --> 00:06:18.260
[Guest]: And those are some interesting conversations from the past that I remember him just coming

00:06:18.260 --> 00:06:23.300
[Guest]: back and grumbling about how entrenched patronage networks were essentially within labor unions

00:06:23.300 --> 00:06:29.940
[Guest]: as well. This is particularly true for Jharkhand, Bengal, what was Bihar back then. And then

00:06:29.940 --> 00:06:36.860
[Guest]: we moved, funnily enough, when I was around, I think five or four, to Chandigarh. And my

00:06:36.860 --> 00:06:43.180
[Guest]: mother and father believe that I must be the most Punjabi of all bongs out there because

00:06:43.180 --> 00:06:48.900
[Guest]: essentially that's Chandigarh was where I learned Hindi, my idioms, the way I speak,

00:06:48.900 --> 00:06:53.340
[Guest]: all of that completely happened when I was there. I went to nursery school there. I have

00:06:53.340 --> 00:06:57.900
[Guest]: very fond memories of Chandigarh. To me, it's just all sky and just a gorgeous area and

00:06:57.900 --> 00:07:03.860
[Guest]: architecture and all of that. And then we moved to Delhi where my mother was working

00:07:03.860 --> 00:07:09.820
[Guest]: as a social worker for the UNHCR. She was managing refugees who were coming in from

00:07:09.820 --> 00:07:15.260
[Guest]: Afghanistan. And it was her job to help them fill out the paperwork to get benefits that

00:07:15.260 --> 00:07:21.420
[Guest]: the UN essentially allocated to refugees were settling into India. And we had days and nights

00:07:21.420 --> 00:07:27.380
[Guest]: where once she fainted in office, once she fainted at hospital because just the hours

00:07:27.380 --> 00:07:32.420
[Guest]: and the expectations and the stress and it was, I think, psychologically very difficult.

00:07:32.420 --> 00:07:37.980
[Guest]: Social work is a very difficult job psychologically. We know that. And I remember being a kid watching

00:07:37.980 --> 00:07:42.100
[Guest]: her and being quite fearful, actually, of, you know, just how much she was dealing with

00:07:42.100 --> 00:07:46.980
[Guest]: and how much she was doing. And all these young men and women who had come who were

00:07:46.980 --> 00:07:51.740
[Guest]: hoping to resettle, they'd left everything, had abandoned their homes and livelihoods

00:07:51.740 --> 00:07:58.580
[Guest]: in Afghanistan, were now in Delhi in defence colony, waiting outside a refugee centre and

00:07:58.580 --> 00:08:02.540
[Guest]: all their hopes pinned on paperwork. Right. And I think somewhere there, perhaps my early

00:08:02.540 --> 00:08:07.500
[Guest]: interest in the welfare state, the politics of paperwork, social protection, safety nets,

00:08:07.500 --> 00:08:12.180
[Guest]: which is an area now I work on, really began, I think, watching my mum. So I'd finished

00:08:12.180 --> 00:08:18.060
[Guest]: school. I'd be dropped off near her refugee centre. And I'd sit next to her. And there

00:08:18.060 --> 00:08:23.180
[Guest]: were these hordes of young Afghan people who I couldn't understand what they were saying.

00:08:23.180 --> 00:08:27.060
[Guest]: And there were interpreters. But I used to watch her and her patience with people. And

00:08:27.060 --> 00:08:32.100
[Guest]: it just it was remarkable to me. And it was extremely exotic. And I remember that very

00:08:32.100 --> 00:08:37.580
[Guest]: well. And on the other hand, my father at that time was working for Moria Sheraton.

00:08:37.580 --> 00:08:44.140
[Guest]: You know, he was, again, managing human resources in a big hotel, very glamorous, but also extremely

00:08:44.140 --> 00:08:49.300
[Guest]: hard hours, saying a lot of yes to things that I sensed he really didn't want to say

00:08:49.300 --> 00:08:53.420
[Guest]: yes to and having to deal with, you know, we know hospitality is one of the most difficult

00:08:53.420 --> 00:08:58.540
[Guest]: sectors to work in, because people just treat service staff and people who work in hospitality

00:08:58.540 --> 00:09:02.980
[Guest]: terribly in our country, and they continue to do so. And I think my father really dealt

00:09:02.980 --> 00:09:09.180
[Guest]: with that. So it was moving from labour unions into difficult customers, posh difficult customers

00:09:09.180 --> 00:09:16.060
[Guest]: in Delhi. And I think my memory of childhood, honestly, is being very conscious of the jobs

00:09:16.060 --> 00:09:22.940
[Guest]: that my parents did. I was very aware of just how complex those jobs were, how difficult

00:09:22.940 --> 00:09:28.740
[Guest]: dealing with people was, because both their jobs involved with an immense amount of, you

00:09:28.740 --> 00:09:35.140
[Guest]: know, constant negotiation with tons and tons of people. And there was this one scary moment,

00:09:35.140 --> 00:09:40.180
[Guest]: which I'll, I'll never forget, which is we used to live in this home in Delhi. And one

00:09:40.180 --> 00:09:45.980
[Guest]: night, essentially, someone broke the glass of the house. And later, we found out it was

00:09:45.980 --> 00:09:50.020
[Guest]: actually one of the Afghan refugees, because he was upset that my mother had not signed

00:09:50.020 --> 00:09:54.740
[Guest]: off on a piece of paper, he'd found out, I don't know how, there was all kinds of case

00:09:54.740 --> 00:10:00.340
[Guest]: files that were formed. And I think I just grew up realising that our lives are very

00:10:00.340 --> 00:10:05.340
[Guest]: precarious. I mean, seeing that, right, that someone felt the urge to essentially violate

00:10:05.340 --> 00:10:10.260
[Guest]: someone's home and to make someone feel unsafe. It came from the fact that they themselves

00:10:10.260 --> 00:10:15.060
[Guest]: felt so unsafe and so precarious in their life. So I think my childhood, I mean, I remember

00:10:15.060 --> 00:10:20.700
[Guest]: as a kid, I just remember being very conscious of these very early memories. Somehow this

00:10:20.700 --> 00:10:25.140
[Guest]: has stayed with me. And then the other stuff was just incredibly banal, right? So I went

00:10:25.140 --> 00:10:30.900
[Guest]: to a school in Delhi, I, you know, picked up all the reading habits that are very typical

00:10:30.900 --> 00:10:35.860
[Guest]: of kids born in the early 1980s. I think, you know, right from be it, you know, Enid

00:10:35.860 --> 00:10:41.740
[Guest]: Leighton to, I started reading Jane Austen, I think much earlier than many of my other

00:10:41.740 --> 00:10:47.540
[Guest]: friends probably did. I was quite young. And, and I think through that, suddenly then being

00:10:47.540 --> 00:10:51.500
[Guest]: exposed to satellite television in the early 90s, which was just so incredibly exciting,

00:10:51.500 --> 00:10:55.860
[Guest]: right? I mean, I've heard you talk about this with so many of your other guests in the past.

00:10:55.860 --> 00:11:01.580
[Guest]: And being obsessed with the X files and discovering mathematics, which was for me at a point of

00:11:01.580 --> 00:11:05.660
[Guest]: time was just a really, to me, math was just this beautiful language, which I really wanted

00:11:05.660 --> 00:11:10.180
[Guest]: to understand and use, but I struggled to completely. I'm not a great mathematician,

00:11:10.180 --> 00:11:14.460
[Guest]: but it's something that's always interested me. And so I just remember my childhood being,

00:11:14.460 --> 00:11:18.820
[Guest]: you know, spending a lot of time with books, struggling with trying to understand a lot

00:11:18.820 --> 00:11:22.220
[Guest]: of math problems and puzzles. I think that was something that was really important and

00:11:22.220 --> 00:11:27.820
[Guest]: fun for me to do. I wasn't a very social kid. I'm not still very social. I'm quite reticent

00:11:27.820 --> 00:11:33.740
[Guest]: and a bit of a recluse. And I think observing people who are very social has been part of,

00:11:33.740 --> 00:11:38.340
[Guest]: I think, my growing up years. I mean, when I was a teenager, even in, you know, my late

00:11:38.340 --> 00:11:42.620
[Guest]: teens, I was friends with people who are far more boisterous than, you know, popular girls

00:11:42.620 --> 00:11:48.660
[Guest]: in school or boys who are really sought after for their social credentials or who they were.

00:11:48.660 --> 00:11:53.540
[Guest]: And I watched. I think maybe because I read Jane Austen at a very early age, I learned

00:11:53.540 --> 00:11:58.740
[Guest]: the value and pleasure of just watching and observing. And so, yeah, I think those have

00:11:58.740 --> 00:12:03.900
[Guest]: been the sense of experiences, I think the books. And as for Shah Rukh, I encountered

00:12:03.900 --> 00:12:10.740
[Guest]: him. My mother's family comes from a small town in Bengal. It's called Kollani, which

00:12:10.740 --> 00:12:17.980
[Guest]: is it's further out from Kolkata. And I was sent to Kollani for essentially summer holidays

00:12:17.980 --> 00:12:22.980
[Guest]: so that, you know, my parents could have some break, a little bit of time to themselves.

00:12:22.980 --> 00:12:25.940
[Guest]: And I used to spend a lot of time with my grandmother and my grandfather. And I think

00:12:25.940 --> 00:12:29.780
[Guest]: a lot of my reading habits, in fact, particularly came from my grandmum. She's really someone

00:12:29.780 --> 00:12:34.660
[Guest]: who encouraged me to read and she was an avid reader. She used to read Bengali literature,

00:12:34.660 --> 00:12:39.420
[Guest]: but she was an avid reader and she would suggest lots of things to me. And there was a cinema

00:12:39.420 --> 00:12:44.300
[Guest]: hall which still exists. And their house was right opposite the railway station of Kollani.

00:12:44.300 --> 00:12:47.340
[Guest]: You could see it. It was so exciting for me because I would go there and I would spend

00:12:47.340 --> 00:12:51.940
[Guest]: all my time staring at these trains just going in and out and the people in them. And I used

00:12:51.940 --> 00:12:56.460
[Guest]: to write, make notes then as well about what I was seeing. And I was just trying to capture,

00:12:56.460 --> 00:13:00.940
[Guest]: I think, what I was seeing constantly and constantly being unhappy with the way I was

00:13:00.940 --> 00:13:09.100
[Guest]: capturing it. And there was a cinema hall next to her home and they were playing Baazigar.

00:13:09.100 --> 00:13:15.620
[Guest]: And I think this must have been 1993 or 1994. And I went to watch Baazigar, which actually

00:13:15.620 --> 00:13:20.540
[Guest]: I do not think is the first film anyone should be watching of Shah Rukhs because he's actively

00:13:20.540 --> 00:13:24.980
[Guest]: harming women, killing them, putting them in suitcases, all kinds of terrible things

00:13:24.980 --> 00:13:30.020
[Guest]: are happening. But I loved it. I have to just confess, I mean, I realise I'm saying something

00:13:30.020 --> 00:13:33.740
[Guest]: that won't be politically correct, but I know that it's actually true for so many fans,

00:13:33.740 --> 00:13:38.540
[Guest]: female fans who may feel uncomfortable with the things that he was doing. When we saw

00:13:38.540 --> 00:13:44.460
[Guest]: him in that film, there was something about the charge of desperation, revenge, wanting

00:13:44.460 --> 00:13:50.060
[Guest]: to sort of make a point just who he was, the way he looked, all of that. I just loved it.

00:13:50.060 --> 00:13:57.180
[Guest]: It was just love at first sight. And I think after that, I started following up just on

00:13:57.180 --> 00:14:02.380
[Guest]: his... Each time we had a film out, I would try and watch it. But to be honest, my parents

00:14:02.380 --> 00:14:05.960
[Guest]: weren't particularly keen that I go and start watching his films, especially these films.

00:14:05.960 --> 00:14:08.700
[Guest]: And they found it a bit perplexing. And this, as you can tell from the book, is actually

00:14:08.700 --> 00:14:13.700
[Guest]: very common with a lot of upper middle class and elite, you know, English speaking fans.

00:14:13.700 --> 00:14:17.760
[Guest]: The parents were a bit confused as to why these young girls were suddenly connecting

00:14:17.760 --> 00:14:24.620
[Guest]: with a man who was not a particularly ideal figure at that time. Right. And I saw DDLJ

00:14:24.620 --> 00:14:30.020
[Guest]: with my parents in 1995. And that completely then was just, you know, I was bowled over

00:14:30.020 --> 00:14:33.580
[Guest]: and who wasn't? I mean, it's just now so trite to say that I think the country fell in love

00:14:33.580 --> 00:14:40.700
[Guest]: with him at that point. You didn't Amit, but the country did. And we'll talk about that.

00:14:40.700 --> 00:14:48.300
[Guest]: And after that, Amit, actually what I remember of him the most is that when I was a latchkey

00:14:48.300 --> 00:14:52.740
[Guest]: kid and I think we're a meagre minority in India still, you know, people whose both their

00:14:52.740 --> 00:14:55.740
[Guest]: parents are working, because I think in the book, as you know, most women don't work in

00:14:55.740 --> 00:14:59.460
[Guest]: the country. My mother was working, my father was working. So I'd come back home and I just

00:14:59.460 --> 00:15:06.260
[Guest]: let myself into the house. And satellite TV had now emerged. And Mr. Khan started doing

00:15:06.260 --> 00:15:10.260
[Guest]: all these interviews. Suddenly, you know, there was an interview on Sony, I still remember

00:15:10.260 --> 00:15:14.660
[Guest]: with Farida Jalal, I think, or, you know, various others. And I used to watch these

00:15:14.660 --> 00:15:20.120
[Guest]: interviews. And somehow, I think it was the interviews that really, I connected with the

00:15:20.120 --> 00:15:27.860
[Guest]: person I saw in those interactions. And to me, he just captured this, this idea of feeling

00:15:27.860 --> 00:15:31.380
[Guest]: left out, but then also trying to make it there was something about what how he was

00:15:31.380 --> 00:15:38.300
[Guest]: presenting himself. And a fan was born at that stage. I mean, I think I loved imagery

00:15:38.300 --> 00:15:42.320
[Guest]: and DDLJ and Baazigar and all of that, I won't deny it. But I think it was the interviews

00:15:42.320 --> 00:15:47.140
[Guest]: that really set me off on this path of being a nutty fan that I still continue to be well

00:15:47.140 --> 00:15:53.200
[Guest]: into my late 30s. I wouldn't say though that Mr. Khan was a very integral part of my childhood

00:15:53.200 --> 00:15:58.580
[Guest]: or teenage years. I mean, he was there and I watched him. But I think it was only after

00:15:58.580 --> 00:16:05.620
[Guest]: I became I think, in my 20s, where I started rediscovering some of the old films again.

00:16:05.620 --> 00:16:09.820
[Guest]: And particularly through the course of the book, I think actually my fandom for him has

00:16:09.820 --> 00:16:14.620
[Guest]: been enriched because of just the way I've heard different people talk about him. But

00:16:14.620 --> 00:16:18.860
[Guest]: I saw him, I think it was that early 90s phase. And it was he was he was like a friend, he

00:16:18.860 --> 00:16:22.140
[Guest]: was someone who would just sort of see on TV, and he was giving you guidance about how

00:16:22.140 --> 00:16:26.820
[Guest]: to live life. And I remember that very well. And I think that helped with all the competition

00:16:26.820 --> 00:16:31.580
[Guest]: and just the anxiety of just what will my job be? What will my life be like? He was

00:16:31.580 --> 00:16:35.860
[Guest]: just a diversion from that. And that helped. But I think my, my, my fandom, I think has

00:16:35.860 --> 00:16:40.220
[Guest]: now has been burnished in a way well into my late 30s, that I don't think it was even

00:16:40.220 --> 00:16:43.220
[Guest]: in my teenage years or my, you know, when I was a kid.

00:16:43.220 --> 00:16:47.860
[Amit Varma]: So isn't Bhajigarh the film with that song, Kitabi Bahut Si Pari Hogi Tumne? And you were

00:16:47.860 --> 00:16:48.860
[Guest]: a reader.

00:16:48.860 --> 00:16:50.860
[Guest]: That's right. Exactly. Exactly. Exactly.

00:16:50.860 --> 00:16:53.580
[Guest]: Pining for a man who would throw you off the roof.

00:16:53.580 --> 00:17:00.060
[Guest]: Yeah, but by God, you know, Amit, now, when I look at that film, and I watched it recently,

00:17:00.060 --> 00:17:05.380
[Guest]: I really I mean, I was wondering what was the younger version of me number one doing

00:17:05.380 --> 00:17:09.740
[Guest]: watching that film? Now, I don't think we live in a world where they let a kid, you

00:17:09.740 --> 00:17:15.780
[Guest]: know, I think I must have been 12 or something, what to watch that movie. And, you know, and

00:17:15.780 --> 00:17:19.700
[Guest]: then the other thing I was, I was watching, I was thinking, God, filmmaking was so innocent

00:17:19.700 --> 00:17:24.120
[Guest]: back then as well. Because while he's doing all these terrible things, there was this

00:17:24.120 --> 00:17:28.620
[Guest]: way in which these films were made as if it was so matter of fact, there was no, there

00:17:28.620 --> 00:17:32.940
[Guest]: was no code to try and hide the fact that he was just a terrible person in parts of

00:17:32.940 --> 00:17:39.180
[Guest]: the film. And yet you could feel that he he drew some empathy out of you. And yet it was

00:17:39.180 --> 00:17:44.820
[Guest]: done without any, you know, it wasn't, it was just a very simple way of telling a story,

00:17:44.820 --> 00:17:49.220
[Guest]: which I just doubt you'd see now. And my God was those outfits he was wearing, which were

00:17:49.220 --> 00:17:53.380
[Guest]: just those oversized blazers. And then in the song and dance, there's some strange,

00:17:53.380 --> 00:17:58.780
[Guest]: you know, outfits going on. Those films, I mean, they'll never be made again. And I think

00:17:58.780 --> 00:18:04.340
[Guest]: that part that partly makes me sad. But partly, I'm also amused at the fact that how far you

00:18:04.340 --> 00:18:08.660
[Guest]: know, the is a very simple era, I think, in even telling a very difficult story, but it's

00:18:08.660 --> 00:18:13.340
[Guest]: just told in this, you know, it's a potboiler. But if you look at the story, it's actually

00:18:13.340 --> 00:18:17.860
[Guest]: quite, it's quite dangerous. And it's quite complex for what it's trying to do. And yet

00:18:17.860 --> 00:18:19.740
[Guest]: it's told in this really simple way.

00:18:19.740 --> 00:18:23.820
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, I mean, if you look at films as a modern mythology, you know, looking back, if you

00:18:23.820 --> 00:18:27.740
[Amit Varma]: just look at all our myths, all our great epics, the people we are supposed to sympathize

00:18:27.740 --> 00:18:31.940
[Amit Varma]: with do some pretty terrible things. Exactly. But it is kind of understood that you just

00:18:31.940 --> 00:18:37.740
[Amit Varma]: go along with them, you're there with them. So here's my question. You've mentioned about

00:18:37.740 --> 00:18:43.220
[Amit Varma]: how you like to watch, you like to observe other people. You also were keenly aware of

00:18:43.220 --> 00:18:48.060
[Amit Varma]: differences, I guess, in the sense that you could see what the Afghan refugees went through.

00:18:48.060 --> 00:18:54.300
[Amit Varma]: So in a sense, you had an extra layer of awareness that people within that typical bubble, your

00:18:54.300 --> 00:18:59.260
[Amit Varma]: peers might have been a part of they weren't aware of. At what point did you start becoming

00:18:59.260 --> 00:19:03.660
[Amit Varma]: self aware? Because one of the things I loved about the book was a very personal way in

00:19:03.660 --> 00:19:09.260
[Amit Varma]: which you start which is so unvarnished, and so self aware, and you know, brutal with yourself.

00:19:09.260 --> 00:19:13.380
[Amit Varma]: And when I think of my own self awareness, I don't think I was at all self aware in my

00:19:13.380 --> 00:19:18.980
[Amit Varma]: teens or into adulthood, right? It's only after a certain period of time that you actually

00:19:18.980 --> 00:19:23.420
[Amit Varma]: start thinking about stuff in that way you take that step out of yourself and look that

00:19:23.420 --> 00:19:27.820
[Amit Varma]: so were you also sort of watching yourself like it? You just mentioned that you can't

00:19:27.820 --> 00:19:31.620
[Amit Varma]: imagine why you watch Bazigar as a 12 year old to begin with, right? So you're looking

00:19:31.620 --> 00:19:35.980
[Amit Varma]: back on your old self and you're reflecting on that. Is that something that came to you

00:19:35.980 --> 00:19:41.340
[Amit Varma]: naturally because, you know, you read a lot, you wanted to write, obviously, you were a

00:19:41.340 --> 00:19:46.460
[Amit Varma]: watcher. So were you also watching yourself? Tell me a little bit about that process where

00:19:46.460 --> 00:19:51.580
[Amit Varma]: you begin to be able to see yourself because I'm sure that there are defensive reactions

00:19:51.580 --> 00:19:55.500
[Amit Varma]: which stop us from doing that. Because you won't like what you see.

00:19:55.500 --> 00:19:59.660
[Guest]: Yeah. In fact, a dear friend of mine recently told me that, you know, it's amazing that

00:19:59.660 --> 00:20:04.260
[Guest]: technologies so many of us use to just hide from ourselves, right? We're constantly hiding

00:20:04.260 --> 00:20:10.060
[Guest]: from ourselves. I was hiding from myself. Absolutely. And in fact, the book, the reason

00:20:10.060 --> 00:20:16.820
[Guest]: I write personally, is that the book became a way for me to actually not hide anymore.

00:20:16.820 --> 00:20:20.760
[Guest]: I'm very transparent about it. I think in the way I write it, it sounds self indulgent.

00:20:20.760 --> 00:20:24.420
[Guest]: But my hope is because the book is actually about the stories of others. The self indulgence

00:20:24.420 --> 00:20:27.840
[Guest]: is balanced out with the fact that this is actually a story of just women in the country

00:20:27.840 --> 00:20:34.860
[Guest]: and society, as you said, Amit. But for me, I think I really entered that path of self

00:20:34.860 --> 00:20:44.340
[Guest]: awareness through feminism. And what I mean by that, Amit, is that in 2004, 2005, I was

00:20:44.340 --> 00:20:48.620
[Guest]: studying economics. I was studying development studies. And at that time, I'd taken a bunch

00:20:48.620 --> 00:20:55.180
[Guest]: of courses on gender and economics. And there were these wonderful books by people like

00:20:55.180 --> 00:20:59.980
[Guest]: Naila Kabir. There's a book called Power to Choose, which actually, to me, was the first.

00:20:59.980 --> 00:21:04.180
[Guest]: For those who don't know, Naila Kabir is a revered feminist economist. She was the head

00:21:04.180 --> 00:21:08.300
[Guest]: of the International Association of Feminist Economists for a while, a woman from Bangladesh

00:21:08.300 --> 00:21:14.940
[Guest]: who wrote about what starts to happen when young Bangladeshi women start making money

00:21:14.940 --> 00:21:21.420
[Guest]: in export zones in their country. And instead of taking a very macro picture, she started

00:21:21.420 --> 00:21:27.060
[Guest]: going into people's homes and using economic theory to understand, well, how do the incentives

00:21:27.060 --> 00:21:34.700
[Guest]: of behavior within families, love affairs, relationships start to change? And I'd always

00:21:34.700 --> 00:21:39.900
[Guest]: been someone who was very moved, it sounds odd, but very moved by the language of economics.

00:21:39.900 --> 00:21:45.300
[Guest]: So the language of taxes, incentives, I think, where many of us see chaos, economists tend

00:21:45.300 --> 00:21:50.740
[Guest]: to be able to see some frameworks. And I find that terribly moving, actually, not just illuminating,

00:21:50.740 --> 00:21:55.060
[Guest]: but I find it the language is something that really, I really enjoy it. It's to me, it's

00:21:55.060 --> 00:22:00.220
[Guest]: like seeing a painting that moves you. And I read these books, and I devoured them. So

00:22:00.220 --> 00:22:04.860
[Guest]: I read Naila Kabir, I read every paper she wrote, and she's definitely my, you know,

00:22:04.860 --> 00:22:09.660
[Guest]: one of my heroes. At that time, I also started reading Marilyn Waring, these are, you know,

00:22:09.660 --> 00:22:15.220
[Guest]: founding texts of feminist economics. And in these books, I started to realize that

00:22:15.220 --> 00:22:24.100
[Guest]: the way I was behaving in my day to day interactions with men, with my mother, with my best friend,

00:22:24.100 --> 00:22:30.120
[Guest]: is so deeply structurally coded by what women's experiences and women's expectations should

00:22:30.120 --> 00:22:38.380
[Guest]: be of society and the economy within it. And I think it was that reading and those experiences

00:22:38.380 --> 00:22:43.660
[Guest]: as a student, with feminist texts that really pushed me into sort of thinking a lot more

00:22:43.660 --> 00:22:49.860
[Guest]: carefully about how I was behaving and my modes of behavior. And so I think it started

00:22:49.860 --> 00:22:54.700
[Guest]: there. And then I had a bunch of terrible love affairs, one of which I talk about in

00:22:54.700 --> 00:23:02.140
[Guest]: the book quite, quite transparently. And nothing, I think, triggers more self reflection than

00:23:02.140 --> 00:23:06.860
[Guest]: heartbreak, right, of any kind. And I think that can be of any form. But I think for women,

00:23:06.860 --> 00:23:12.820
[Guest]: particularly heartbreak in the area of love and intimacy tends to be very potent because

00:23:12.820 --> 00:23:17.340
[Guest]: women are socialized into believing that loving is what you're supposed to do, right? Love

00:23:17.340 --> 00:23:22.500
[Guest]: is so fundamental to a female life because the economy and the world outside is supposed

00:23:22.500 --> 00:23:26.780
[Guest]: to be for men and the intimacy and the interior world is supposed to be for women. So women

00:23:26.780 --> 00:23:31.500
[Guest]: have to secure love. And so when you don't secure love or the love that you think you've

00:23:31.500 --> 00:23:38.900
[Guest]: secured suddenly vanishes, you are left asking a lot of questions about why did I choose

00:23:38.900 --> 00:23:44.300
[Guest]: this path? What was the dynamic between me and this person? And this was, I think, Amit

00:23:44.300 --> 00:23:49.420
[Guest]: around 2013. And by then, actually, the idea of the book has somewhat germinated already

00:23:49.420 --> 00:23:52.780
[Guest]: because I was interviewing people in the past, but I had a very different idea what the book

00:23:52.780 --> 00:23:57.740
[Guest]: would be at that time. But I think it was around that 2013 period where along with,

00:23:57.740 --> 00:24:03.900
[Guest]: I think, all the sort of early feminist texts that I had read, compounded with this heartbreak,

00:24:03.900 --> 00:24:09.700
[Guest]: I then started reading women, largely actually American women, funnily enough, whose memoirs

00:24:09.700 --> 00:24:16.260
[Guest]: I just found incredibly moving. I was reading Vivian Gornick and I was reading Emily Witt.

00:24:16.260 --> 00:24:19.820
[Guest]: If anyone ever just wants to understand, I don't know, I think there's something really

00:24:19.820 --> 00:24:22.820
[Guest]: beautiful particularly about the way Vivian Gornick, I call her the first lady of the

00:24:22.820 --> 00:24:26.680
[Guest]: contemporary memoir. And there was something about the way she was writing and reflecting

00:24:26.680 --> 00:24:31.420
[Guest]: on her own experiences. And this book that I read was when she was in her 60s. And I

00:24:31.420 --> 00:24:35.340
[Guest]: realized one of the things she wrote in the book was keeping oneself company is one of

00:24:35.340 --> 00:24:39.780
[Guest]: the hardest things that you will ever have to do. And I realized at that point, it was

00:24:39.780 --> 00:24:44.580
[Guest]: this eureka moment for me when I was reading her writing, and at the same time dealing

00:24:44.580 --> 00:24:49.260
[Guest]: with my own heartbreak and you know what was happening in my life in Delhi, that I started

00:24:49.260 --> 00:24:54.100
[Guest]: to realize that I was behaving in ways that were partly were predictable, because I think

00:24:54.100 --> 00:24:58.300
[Guest]: I didn't want to keep myself company. It was almost, you know, textbook escapism, right?

00:24:58.300 --> 00:25:02.660
[Guest]: So you escape into torrid, complicated love affairs, because you don't really want to

00:25:02.660 --> 00:25:06.620
[Guest]: do the business of just being with yourself and sitting with yourself and being at peace

00:25:06.620 --> 00:25:11.860
[Guest]: with who you are. You want to just sort of run away from all of that. And in a way, and

00:25:11.860 --> 00:25:15.180
[Guest]: each time I try and run away, I just come back because you know, there's that great

00:25:15.180 --> 00:25:20.700
[Guest]: line and wherever you are, you are always there. And I, I think it was that heartbreak

00:25:20.700 --> 00:25:25.980
[Guest]: along with all the reading I was doing that pushed me to be, I don't think I'm fully self

00:25:25.980 --> 00:25:30.820
[Guest]: aware yet. I don't I think this is like a practice for all of us. But it pushed me to

00:25:30.820 --> 00:25:37.420
[Guest]: think much more carefully about how structures, incentives, status, taxes, all these things

00:25:37.420 --> 00:25:42.700
[Guest]: were shaping the way I was behaving. And I think that finds itself in the page. What

00:25:42.700 --> 00:25:47.940
[Guest]: I will also say, Amit, is that I think the book is a I think I'm far more self aware

00:25:47.940 --> 00:25:52.620
[Guest]: in the book than I probably am in person, if that makes sense. I think writing allows

00:25:52.620 --> 00:25:57.580
[Guest]: you that space, right? Because then you can be liberated of even having to perform a certain

00:25:57.580 --> 00:26:01.060
[Guest]: way, even right now, when I'm with you, you know, there's a there's a performance here.

00:26:01.060 --> 00:26:06.060
[Guest]: And when you're writing, I wrote, not to perform, but to liberate myself from performing, I

00:26:06.060 --> 00:26:09.940
[Guest]: do know that there is writing that sometimes does the opposite, which can also be very

00:26:09.940 --> 00:26:14.860
[Guest]: beautiful. I mean, that has its own, you know, balance, and it means something. But for me,

00:26:14.860 --> 00:26:22.340
[Guest]: I wrote in a somewhat open hearted way, because I wanted to escape to me writing and reading

00:26:22.340 --> 00:26:26.140
[Guest]: is the place where I've escaped that performance art of, you know, being a certain kind of

00:26:26.140 --> 00:26:30.060
[Guest]: person in Delhi. And the last thing I will say, and probably we'll get into it more is

00:26:30.060 --> 00:26:38.580
[Guest]: I think that Delhi is a city in particular, and the way it's set up, it guarantees unlike

00:26:38.580 --> 00:26:43.980
[Guest]: a I really believe unlike a Mumbai or unlike a Kolkata, definitely not like a Bangalore,

00:26:43.980 --> 00:26:48.900
[Guest]: there is something particular about Delhi, that just gets people to put on this farce

00:26:48.900 --> 00:26:54.180
[Guest]: of who you are, much, much more. And I'm yet to understand it, maybe my next book or whatever

00:26:54.180 --> 00:26:59.300
[Guest]: I try and do, we'll delve into that I try and attack it a bit in this book. I don't

00:26:59.300 --> 00:27:03.620
[Guest]: think I've understood it enough. I don't think I want to glibly dismiss it as always because

00:27:03.620 --> 00:27:07.500
[Guest]: it's the capital and there's power play and all of that. I don't think it's that I don't

00:27:07.500 --> 00:27:13.340
[Guest]: think it's just because it's a city of power. There is something about opportunity and the

00:27:13.340 --> 00:27:20.060
[Guest]: way opportunities mediated in Delhi, the way network wealth in a way works in Delhi, that

00:27:20.060 --> 00:27:25.300
[Guest]: everyone then starts to behave in ways, which almost dissents, there is no incentive in

00:27:25.300 --> 00:27:29.940
[Guest]: Delhi to be self aware, because you're always playing this game within a certain milieu.

00:27:29.940 --> 00:27:36.060
[Guest]: And I think the book was a place for me to escape from that. And then if I'm able to

00:27:36.060 --> 00:27:39.780
[Guest]: actually practice that level of self awareness in real life, one can only hope and I'm a

00:27:39.780 --> 00:27:43.620
[Guest]: work in progress. But thank you for noticing that it that's, it's nice to hear.

00:27:43.620 --> 00:27:47.140
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, I mean, what do you say of Delhi always having to be performative, always playing

00:27:47.140 --> 00:27:51.260
[Amit Varma]: a game, one that is at some level true of everything. I mean, you're not just performing

00:27:51.260 --> 00:27:55.020
[Amit Varma]: for me, you're also performing for yourself, right? Yeah. And specifically what you said

00:27:55.020 --> 00:27:59.700
[Amit Varma]: about Delhi could also be true of South Bombay and, you know, the various other little parts

00:27:59.700 --> 00:28:04.540
[Amit Varma]: of the country, a couple of things like one reason I really what elevates this book for

00:28:04.540 --> 00:28:10.140
[Amit Varma]: me beyond what I expected is that it is not just a project, it is your project, the personal

00:28:10.140 --> 00:28:14.940
[Amit Varma]: is very much part of it, which is one of the things I really enjoyed about it, because

00:28:14.940 --> 00:28:18.780
[Amit Varma]: then you know that the quest is real. And and you can see where it's coming from the

00:28:18.780 --> 00:28:24.140
[Amit Varma]: way it cuts across. The other thing that strikes me and this is this is a very interesting

00:28:24.140 --> 00:28:29.260
[Amit Varma]: sort of mix of two different aspects, which many people would think are contradictory,

00:28:29.260 --> 00:28:33.980
[Amit Varma]: but which should actually be seen together. And one of them is that you're embracing the

00:28:33.980 --> 00:28:39.580
[Amit Varma]: messiness of real life. People are complex, you're acknowledging those complexities, you're

00:28:39.580 --> 00:28:44.260
[Amit Varma]: not really passing judgment, you're vicious about certain kinds of people. And we'll discuss

00:28:44.260 --> 00:28:48.540
[Amit Varma]: those kinds of people. But on these individuals, you're not really passing judgment, you're

00:28:48.540 --> 00:28:54.020
[Amit Varma]: incredibly empathetic. And that's one aspect of it. Yeah. And that's something that you'd

00:28:54.020 --> 00:29:00.020
[Amit Varma]: expect, say, from literature. And the other aspect of it is, like earlier, you spoke about

00:29:00.020 --> 00:29:04.980
[Amit Varma]: being moved by mathematics. And I get that I really do. Yeah. When when there's a beautiful,

00:29:04.980 --> 00:29:10.620
[Amit Varma]: elegant sort of expression of a deep truth, it hits you in a visceral way, right? Yeah.

00:29:10.620 --> 00:29:16.780
[Amit Varma]: And I see that aspect also, because running through this is also you know, you're an economist,

00:29:16.780 --> 00:29:21.020
[Amit Varma]: there is a fair amount of data in this book, though, in a very reader friendly way. And

00:29:21.020 --> 00:29:26.620
[Amit Varma]: there is also to some extent, that clinical gaze that you know, this is a data, this also

00:29:26.620 --> 00:29:31.020
[Amit Varma]: shows a kind of reality. So what you're doing is, you're bringing together these two pictures

00:29:31.020 --> 00:29:36.180
[Amit Varma]: of reality, both of which are equally valid, but most people will focus on one. So often,

00:29:36.180 --> 00:29:39.740
[Amit Varma]: you'll see economists who will give you a bunch of numbers, but they don't come alive,

00:29:39.740 --> 00:29:44.100
[Amit Varma]: they're not vivid, they may be the truth. And equally, you will have people paint you

00:29:44.100 --> 00:29:49.540
[Amit Varma]: stories of lives, human struggles and so on. But you don't see a larger picture. And that's

00:29:49.540 --> 00:29:54.700
[Amit Varma]: also the truth, right? And you've kind of brought these together. And I want to actually

00:29:54.700 --> 00:29:59.420
[Amit Varma]: ask you about these two aspects separately before we get to how they come together. And

00:29:59.420 --> 00:30:04.160
[Amit Varma]: I want to start with the literature aspect. Like you said, you read a lot, you were watching,

00:30:04.160 --> 00:30:09.420
[Amit Varma]: you would sit by the railway station and write little stories, I presume, of what you saw,

00:30:09.420 --> 00:30:13.820
[Amit Varma]: which is similar to something I used to do back in the day. And it's such a writer's

00:30:13.820 --> 00:30:19.340
[Amit Varma]: habit. So clearly, there is a storyteller, someone wanting to be a storyteller within

00:30:19.340 --> 00:30:23.220
[Amit Varma]: that, right? So tell me a little bit about that aspect of it. What kind of books did

00:30:23.220 --> 00:30:26.980
[Amit Varma]: you read? What kind of books did you like? What really moved you? You know, was there

00:30:26.980 --> 00:30:30.940
[Amit Varma]: something which made you say that, I want to do, I want to write like this. So these

00:30:30.940 --> 00:30:32.740
[Guest]: are the kind of stories I want to tell.

00:30:32.740 --> 00:30:38.300
[Guest]: Yeah, Amit, you know, firstly, I have to say, I thought of myself as a reader, more than

00:30:38.300 --> 00:30:43.180
[Guest]: a writer. In fact, I didn't even know that I had this book in me. It reached Shruti Devi,

00:30:43.180 --> 00:30:47.780
[Guest]: who's my agent, but she's really not my agent. She's my guide in this book. And I think she

00:30:47.780 --> 00:30:53.260
[Guest]: saw the book as a writing text, because for me, it was just a bunch of things that I had.

00:30:53.260 --> 00:30:57.700
[Guest]: I think a lot of us do this, right? We just make notes. These were diary entry notes.

00:30:57.700 --> 00:31:01.000
[Guest]: I didn't particularly know that they were lyrical. There was a way I was writing and

00:31:01.000 --> 00:31:06.020
[Guest]: I wrote it and I somehow thought with some grand fit of confidence that I would put it

00:31:06.020 --> 00:31:10.420
[Guest]: all together. And so I've actually always seen myself and I think still see myself as

00:31:10.420 --> 00:31:16.860
[Guest]: a reader, more than a writer. And the books that I absolutely love, you know, that there

00:31:16.860 --> 00:31:23.220
[Guest]: are sort of two genres there. One is, I think I hinted at this sort of large genre, particularly,

00:31:23.220 --> 00:31:27.780
[Guest]: I think a lot of women writing what we would call confessional style writing, which tends

00:31:27.780 --> 00:31:32.140
[Guest]: to get dismissed at a point, you know, I'm thinking of Kamala Das in India, I'm thinking

00:31:32.140 --> 00:31:36.380
[Guest]: of, as I said, Vivian Gornick before, I'm thinking of Deborah Levy, I'm thinking of

00:31:36.380 --> 00:31:42.380
[Guest]: a lot of women who wrote about themselves, but it was never this self indulgent trite,

00:31:42.380 --> 00:31:48.940
[Guest]: right? It was, it was actually a very rigorous, disciplined look at life entering the world

00:31:48.940 --> 00:31:52.420
[Guest]: through your own experiences, but in a way you're commenting on the world. And you're

00:31:52.420 --> 00:31:58.980
[Guest]: just situating yourself very honestly. And to me, these books in particular book called

00:31:58.980 --> 00:32:04.000
[Guest]: Odd Woman in the City by Vivian Gornick was, for me, just eye opening and what writing

00:32:04.000 --> 00:32:09.780
[Guest]: could do. It just just changed the way I was thinking of text. And I was one of those people

00:32:09.780 --> 00:32:13.420
[Guest]: who thought memoir and all of this was sort of, you know, again, as I said, just somewhat

00:32:13.420 --> 00:32:18.220
[Guest]: narcissistic effort to just dwell on yourself and make even, you know, really banal things

00:32:18.220 --> 00:32:22.300
[Guest]: seem lofty, but it really wasn't. And I think I read these women and I realised that there

00:32:22.300 --> 00:32:28.460
[Guest]: was a way to situate yourself in larger structural forces that were very important. There was

00:32:28.460 --> 00:32:33.940
[Guest]: Bell Hooks, who recently sadly passed away. And her books, again, just her books were

00:32:33.940 --> 00:32:37.420
[Guest]: a bit different because they were much more theoretical. They were essentially, in a way,

00:32:37.420 --> 00:32:41.020
[Guest]: they were prescriptive somewhat, they were telling you how to live. But I found them

00:32:41.020 --> 00:32:48.180
[Guest]: very instructive in, again, thinking about all these very everyday feelings we have feeling

00:32:48.180 --> 00:32:53.140
[Guest]: unloved, feeling lonely, feeling cut up, short changed, all of us deal with these negative

00:32:53.140 --> 00:32:57.460
[Guest]: feelings. And what I loved about these books was that they were telling you that these

00:32:57.460 --> 00:33:01.020
[Guest]: negative feelings, well, number one, you were not alone in them, which I think is the function

00:33:01.020 --> 00:33:06.140
[Guest]: of art. But the other was that they were telling you, unlike other kinds of art, they were

00:33:06.140 --> 00:33:10.540
[Guest]: actually telling you that there's a structural reason why you seem to be persisting with

00:33:10.540 --> 00:33:15.820
[Guest]: these feelings. And you seem to also always be dwelling on these feelings. And I realised

00:33:15.820 --> 00:33:21.900
[Guest]: that there was a way to write about intimacy then, which would very beautifully connect

00:33:21.900 --> 00:33:25.860
[Guest]: with the structures of the economy. Suddenly, I think the notes that I had kept from 2006

00:33:25.860 --> 00:33:29.980
[Guest]: with all these fans that I had interviewed, these women, it all just came alive around

00:33:29.980 --> 00:33:33.740
[Guest]: the time that I was reading these different women's books. So there's, I think, a lot

00:33:33.740 --> 00:33:38.340
[Guest]: of the feminist memoir literature, and the feminist literature around love, in particular

00:33:38.340 --> 00:33:44.700
[Guest]: bell hooks and so on and so forth. The other genre that I was reading, Amit, is economics.

00:33:44.700 --> 00:33:51.900
[Guest]: And here, I have to sort of say that the book still, I think I read Abhijit Banerjee's

00:33:51.900 --> 00:33:57.140
[Guest]: and Asadu Flow's Poor Economics. There was essentially just, you know, there was Exit

00:33:57.140 --> 00:34:02.100
[Guest]: Voice and Loyalty, which was one of my favourite books. But all of these books were very heavy

00:34:02.100 --> 00:34:06.700
[Guest]: handed in the way that they were structured, because they were still technical economists

00:34:06.700 --> 00:34:12.140
[Guest]: writing in that language. And it's a beautiful language. But I felt that I was reading those

00:34:12.140 --> 00:34:16.660
[Guest]: books, I was reading a lot of academic work on contract theory, on incentives, on taxes,

00:34:16.660 --> 00:34:21.700
[Guest]: as I mentioned, microeconomics of the household. So there's a book by her edited by Haddad

00:34:21.700 --> 00:34:26.220
[Guest]: and Hodinath, which is on intra household bargaining power. It's extremely droll and

00:34:26.220 --> 00:34:31.220
[Guest]: very technical, but I was reading it along with reading Kamala Das talking about her

00:34:31.220 --> 00:34:34.740
[Guest]: personal life. And what's interesting is you start to realise when you're reading these

00:34:34.740 --> 00:34:38.660
[Guest]: different genres together, I think somehow for me, they just came together because I

00:34:38.660 --> 00:34:42.180
[Guest]: realised and this is something I'm trying to do in the book is I'm trying to tell you

00:34:42.180 --> 00:34:47.340
[Guest]: that the way you feel in your family has something to do with the way you are treated in the

00:34:47.340 --> 00:34:50.420
[Guest]: labour market. And the way you're treated in the labour market has everything to do

00:34:50.420 --> 00:34:55.020
[Guest]: with the way your intimate relationships are treating you. And this was a link between

00:34:55.020 --> 00:34:59.380
[Guest]: these two genres of reading that hadn't really been made, I felt in Indian writing, and at

00:34:59.380 --> 00:35:04.260
[Guest]: least in nonfiction, I think it was, it was tried, but but I felt this was my book was

00:35:04.260 --> 00:35:12.020
[Guest]: just an effort to push that along. And I also at this point, the other book that really,

00:35:12.020 --> 00:35:16.980
[Guest]: I think, has shaped the way I think about writing is there's a book by Eric Fromm called

00:35:16.980 --> 00:35:23.420
[Guest]: The Art of Loving. And I think it's a must read for everyone, only because it's a slim

00:35:23.420 --> 00:35:29.460
[Guest]: book. He was a psychotherapist, but also a philosopher, social philosopher. And he essentially

00:35:29.460 --> 00:35:34.020
[Guest]: was telling us that love is not, you know, we now live in a world within, you know, sort

00:35:34.020 --> 00:35:38.380
[Guest]: of capitalist modes of production that we've all started to believe love is power, that

00:35:38.380 --> 00:35:42.460
[Guest]: if you have power over someone, then they love you, right? If you can get them to do

00:35:42.460 --> 00:35:46.500
[Guest]: something, if they can get them to pick you, if you can get them to have sex with you,

00:35:46.500 --> 00:35:50.740
[Guest]: there's this always getting and having, exactly, it's very transactional. And he, I think,

00:35:50.740 --> 00:35:56.500
[Guest]: you know, way before this became trendy to talk about recently on Twitter, he was telling

00:35:56.500 --> 00:36:02.540
[Guest]: us that love is an art, love requires, you have to sort of think of it not as a self

00:36:02.540 --> 00:36:08.300
[Guest]: maximising endeavour, but actually an act of generosity. And somehow, when I was reading

00:36:08.300 --> 00:36:11.780
[Guest]: all these, all these writers, and most of them, actually, I recognise many of them are

00:36:11.780 --> 00:36:16.860
[Guest]: not fiction writers per se, many of this is, it's memoir, it's philosophy, it's works of

00:36:16.860 --> 00:36:22.020
[Guest]: economics, some of it is somewhat academic. But I think these were the books and papers

00:36:22.020 --> 00:36:28.860
[Guest]: that really pushed me to think about writing about seemingly banal things, but with a fair

00:36:28.860 --> 00:36:33.380
[Guest]: amount of empathy. And then the last thing I will say is, I've been obsessed with this

00:36:33.380 --> 00:36:37.820
[Guest]: writer Nancy Mitford for the longest time, she just, if you if you pick up, you know,

00:36:37.820 --> 00:36:43.620
[Guest]: any amount of me trying to be sardonic, in the book, I think it owes tremendous debt

00:36:43.620 --> 00:36:49.780
[Guest]: to me reading her. And I think that The Pursuit of Love, you know, just all these books, because

00:36:49.780 --> 00:36:54.500
[Guest]: she was writing about these extremely wicked people, they were self indulgent, self involved,

00:36:54.500 --> 00:36:59.300
[Guest]: self obsessed. And yet you loved them, because she wrote about them in this deep sense of

00:36:59.300 --> 00:37:05.100
[Guest]: empathy. And she wrote about them in this extremely interesting stylistic way where

00:37:05.100 --> 00:37:10.140
[Guest]: you would recognize what they were doing was so narcissistic, and yet you understood them

00:37:10.140 --> 00:37:14.580
[Guest]: and you understood where they came from. And I think that really had a very significant

00:37:14.580 --> 00:37:17.860
[Guest]: impact on at least the way I think about writing women in particular, because I think she was

00:37:17.860 --> 00:37:22.780
[Guest]: able to do that much more with women per se, than men. And I think that this was sort of

00:37:22.780 --> 00:37:28.960
[Guest]: the broad sets of, you know, influences and thinking about just literature and writing.

00:37:28.960 --> 00:37:33.420
[Guest]: When it comes to Indian letters, I read, I read Hindi, I love Hindi literature, and,

00:37:33.420 --> 00:37:39.900
[Guest]: and Srilal Shukla to me is, I just, I think, because I was, I was, you know, when you have

00:37:39.900 --> 00:37:43.940
[Guest]: that choice, Amit, between Sanskrit and Hindi, I chosen to study Hindi, you know, when you

00:37:43.940 --> 00:37:49.540
[Guest]: have that before your board exams, you choose. And I'm so glad because I just, you know,

00:37:49.540 --> 00:37:53.900
[Guest]: Premchand, Srilal Shukla, these are, these are classics. And I realized it's again, tried

00:37:53.900 --> 00:37:58.220
[Guest]: to mention, but particularly Mr. Shukla, because, you know, to me, the way he was writing about

00:37:58.220 --> 00:38:04.060
[Guest]: government, the way he was writing about what the emerging middle class even in his time

00:38:04.060 --> 00:38:08.140
[Guest]: was, he wrote satire. And, you know, one of my favorite stories that he did is called

00:38:08.140 --> 00:38:12.620
[Guest]: Mummy G's Donkey. And I really think everyone should read it. I think Penguin has come out

00:38:12.620 --> 00:38:17.500
[Guest]: recently with, they've re translated and it's out. And essentially what he's trying, it's

00:38:17.500 --> 00:38:22.580
[Guest]: a story actually about someone's son, who they call a donkey. And the English translation

00:38:22.580 --> 00:38:28.340
[Guest]: is extremely fantastic as well. But the Hindi is just as, it's just superior, of course.

00:38:28.340 --> 00:38:35.220
[Guest]: And I think some combination of reading Hindi satire, along with these really biting feminists

00:38:35.220 --> 00:38:39.460
[Guest]: who were trying to write about people, I think that all of that finds its way, at least in

00:38:39.460 --> 00:38:41.620
[Guest]: the influences that you're seeing on the page.

00:38:41.620 --> 00:38:47.060
[Amit Varma]: Wow. And you mentioned bureaucracy, you know, there's this excellent little excerpt from

00:38:47.060 --> 00:38:51.860
[Amit Varma]: your chapter about the accountant, where, just quote that bit, you're talking to someone,

00:38:51.860 --> 00:38:55.220
[Amit Varma]: so you also quote her during this bit. So there's like, it's a quote within a quote.

00:38:55.220 --> 00:38:59.300
[Amit Varma]: Relentless record keeping must be part of a young bureaucrat's oeuvre. There is no meeting

00:38:59.300 --> 00:39:03.180
[Amit Varma]: if there are no minutes. There are no minutes if you don't take proper notes. Director Sahib

00:39:03.180 --> 00:39:07.460
[Amit Varma]: had emphasized while staring at her breasts. Eleven months at the Secretariat have taught

00:39:07.460 --> 00:39:11.860
[Amit Varma]: her three things, and she has taught me well. One, the Sarkar notes everything, especially

00:39:11.860 --> 00:39:16.180
[Amit Varma]: breasts. Two, to avoid trouble, it is best to file and forget. Three, the most valuable

00:39:16.180 --> 00:39:23.140
[Amit Varma]: meetings have reams of notes which say nothing. Yeah, you mentioned sardonic also. So to go

00:39:23.140 --> 00:39:27.540
[Amit Varma]: back to that other angle of it, that you're studying economics, right? And why did you

00:39:27.540 --> 00:39:33.380
[Amit Varma]: choose economics per se? Because it's not really a straight line from math to there

00:39:33.380 --> 00:39:38.180
[Amit Varma]: always necessary. And you know, was it kind of happenstance? Did you have a natural interest

00:39:38.180 --> 00:39:44.580
[Amit Varma]: on it? And where do we reach that stage where it feels interesting to you for the way it

00:39:44.580 --> 00:39:48.340
[Amit Varma]: applies to the real world? Like one of the criticisms you've had of economists in this

00:39:48.340 --> 00:39:53.780
[Amit Varma]: book as well is that, you know, economists like and that I lament also all the time on

00:39:53.780 --> 00:39:59.140
[Amit Varma]: my show is that economists sometimes, you know, lose sight of the real world in the

00:39:59.140 --> 00:40:02.980
[Amit Varma]: sense that they'll have their meta way and their frameworks of looking at everything.

00:40:02.980 --> 00:40:07.620
[Amit Varma]: And they'll have the dry data. And somehow it doesn't connect up with real people, you

00:40:07.620 --> 00:40:11.220
[Amit Varma]: know, and you the consequences of this can be pretty bad because you look at something

00:40:11.220 --> 00:40:15.300
[Amit Varma]: like demonetization. And it would just make me so angry that people are talking about

00:40:15.300 --> 00:40:18.980
[Amit Varma]: costs and benefits. And of course, there were no benefits. But the point is, even if there

00:40:18.980 --> 00:40:23.060
[Amit Varma]: were benefits, the cost went to one set of people, yes, the benefits went to another

00:40:23.060 --> 00:40:28.340
[Amit Varma]: set of people, there is a moral issue that the people who are suffering are real people,

00:40:28.340 --> 00:40:32.420
[Amit Varma]: you got to get down to that level of looking at the real people and thinking about it.

00:40:32.420 --> 00:40:37.220
[Amit Varma]: And many economists I know don't make that connection. They're trapped in the discipline.

00:40:37.220 --> 00:40:42.660
[Amit Varma]: Everything is abstract. It is not concrete. What you do so well in this book is that you

00:40:42.660 --> 00:40:47.460
[Amit Varma]: make it concrete. But when you started, was it like that? What was that journey like of

00:40:47.460 --> 00:40:53.140
[Guest]: like applying what you have learned to the world is a very frustrating journey, Amit,

00:40:53.140 --> 00:40:57.780
[Guest]: because the one community that I am a part of, I don't have a PhD in economics, but I'm

00:40:57.780 --> 00:41:02.180
[Guest]: trained in economics. And I'm what we call a jobbing economist. So you know, economics

00:41:02.180 --> 00:41:08.580
[Guest]: is is my job. I'm a part of the community. But I absolutely loathe what is happening

00:41:08.580 --> 00:41:14.660
[Guest]: in the way economists engage with the real world. And what I mean by that is even if

00:41:14.660 --> 00:41:18.820
[Guest]: you look right now at the COVID crisis, and I'll come to the book in a second. But if

00:41:18.820 --> 00:41:23.780
[Guest]: you look at the COVID crisis, it's fascinating to me that some of the best economists in

00:41:23.780 --> 00:41:28.420
[Guest]: the world who happen to be South Asian, Indian, have come out time and time and again and

00:41:28.420 --> 00:41:33.620
[Guest]: said we need a livelihood stimulus. And it needs to have an income support package. There

00:41:33.620 --> 00:41:38.580
[Guest]: are very sensible reasons to do it. And there are feasible solutions to do so. They have

00:41:38.580 --> 00:41:42.660
[Guest]: been saying this in op eds, they've written books, they've appeared on television shows,

00:41:42.660 --> 00:41:48.100
[Guest]: podcasts, you name it, and the best including Nobel laureates, ex you know, RBI governors,

00:41:48.100 --> 00:41:54.980
[Guest]: all of that. And yet, no one is listening. There is this complete paralysis and first

00:41:54.980 --> 00:42:02.420
[Guest]: just picking up what the community is saying. And I think part of the problem is that over

00:42:02.420 --> 00:42:05.860
[Guest]: the years, and I think you're absolutely right in picking up demonetization as an example

00:42:05.860 --> 00:42:09.300
[Guest]: of this, because to me, it is I fully agree with you, by the way, that to me, it is the

00:42:09.300 --> 00:42:12.900
[Amit Varma]: dividing line between whether I can even talk to you or not, to be perfectly honest.

00:42:12.900 --> 00:42:13.860
[Amit Varma]: It's a litmus test.

00:42:13.860 --> 00:42:23.060
[Guest]: And for me, when I look at the way, even during the farm laws, this really unemotional,

00:42:23.060 --> 00:42:28.260
[Guest]: really disengaged way, even most technocratic economists would talk about what's happening.

00:42:28.260 --> 00:42:32.500
[Guest]: Immediately, then you know that it's already just become something that, you know, experts

00:42:32.500 --> 00:42:36.260
[Guest]: in the world of economics are essentially now brought out to essentially fill in TV,

00:42:36.260 --> 00:42:40.420
[Guest]: you know, sort of infotainment gap. So there are debates and there's it's become that but

00:42:41.460 --> 00:42:45.140
[Guest]: the ability to actually translate some of the really important insights into the real

00:42:45.140 --> 00:42:48.900
[Guest]: world, I think is heavily compromised. And I think there are two reasons for that.

00:42:48.900 --> 00:42:52.580
[Guest]: And I think this speaks to my frustration, which has found its way in the book.

00:42:53.140 --> 00:42:58.340
[Guest]: I think one is Danny Roderick had a set of fabulous tweets, it's very rare that I say

00:42:58.340 --> 00:43:03.460
[Guest]: someone had fabulous tweets, but he actually had a set of fabulous tweets, where he basically,

00:43:03.460 --> 00:43:08.900
[Guest]: I'm going to say maybe two years ago, three years ago, he essentially said that academic

00:43:10.180 --> 00:43:15.460
[Guest]: economics, academia, academic economists, especially those trained in elite universities

00:43:15.460 --> 00:43:21.940
[Guest]: elite universities in the US in particular, tend to become socialized in what he calls,

00:43:21.940 --> 00:43:26.740
[Guest]: you know, this jerk quotient, he actually he called it the jerk quotient. And he said that

00:43:27.460 --> 00:43:33.620
[Guest]: you are taught to be always with your elbows out the notion of collaboration, understanding,

00:43:33.620 --> 00:43:39.940
[Guest]: let alone within your own peers, but with other disciplines, with civil society with activists

00:43:39.940 --> 00:43:45.700
[Guest]: is heavily frowned on, because you need to produce a paper, there is brutal competition in the way

00:43:45.700 --> 00:43:51.220
[Guest]: these departments work. And and what he was trying to say, very sensibly, I thought was that then

00:43:51.220 --> 00:43:55.780
[Guest]: those modes of competition and lack of collaboration just become imprinted on you.

00:43:55.780 --> 00:43:59.380
[Guest]: So even though you've left the department, and you may do very well for yourself,

00:43:59.940 --> 00:44:04.340
[Guest]: when you're engaging with what you and I would call the real world, you're constantly engaging

00:44:04.340 --> 00:44:07.940
[Guest]: with them with still that mindset. So people are only useful to you if they have a data set to

00:44:07.940 --> 00:44:12.420
[Guest]: give you, if they have grant funding to give you if you if they can help you with your brand or

00:44:12.420 --> 00:44:16.900
[Guest]: status. And they can ideally put you on some kind of panel with a politician or someone who probably

00:44:16.900 --> 00:44:22.740
[Guest]: help you run an RCT or something like that. There are very few economists and to me the gold

00:44:22.740 --> 00:44:27.140
[Guest]: standard in this is Professor Jean Drez. I don't think there is anyone who sort of embodies this,

00:44:27.140 --> 00:44:32.020
[Guest]: which is that he went out to say you need to keep all research people centric. And he is,

00:44:32.020 --> 00:44:36.340
[Guest]: you know, as much activist as economists. And you know, it's not that the rigor of what he's doing

00:44:36.340 --> 00:44:41.540
[Guest]: has ever been sacrificed. But the way it is practiced, I think is just remarkable. I don't

00:44:41.540 --> 00:44:45.540
[Guest]: think I would not be able to do it. I think the kinds of sacrifices in the way he lives his life,

00:44:45.540 --> 00:44:51.860
[Guest]: it would be very difficult for me to do so. But I really think that those are the kinds of stories

00:44:51.860 --> 00:44:57.460
[Guest]: about professional academia or and you need to talk about and and yet we don't see that right,

00:44:57.460 --> 00:45:02.260
[Guest]: like we see a very different kind of rock star worship, which is completely associated with

00:45:02.260 --> 00:45:07.620
[Guest]: status. So I think part of the problem is the real world is not interesting, because unless it

00:45:07.620 --> 00:45:13.380
[Guest]: accrues status in your professional ambitions, good luck, that's one. And the second I think,

00:45:13.380 --> 00:45:20.340
[Guest]: Amit, is that somewhere in all of this, and I think this is something I really believe has a lot

00:45:20.340 --> 00:45:23.940
[Guest]: to do with the caste system as well, because education is so heavily mediated through,

00:45:23.940 --> 00:45:28.500
[Guest]: you know, upper caste, it's very Brahminical pursuit, right? And I say this, bearing a Brahmin

00:45:28.500 --> 00:45:34.500
[Guest]: surname, and I'm acutely conscious of that. But I do think what's happened is that when men,

00:45:34.500 --> 00:45:39.220
[Guest]: particularly men, and I think I make fun of them quite a bit in the book, and I'm sure it'll be

00:45:39.220 --> 00:45:43.860
[Guest]: interesting seeing the reactions that come through. When men have these really posh degrees,

00:45:44.580 --> 00:45:47.780
[Guest]: it's almost you know, the character in a book said to me that, you know, you give a man

00:45:47.780 --> 00:45:53.780
[Guest]: a degree and a good job, and then he just thinks he's God. And there is this constant

00:45:53.780 --> 00:45:58.740
[Guest]: patronizing of other fields, of other ways of looking, of people who don't have the same

00:45:58.740 --> 00:46:04.100
[Guest]: prestige as you. And I, you know, I work in social protection, I work in social policy,

00:46:04.100 --> 00:46:09.620
[Guest]: and I can tell you, Amit, if you're a social worker now, or you're a non-techie, non-PhD,

00:46:09.620 --> 00:46:13.700
[Guest]: who happens to actually work every day in the program management of a livelihoods program,

00:46:13.700 --> 00:46:19.380
[Guest]: or the public distribution system, no one will take you seriously. This group will constantly,

00:46:19.380 --> 00:46:24.180
[Guest]: essentially, you will be expected to run through hoops of trying to gain legitimacy for your voice.

00:46:25.220 --> 00:46:31.220
[Guest]: And there is such caste pride in the profession, I think, particularly amongst its men. I actually

00:46:31.220 --> 00:46:35.140
[Guest]: think the women in the profession, it's a very small pool of women. I do think it operates

00:46:35.140 --> 00:46:39.140
[Guest]: differently because they're extremely aware of what it feels like to be a marginalized

00:46:39.140 --> 00:46:45.220
[Guest]: community within the profession. And I think my book was actually honestly a way for me to voice

00:46:45.220 --> 00:46:50.340
[Guest]: my frustration with this. There's this game that economists, young economists, are playing. I

00:46:50.340 --> 00:46:54.180
[Guest]: actually don't think established economists are not playing that game anymore, because it's very

00:46:54.180 --> 00:46:58.420
[Guest]: different for them. They operate in a very different reality. But young economists are

00:46:58.420 --> 00:47:02.820
[Guest]: constantly being trained to look at the real world only from the perspective of their research

00:47:02.820 --> 00:47:08.660
[Guest]: projects. And that's fine. But surely there has to be more than that. And to me, one of the things

00:47:08.660 --> 00:47:13.220
[Guest]: that we're risking in that is, I say this in the book, that the economy actually has a very rich

00:47:13.220 --> 00:47:20.420
[Guest]: ethical and emotional life. The economy is a feeling being. It is not just a bunch of soulless

00:47:20.420 --> 00:47:25.300
[Guest]: transactions. The stock market is soulless. The economy is not the stock market. The economy is

00:47:25.860 --> 00:47:30.980
[Guest]: all our relationships, you and me drinking our coffees here, our moods, our predilections.

00:47:30.980 --> 00:47:37.700
[Guest]: They find their way into the numbers on consumption, growth, jobs. And there is tremendous

00:47:37.700 --> 00:47:43.780
[Guest]: sentiment that the economy holds. And the best writing on the economy has always captured those

00:47:43.780 --> 00:47:50.980
[Guest]: sentiments, be it a Jean Drez, be it an Abhijit Banerjee. And I felt that I was trying to write

00:47:50.980 --> 00:47:54.740
[Guest]: a very different book. It was not, you know, as you say, this is a book on gender and society,

00:47:54.740 --> 00:48:01.460
[Guest]: and the economy shapes that. But I was very keen to tell a story about women's employment from the

00:48:01.460 --> 00:48:05.860
[Guest]: perspective of feeling. What did it feel like? Because we all know that graph, Amit, that graph

00:48:05.860 --> 00:48:13.700
[Guest]: from 2004 to 2017, sharp drop in female employment. And I think we've all grown inured to it, right?

00:48:13.700 --> 00:48:17.460
[Guest]: And a lot of people even said this about death statistics during the pandemic, sadly.

00:48:18.420 --> 00:48:25.220
[Guest]: And I wanted the reader to walk away from the book and realize the tears, the frustrations,

00:48:25.220 --> 00:48:30.500
[Guest]: the loneliness of that sharp drop, but that you see in that graph. And in fact, the book starts

00:48:30.500 --> 00:48:36.100
[Guest]: with that graph. It's right up on the first page. And at the end, I have a set of data annextures,

00:48:36.100 --> 00:48:40.580
[Guest]: and I quote someone, and actually, nobody knows who wrote, who said this, but they say it's Bertrand

00:48:40.580 --> 00:48:45.060
[Guest]: Russell, which is, it is the mark of a civilized man to look at a column of numbers and weep.

00:48:45.620 --> 00:48:49.700
[Guest]: And I think we should all be weeping when, my hope actually is that by the time you reach those

00:48:49.700 --> 00:48:56.180
[Guest]: numbers, you are weeping, because there is, it's brutal what's happening with that sharp drop in

00:48:56.180 --> 00:49:02.020
[Guest]: with that sharp drop in job rates for women. And yet economists, I mean, I think there's some

00:49:02.020 --> 00:49:06.340
[Guest]: economists who are obviously committed to it. But I don't think we are committed to telling the

00:49:06.340 --> 00:49:10.340
[Guest]: stories behind the statistics. And I think if you understand the statistics well enough, then only

00:49:10.340 --> 00:49:13.940
[Guest]: will you be able to tell those stories well, and I was privileged to at least have that kind of

00:49:13.940 --> 00:49:19.140
[Guest]: background to be able to mirror the two together and marry them. And the book is essentially an

00:49:19.140 --> 00:49:25.700
[Guest]: effort in that direction. But I will say one thing that I also think that this is a larger problem

00:49:25.700 --> 00:49:31.700
[Guest]: when you start to you know, the book is also is is a hat tip to the female gaze. And I like to

00:49:31.700 --> 00:49:36.740
[Guest]: believe it's actually without sounding too lofty and full of myself, maybe I will, but I think it's

00:49:36.740 --> 00:49:41.060
[Guest]: the it's the female gaze towards the economy. Because if women start to look at the economy,

00:49:41.700 --> 00:49:46.020
[Guest]: I was very curious, what does that look like? And in fact, I think the stories over the 15 years

00:49:46.020 --> 00:49:50.660
[Guest]: that I followed all these women, they're actually telling me what when they look at the economy,

00:49:50.660 --> 00:49:55.220
[Guest]: what are they seeing, they're seeing the home because the home remains their principal productive

00:49:55.220 --> 00:50:00.340
[Guest]: workplace. It is not the factories and fields. And yet, when you look at the conversation amongst

00:50:00.340 --> 00:50:04.980
[Guest]: technocrats and policymakers, the home is yet to be acknowledged as a productive workplace,

00:50:04.980 --> 00:50:10.740
[Guest]: because if it were then conversations and policy around tenure security around domestic

00:50:10.740 --> 00:50:16.260
[Guest]: infrastructure around water would be radically different around reproductive health as well.

00:50:16.900 --> 00:50:20.980
[Guest]: And we don't spend enough in these areas and the quality of spending remains poor because

00:50:20.980 --> 00:50:25.780
[Guest]: there's a very different gaze. I think the conversation on the economy is still dominated,

00:50:25.780 --> 00:50:29.620
[Guest]: I won't say by men, but I think by masculine gaze, because then many of us who even women

00:50:29.620 --> 00:50:34.420
[Guest]: who have been trained in a way of thinking, you inherit that kind of technical way of thinking,

00:50:34.980 --> 00:50:39.620
[Guest]: without recognizing that the home actually is the principal workplace for half the population.

00:50:40.260 --> 00:50:45.140
[Guest]: And we don't talk about that. The second thing you realize when women start to look at the economy

00:50:45.140 --> 00:50:52.260
[Guest]: is that notions of love of care of social relationships, become fulcrums and levers

00:50:52.260 --> 00:50:57.300
[Guest]: of any kind of change in the economy. That's actually where incentives and taxes come into

00:50:57.300 --> 00:51:01.300
[Guest]: play. And in the book, I give people a flavor drawing on work of Sendhil Mullainathan,

00:51:01.300 --> 00:51:04.900
[Guest]: because he has this wonderful framework, he calls it a hidden tax. And he says that

00:51:04.900 --> 00:51:09.220
[Guest]: anytime people start to do things that social scripts really don't want them to do,

00:51:09.780 --> 00:51:13.540
[Guest]: interpersonally, we start taxing people making them feel unloved. And in the book,

00:51:13.540 --> 00:51:17.300
[Guest]: the stories are women who want to just earn their own money, and they want to spend it,

00:51:17.300 --> 00:51:22.820
[Guest]: it sounds really simple. It's incredibly complex thing to do. I think the book gives you a flavor

00:51:22.820 --> 00:51:27.780
[Guest]: of that. And they also happen to have a favorite actor, and it's their own way of asserting their

00:51:27.780 --> 00:51:34.740
[Guest]: selfhood. And something as simple as that suddenly lovers, boyfriends, fathers, mothers,

00:51:35.300 --> 00:51:40.500
[Guest]: in laws, their own friends. This is not a male female issue. It's cross gender.

00:51:40.500 --> 00:51:45.300
[Guest]: People start taxing these women for Oh, how dare you want to stand on your own two feet? How dare

00:51:45.300 --> 00:51:51.380
[Guest]: you want to do things that are moving away from what is conformist and it makes us comfortable,

00:51:51.380 --> 00:51:56.820
[Guest]: you know, you as a mother or you as just a caregiver. And I realized that the female

00:51:56.820 --> 00:52:02.580
[Guest]: gaze of the economy would focus on those things. Because many of the women in the book will say

00:52:02.580 --> 00:52:07.540
[Guest]: this, and I think you've read it, but they will say that we don't work. Because we know if we

00:52:07.540 --> 00:52:15.060
[Guest]: start to work more number of hours, our loved ones will feel neglected. And so love as a lever

00:52:15.060 --> 00:52:20.260
[Guest]: in the way women are participating in the economy becomes very clear when you start to ask the

00:52:20.260 --> 00:52:25.380
[Guest]: questions in a different way. And I don't think that's currently the way economists are thinking

00:52:25.380 --> 00:52:29.940
[Guest]: about the economy. And I think it's shifting. I think as more as feminist economics as a field

00:52:29.940 --> 00:52:35.540
[Guest]: starts to grow, I think things will change. And the notion of obviously, I think there's been a

00:52:35.540 --> 00:52:42.980
[Guest]: lot of lip service paid to valuing unpaid care work. And we know that it's a huge contribution

00:52:42.980 --> 00:52:46.820
[Guest]: to the economy, the workforce would not be sustained. And I say this in the book that

00:52:46.820 --> 00:52:53.220
[Guest]: the economy, the surface of it is a bunch of men trading money. But behind that is the invisible

00:52:53.220 --> 00:52:59.220
[Guest]: love and care that women provide that allows for these men to trade labor and money. And right now

00:52:59.220 --> 00:53:06.580
[Guest]: the economy works in such a way that women earn love and men earn money. And the earning money

00:53:06.580 --> 00:53:10.740
[Guest]: is actually much easier than earning love. And the labor of what women are doing in the economy

00:53:10.740 --> 00:53:15.860
[Guest]: is just continues to be disregarded. I don't know, there are several solutions about what that could

00:53:15.860 --> 00:53:21.140
[Guest]: look like an economy that actually values care. Fiscally, it could be very challenging. But I

00:53:21.140 --> 00:53:26.020
[Guest]: think those are the questions to ask, especially as we emerge out of a pandemic, when we know that

00:53:26.020 --> 00:53:30.500
[Guest]: we know that care has been absolutely central to the way we've emerged out of the pandemic,

00:53:30.500 --> 00:53:36.180
[Guest]: be it nursing doctors, be it you know, women telling kids to wash their hands or you know,

00:53:36.180 --> 00:53:43.620
[Guest]: wear a mask. All of that requires care. And if women are doing the giant share of care,

00:53:43.620 --> 00:53:48.740
[Guest]: and India still continues to be bottom five when it comes to the share of men supporting care work

00:53:48.740 --> 00:53:54.500
[Guest]: in the world. Surely, then a female gaze to the economy is a helpful thing to at least ask

00:53:54.500 --> 00:54:00.420
[Guest]: us to think about policy very differently. And I am yet to see that shift happening. I think

00:54:00.420 --> 00:54:05.300
[Guest]: it's happening in spaces and in some different initiatives, and I'm hopeful. But the book

00:54:05.300 --> 00:54:09.940
[Guest]: essentially tries to tell you well, what what happens when women start to look at the economy?

00:54:09.940 --> 00:54:15.060
[Guest]: And what does that look like? And what does that feel like? And I think the feel is the emphasis

00:54:15.060 --> 00:54:19.300
[Amit Varma]: in the book for me. Yeah, you know, I mean, there are about 40 things in what you just said,

00:54:19.300 --> 00:54:23.860
[Amit Varma]: which I want to double click on, which I will duly do in the course of this nine hour conversation.

00:54:23.860 --> 00:54:28.900
[Amit Varma]: So I hope you've got your energy bars with you. But you know, my mind goes back to that cliched

00:54:28.900 --> 00:54:32.740
[Amit Varma]: parable of the blind man and the elephant. Yeah. And all these blind men are feeling different

00:54:32.740 --> 00:54:36.420
[Amit Varma]: parts of the elephant seeing different things. And I think society is a bit like that. It's the

00:54:36.420 --> 00:54:41.460
[Amit Varma]: elephant. And an economist will look at one aspect of it. And a social scientist or a social worker

00:54:41.460 --> 00:54:45.940
[Amit Varma]: will look at another aspect of it. A feminist will look at one aspect of it. And what I really

00:54:45.940 --> 00:54:51.140
[Amit Varma]: liked about your book is that you've got multiple aspects to bear on them. So we can see some of the

00:54:51.140 --> 00:54:56.100
[Amit Varma]: connections, some of those dots become clearer. I mean, what is really the economy? It's a subset

00:54:56.100 --> 00:55:01.060
[Amit Varma]: of society. It's the sum total of the voluntary transactions between people, right? And that's

00:55:01.060 --> 00:55:05.300
[Amit Varma]: one way in which you can see what's happening in society. And the other way, which is more

00:55:05.300 --> 00:55:11.140
[Amit Varma]: nebulous and harder to put down in numbers is all of these interpersonal relationships, these social

00:55:11.140 --> 00:55:15.780
[Amit Varma]: structures, how some of them are so oppressive, how people deal with those oppressions, the

00:55:15.780 --> 00:55:20.260
[Amit Varma]: interior lives of the people who do that. And that's one thing I really liked about the book

00:55:20.260 --> 00:55:25.140
[Amit Varma]: that it brings these two kind of together. And I found your quote about economists from the book,

00:55:25.140 --> 00:55:30.420
[Amit Varma]: and I'm going to read it out because I liked so much of your book for the writing. It's delightful.

00:55:30.420 --> 00:55:35.060
[Amit Varma]: Thank you. Often when we think of the economy, we think of it as some intimidating notion

00:55:35.060 --> 00:55:40.740
[Amit Varma]: accessible only to a group of stuffy technocrats and Davos attendees. So precious that it can only

00:55:40.740 --> 00:55:46.500
[Amit Varma]: be discussed and understood by finance dude bros, stock market analysts, and know it all economists.

00:55:46.500 --> 00:55:51.060
[Amit Varma]: However, the best economists know that the economy is nothing but our modes and relationships,

00:55:51.060 --> 00:55:57.060
[Amit Varma]: which define who produces and transacts what the economy has a rich emotional and ethical life.

00:55:57.060 --> 00:56:01.860
[Amit Varma]: The economy is made up of the loves and losses of the women I encountered, their fandom and

00:56:01.860 --> 00:56:07.220
[Amit Varma]: their fantasies, a set of feelings we must be able to conjure up when we look at bland data

00:56:07.220 --> 00:56:13.620
[Amit Varma]: sheets on jobs, consumption sales, or box office collections. Those statistics represent an ocean

00:56:13.620 --> 00:56:19.620
[Amit Varma]: of sentiment. Stop good. Beautifully said. And I love that quote, which you said is allegedly

00:56:19.620 --> 00:56:24.180
[Amit Varma]: by Bertrand Russell. And you know, I feel like saying numbers are people too. But then some

00:56:24.180 --> 00:56:28.180
[Amit Varma]: people in a certain party in India would no doubt create the hashtag not all numbers.

00:56:31.380 --> 00:56:37.060
[Amit Varma]: There's a slippery slope there. It's a slippery slope. Yeah. I also want to talk a bit about

00:56:37.060 --> 00:56:42.340
[Amit Varma]: academia. Yeah, I think I put out a tweet a couple of days back, we are recording this on

00:56:42.340 --> 00:56:48.340
[Amit Varma]: December 17, though, it'll probably come out a long time after this. But I put out a tweet

00:56:48.340 --> 00:56:53.220
[Amit Varma]: talking about how academia is a big circle jerk. And I've had conversations with my good friend,

00:56:53.220 --> 00:56:58.180
[Amit Varma]: the economist Ajay Shah, who's also been on the show. And one of his laments is that so few

00:56:58.180 --> 00:57:02.660
[Amit Varma]: economists engage with the real world in the manner in which he tries to do or you have done.

00:57:03.540 --> 00:57:09.540
[Amit Varma]: And that, you know, the academy game has its own incentives, its own constraints, you know,

00:57:09.540 --> 00:57:14.500
[Amit Varma]: you get into a particular department somewhere, there'll be a dominant ideology, you know,

00:57:14.500 --> 00:57:18.980
[Amit Varma]: there'll be a certain set of research projects you can do and others that you better not venture

00:57:18.980 --> 00:57:24.260
[Amit Varma]: into. And all of these constraints drive you down particular directions. And it just seems to be

00:57:24.260 --> 00:57:30.340
[Amit Varma]: completely separate from the way the world works. And, and I'm just thinking aloud here, one of the

00:57:30.340 --> 00:57:36.580
[Amit Varma]: things I've noticed in the creator economy, which I've thought a lot about and experienced is that

00:57:36.580 --> 00:57:42.820
[Amit Varma]: gatekeepers are becoming irrelevant in the sense that in the 1990s, if I wanted to write something,

00:57:42.820 --> 00:57:47.460
[Amit Varma]: means of production are not not available to me, I have to go to gatekeepers, I want to make a

00:57:47.460 --> 00:57:53.220
[Amit Varma]: movie, I want to record a song, whatever I want to do, I need to go to gatekeepers. Today, over a

00:57:53.220 --> 00:57:59.140
[Amit Varma]: period of time, it's we've evolved to a space where I think gatekeepers have are becoming irrelevant

00:57:59.140 --> 00:58:04.420
[Amit Varma]: really fast for most creators already have, like if I was to pitch the show to some established

00:58:04.420 --> 00:58:09.460
[Amit Varma]: company and say, I'll have four hour conversations with feminist economists, you know, I'd be laughed

00:58:09.460 --> 00:58:13.460
[Amit Varma]: out of the room. Yeah, but it's it's happening, you know, in one of my earlier episodes, which

00:58:13.460 --> 00:58:17.460
[Amit Varma]: is not released yet, but will be released before this one. My good friend, Chuck Gopal told me

00:58:17.460 --> 00:58:23.380
[Amit Varma]: about this lady on Instagram called Miss Excel. And she's great at Excel. And she loves dancing

00:58:23.380 --> 00:58:29.220
[Amit Varma]: and she loves EDM. So the she does these Instagram videos, where you have this window on top where

00:58:29.220 --> 00:58:34.260
[Amit Varma]: there's an Excel sheet. And there are instructions there on how to do whatever. And she's dancing

00:58:34.260 --> 00:58:41.220
[Amit Varma]: to EDM. Wow. Now, and she makes I think $100,000 a day, because she sells courses on how to teach

00:58:41.220 --> 00:58:46.580
[Amit Varma]: Excel. She is the most successful Excel teacher in the world. Yeah, right. And no gatekeeper would

00:58:46.580 --> 00:58:51.860
[Amit Varma]: allow that. Yeah. But within the context of the creator economy, she actually fits what I would

00:58:51.860 --> 00:58:57.620
[Amit Varma]: say the formula is, which to me is number one, be authentic to yourself. And she knows Excel,

00:58:57.620 --> 00:59:02.500
[Amit Varma]: and she loves dancing and EDM. Number two, be relatable. And that's it's relatable, because

00:59:02.500 --> 00:59:08.340
[Amit Varma]: everyone wants to bet so many people want to learn Excel. And number three, create that intimate

00:59:08.340 --> 00:59:14.340
[Amit Varma]: space where you know, your reader feels that they know you, which also she does. Now, if I

00:59:14.340 --> 00:59:20.500
[Amit Varma]: transpose that to the context of say something like economics, which people think, okay, it's a

00:59:20.500 --> 00:59:27.140
[Amit Varma]: dry field. It is an academic field. Sometimes there is a correlation between what happens there

00:59:27.140 --> 00:59:32.260
[Amit Varma]: and what happens in the real world. But it's like a separate thing, right? And at the same time,

00:59:32.260 --> 00:59:37.140
[Amit Varma]: we realized that there is a hunger among people to figure the world out. Yes, there's no question

00:59:37.140 --> 00:59:41.540
[Amit Varma]: about this. There's a hunger among people who want to figure the world out, and no one speaking to

00:59:41.540 --> 00:59:47.060
[Amit Varma]: them. Most academics are in their little circle jerk with their abstruse jargon, yes, with their

00:59:47.060 --> 00:59:53.060
[Amit Varma]: predetermined mindsets, and no one speaking to them. And therefore, it seems that over time,

00:59:53.060 --> 00:59:58.420
[Amit Varma]: do you think it is a possibility that even from within this discipline, the gatekeepers can become

00:59:58.420 --> 01:00:06.900
[Amit Varma]: irrelevant, and they can be a way for economists to exist outside of this? Amit, in fact, I think

01:00:06.900 --> 01:00:12.980
[Guest]: it's happening. So there are organizations like for example, Bahujan Economics. And, you know,

01:00:12.980 --> 01:00:18.100
[Guest]: what they are doing is it's a collective of scholars who want to look at it's the Dalit

01:00:18.100 --> 01:00:23.620
[Guest]: gaze to the economy. And it's really exciting some of the things that at least I've read,

01:00:23.620 --> 01:00:28.500
[Guest]: and I'm really curious to learn more about what they're doing. Look at the right to food in

01:00:28.500 --> 01:00:33.620
[Guest]: particular as a movement. And I think the the academic work that so many of the economists

01:00:33.620 --> 01:00:38.100
[Guest]: connected with right to food have done. And honestly, Amit, the reason we have a public

01:00:38.100 --> 01:00:43.300
[Guest]: distribution system that was able to provide food grains to 800 million people during the crisis is

01:00:43.300 --> 01:00:49.460
[Guest]: because of the sustained work of economists who are involved in that fight in making food security

01:00:49.460 --> 01:00:55.700
[Guest]: universal. So I think there are some phenomenal and really good examples of that. And then there

01:00:55.700 --> 01:01:00.660
[Guest]: are limits to that, because now the same movements are trying to contend with how do you use technology

01:01:00.660 --> 01:01:06.500
[Guest]: better? And how do you study the use of technology better as as economists on the ground? I think

01:01:06.500 --> 01:01:10.900
[Guest]: there are two things to me that really need to change. And again, here, I will go back to

01:01:10.900 --> 01:01:15.220
[Guest]: traditional good old economics, which is, you know, incentives and compensation, which is that

01:01:15.220 --> 01:01:23.220
[Guest]: currently, if you look at, you know, I've done a bunch of surveys during the crisis, even before

01:01:24.260 --> 01:01:29.300
[Guest]: I work for the World Bank, and often we need to do real time data collection to understand I work

01:01:29.300 --> 01:01:34.740
[Guest]: on safety nets and social insurance programs, we need to run surveys to understand who's getting

01:01:34.740 --> 01:01:40.660
[Guest]: what are people even receiving benefits. We run these surveys, the data sits and we use it for

01:01:40.660 --> 01:01:45.300
[Guest]: our dialogue with state governments or the national government or different stakeholders.

01:01:46.260 --> 01:01:50.340
[Guest]: But then it just sits there. And at least the one thing I'm really pleased is that the World Bank

01:01:50.340 --> 01:01:53.860
[Guest]: as an organisation has a policy that you're supposed to open up the data, you're supposed

01:01:53.860 --> 01:01:57.940
[Guest]: to make it available. And so other researchers and scholars can use it in whichever way they'd like.

01:01:58.980 --> 01:02:07.860
[Guest]: And I think that as access to information and data starts to become more democratic,

01:02:07.860 --> 01:02:13.860
[Guest]: because one of the biggest hurdles in doing what we would call real world engaged economics or

01:02:13.860 --> 01:02:20.900
[Guest]: ground up economics in a way, is that it's really costly to collect data, it's costly to do some of

01:02:20.900 --> 01:02:24.420
[Guest]: the things that you would want to do. I mean, and especially because you want to do them in an

01:02:24.420 --> 01:02:29.540
[Guest]: ethical, good, rigorous way where you're protecting the people who are collecting the information as

01:02:29.540 --> 01:02:36.100
[Guest]: well. And that's an extremely expensive enterprise. And right now, I'm sure you notice that Professor

01:02:36.100 --> 01:02:39.700
[Guest]: Drez is, you know, there have been lots of articles back and forth between him and his

01:02:39.700 --> 01:02:45.140
[Guest]: colleagues in CMIE about access to CMIE data as well, right? Because it is extremely expensive

01:02:45.140 --> 01:02:48.580
[Guest]: organisations like the World Bank can access it, and there are others who can, but then there are

01:02:48.580 --> 01:02:54.260
[Guest]: lots of young students who might be in small towns or villages who may be able to make some

01:02:54.260 --> 01:03:00.340
[Guest]: remarkable, make that data sing in a way, but they currently don't fully have access. So I think the

01:03:00.340 --> 01:03:06.340
[Guest]: first thing we start to need to do is the costs of access to just fundamental data, which will be

01:03:06.340 --> 01:03:11.380
[Guest]: useful to create some of this rich information just needs to be much more democratic. And in

01:03:11.380 --> 01:03:16.100
[Guest]: going back to your creator economy parallel, one of the beautiful things about the creator economy

01:03:16.100 --> 01:03:19.780
[Guest]: is that some of the gatekeeping has gone because access to data has become an access to the

01:03:19.780 --> 01:03:24.580
[Guest]: internet as well has become far more democratic, and it's just made platforms much more open.

01:03:24.580 --> 01:03:28.740
[Guest]: I think we really need to think about things like that when it comes to data and economics. I think

01:03:28.740 --> 01:03:35.140
[Guest]: there needs to be a big shift there. So that's one. I think the second is, if you look at again,

01:03:35.140 --> 01:03:41.140
[Guest]: the surveys we run and what we write, often, and you're absolutely right, it's like we live in this

01:03:41.140 --> 01:03:46.500
[Guest]: bubble where many of us write op-eds and, you know, an occasional op-ed in the Indian Express,

01:03:46.500 --> 01:03:52.180
[Guest]: there'll be an article in EPW, but it's not really considered academic prestige, right?

01:03:52.180 --> 01:03:58.180
[Guest]: And I remember once I was listening to Professor Raghuram Rajan at, I think it was a seminar at

01:03:58.180 --> 01:04:03.380
[Guest]: the Kennedy School, he'd come in to talk to somebody and he said that the problem is that

01:04:04.900 --> 01:04:10.420
[Guest]: economics departments in academia will socialize you into believing that anything other than these,

01:04:10.420 --> 01:04:15.060
[Guest]: you know, top peer-reviewed journals is just, that's just meaningless. It's just, you know,

01:04:15.060 --> 01:04:20.100
[Guest]: trash in a way. Well, not even trash, but sweet trash, you know, somewhat helpful, but not,

01:04:20.100 --> 01:04:23.940
[Guest]: you know, and I think he had a very clever way he put it, which I've forgotten, but it was

01:04:23.940 --> 01:04:28.500
[Guest]: quite interesting. And even he was saying that that needs to start to change because, in fact,

01:04:28.500 --> 01:04:32.900
[Guest]: if you look at a lot of macroeconomic work, it's, in fact, chief economists of banks that,

01:04:32.900 --> 01:04:38.740
[Guest]: who are producing some really fascinating analysis. It may not be academically valid,

01:04:38.740 --> 01:04:44.900
[Guest]: it may not have legitimacy of that kind in academia, but it is extremely useful information.

01:04:44.900 --> 01:04:51.140
[Guest]: And I think trying to create communities that reward value, recognize that work,

01:04:51.140 --> 01:04:55.140
[Guest]: the quality of that work, it may have very different metrics of assessment.

01:04:56.020 --> 01:05:00.820
[Guest]: I think that really needs to be amplified far more so that you create an economy of

01:05:00.820 --> 01:05:04.980
[Guest]: prestige of its own, right? Because people do want to feel meaningful. I think human beings,

01:05:04.980 --> 01:05:08.980
[Guest]: it's just not possible for us not to want to put something out there and not feel that

01:05:08.980 --> 01:05:12.660
[Guest]: it's being recognized and it's being valued. And there is a competition inherently,

01:05:12.660 --> 01:05:15.780
[Guest]: which is also healthy in a way amongst people that will just play itself out.

01:05:15.780 --> 01:05:21.860
[Guest]: But just like, as you mentioned, Miss Excel, I think, just as what you just described,

01:05:22.500 --> 01:05:27.460
[Guest]: you know, now there is an audience and a platform that recognizes and rewards and appreciates that

01:05:27.460 --> 01:05:35.460
[Guest]: kind of effort. I'm yet to see that happen in more grounded economic writing or surveys,

01:05:35.460 --> 01:05:40.580
[Guest]: analysis. I think there's some stuff that what tends to happen is even there's a crisis,

01:05:40.580 --> 01:05:44.340
[Guest]: as we saw with the pandemic, there was such useful stuff that was coming out from different,

01:05:44.340 --> 01:05:48.980
[Guest]: typically civil society organizations who just somehow, despite all the perils of the pandemic,

01:05:48.980 --> 01:05:53.940
[Guest]: just were able to collect data from migrant workers, from others. And then it's right now,

01:05:53.940 --> 01:05:57.540
[Guest]: for example, Azeem Premji University now maintains an entire database where they're

01:05:57.540 --> 01:06:05.060
[Guest]: trying to collate all these papers and all the data. But, you know, why not create a space where,

01:06:05.060 --> 01:06:09.860
[Guest]: you know, papers of that kind essentially can be published, can be rewarded, can be discussed.

01:06:09.860 --> 01:06:14.100
[Guest]: Often people who are participating in this kind of knowledge production, and it is economics,

01:06:14.100 --> 01:06:18.500
[Guest]: will never be invited to, you know, the Fashion Week for Policy Economists, right? Which is all

01:06:18.500 --> 01:06:22.900
[Guest]: these events that you have in Delhi, curated typically by economists who live abroad and

01:06:22.900 --> 01:06:27.060
[Guest]: they come here. And I think we need to start to think about creating spaces like that,

01:06:27.060 --> 01:06:30.660
[Guest]: that are very different. It could be done through local think tanks. And I think

01:06:30.660 --> 01:06:37.220
[Guest]: there has to be a way to value it. And I think if the two start to happen, we democratize access

01:06:37.220 --> 01:06:42.180
[Guest]: to data, and incredibly so, not just saying that there's a portal and you can go access the portal,

01:06:42.180 --> 01:06:45.460
[Guest]: but doing it in a way which actually makes it easier for people to access through local

01:06:45.460 --> 01:06:51.140
[Guest]: organizations, online, so on and so forth. And the second is if we start to create incentives

01:06:51.140 --> 01:06:56.580
[Guest]: of a very different recognition, a very different kind of work, and come up with a language and a

01:06:56.580 --> 01:07:01.700
[Guest]: set of codes for that, I think that'll be really helpful as we move forward. And the third, Amit,

01:07:01.700 --> 01:07:08.340
[Guest]: I will say this, is that, and I think my book is one little meagre attempt at this, I hate a

01:07:08.340 --> 01:07:14.500
[Guest]: certain kind of economics writing, which assumes that the government and people with power are the

01:07:14.500 --> 01:07:20.660
[Guest]: only audience that matters, right? So there's a kind of stuffy, terrible writing, just terrible,

01:07:21.540 --> 01:07:27.780
[Guest]: which I just loathe where you have all these extremely powerful men, it's usually always men

01:07:27.780 --> 01:07:31.540
[Guest]: who will write these books saying the government should do this and the government should do that

01:07:31.540 --> 01:07:35.220
[Guest]: and it's like a list of prescriptions. And of course, the government is not listening,

01:07:35.220 --> 01:07:38.900
[Guest]: the government is going to do what it is feasible politically and administratively to do.

01:07:39.940 --> 01:07:48.100
[Guest]: And I think economists also need to stop writing for power. Why don't we write to explain the world

01:07:48.100 --> 01:07:52.180
[Guest]: to ourselves and to others, to people we know? And I think it is happening. In fact, people like you

01:07:52.180 --> 01:07:57.300
[Guest]: and even a lot of activists are trying, and Mr. Shah, Professor Shah, you mentioned, so many people

01:07:57.300 --> 01:08:02.660
[Guest]: are trying to now write in a way where they're not really interested whether the government or

01:08:02.660 --> 01:08:08.100
[Guest]: structures of power are listening. It's more for the general public or it could actually just be

01:08:08.100 --> 01:08:11.540
[Guest]: for communities. This idea of the Bahujan economics group is really interesting to me

01:08:12.900 --> 01:08:17.220
[Guest]: because suddenly the audience, it's not just for government, it's actually to understand our own

01:08:17.220 --> 01:08:20.980
[Guest]: communities better. And if you look at the feminist economics movement, I mean, it's very

01:08:20.980 --> 01:08:27.540
[Guest]: similar. The interest is not in just getting governments to see the value in seeing this

01:08:27.540 --> 01:08:32.740
[Guest]: research is viable or legitimate and actionable. They are not in the business of giving advice to

01:08:32.740 --> 01:08:37.460
[Guest]: prime ministers and chief ministers. They are in the business of completely changing the way we

01:08:37.460 --> 01:08:41.620
[Guest]: think about the world. And that they realize is not just something powerful people can do.

01:08:41.620 --> 01:08:47.540
[Guest]: They're interested in students and communities and the general public. And I think the more we

01:08:47.540 --> 01:08:51.620
[Guest]: have that, and that will require some people to take risks in their careers. And I think some

01:08:51.620 --> 01:08:58.020
[Guest]: people have. And I think the more we see that happening, I'll be more hopeful of the way

01:08:58.020 --> 01:09:03.700
[Guest]: economics as a profession is moving. And yeah, so I'm hopeful. But I think these different things

01:09:03.700 --> 01:09:07.620
[Guest]: need to happen. And we need to stop kowtowing to just an audience of power. I think there's a

01:09:07.620 --> 01:09:12.820
[Guest]: larger audience out there. And then perhaps the structures of power can start to move. But

01:09:12.820 --> 01:09:16.580
[Amit Varma]: I think it's a different game then. Yeah, I'll double down, not double click,

01:09:16.580 --> 01:09:20.740
[Amit Varma]: but double down on a couple of the things you said, because I feel so strongly about them as well.

01:09:20.740 --> 01:09:24.980
[Amit Varma]: And one of them is democratic access to data. Like one of my best books I've read in the last

01:09:24.980 --> 01:09:29.380
[Amit Varma]: few years is a book called Super Forecasting by Philip Tetlock. And where, you know, one of the

01:09:29.380 --> 01:09:35.460
[Amit Varma]: things he points out is how often experts get predictions wrong, where there is so much data

01:09:35.460 --> 01:09:40.340
[Amit Varma]: that shows that all these experts with their fancy degrees and their Ivy League school

01:09:40.340 --> 01:09:44.420
[Amit Varma]: professorships, they'll go on TV, they'll make predictions, they'll be wrong. While it is

01:09:44.420 --> 01:09:48.740
[Amit Varma]: actually, you know, there are forecasting competitions and the kind of people who really

01:09:48.740 --> 01:09:54.500
[Amit Varma]: do well in them are just self taught people who are skeptical about everything and open to changing

01:09:54.500 --> 01:10:00.260
[Amit Varma]: their mind. And my sense is that, you know, if every data set is available to everyone,

01:10:00.260 --> 01:10:05.300
[Amit Varma]: then somebody from God knows where without a shred of privilege, yes, can just access it

01:10:05.300 --> 01:10:09.940
[Amit Varma]: on the internet, apply her own brain. And as you said, so well make the data sing,

01:10:09.940 --> 01:10:13.460
[Amit Varma]: see something that others can't see, because they're coming at it differently.

01:10:13.460 --> 01:10:15.940
[Amit Varma]: While the whole academic world will come at it from one lens.

01:10:15.940 --> 01:10:19.940
[Guest]: Exactly. And you know, Amit, I think the reason that's so powerful is because

01:10:20.980 --> 01:10:26.660
[Guest]: I once foolishly, I had gone to a seminar, because you know, I'm, of course, I'm such a nerd,

01:10:26.660 --> 01:10:30.260
[Guest]: and I'm obsessed with economists. So I went to a seminar that Amartya Sen was doing. This is,

01:10:30.260 --> 01:10:35.780
[Guest]: I think the last time he was probably in Delhi. And it was at the Habitat Center, and you know,

01:10:35.780 --> 01:10:39.940
[Guest]: large audience, and then it was opened up to questions. Sharmila Tagore was there,

01:10:39.940 --> 01:10:44.500
[Guest]: which is very exciting for me. It was like economics meets Bollywood. So it's so exciting.

01:10:44.500 --> 01:10:47.700
[Amit Varma]: She's not even Bollywood, Shuttujit Rai, that's where she started.

01:10:47.700 --> 01:10:50.500
[Guest]: I also think of her as Kashmiri Kali and all of that.

01:10:50.500 --> 01:10:51.700
[Guest]: She's too good for Bollywood.

01:10:51.700 --> 01:10:58.900
[Guest]: No, Amit, this is your arrogance coming in. But she's both, but she's marvellous. But what I was

01:10:58.900 --> 01:11:05.460
[Guest]: going to say is that, so I remember I asked him, and I asked him, I said, do you think that RCTs

01:11:05.460 --> 01:11:12.340
[Guest]: have just changed the incentive for students in academic economics? And you know, he said yes,

01:11:12.340 --> 01:11:17.380
[Guest]: because now, and that was RCTs a while ago. So that was almost, it must be five, seven years ago,

01:11:17.380 --> 01:11:23.140
[Guest]: longer than that. And now, you know, there are different trends. And that's fine. I mean,

01:11:23.140 --> 01:11:27.700
[Guest]: I don't want anyone listening to us to think that, I certainly don't think that there's anything

01:11:27.700 --> 01:11:33.220
[Guest]: wrong with being on trend within academia, because there might be very useful reasons why, you know,

01:11:33.220 --> 01:11:38.420
[Guest]: certain models and modes of investigation are being privileged in certain places. And we will

01:11:38.420 --> 01:11:42.100
[Guest]: find learn lots of very useful things from them. I think the RCT movement also teaches us that

01:11:42.100 --> 01:11:45.460
[Guest]: there's something very useful there. And then there are things you have to take with its caveats as

01:11:45.460 --> 01:11:53.620
[Guest]: well, which is true for everything. But while that world can exist and do its thing and play its game

01:11:53.620 --> 01:11:58.980
[Guest]: and the circle jerk and all of that that you mentioned, so eloquently, there need to be other

01:11:58.980 --> 01:12:03.620
[Guest]: worlds as well. And those have to be created by people. I don't know who and I don't know where.

01:12:03.620 --> 01:12:08.580
[Guest]: I mean, if sometime, you know, I leave the bank, these are the kinds of things that I think I'm

01:12:08.580 --> 01:12:12.660
[Guest]: really interested in trying to do. I know that I think tanks that are thinking about these kinds

01:12:12.660 --> 01:12:21.220
[Guest]: of issues as well. So to me, I think the task is not to get lost in what the academic world is

01:12:21.220 --> 01:12:25.300
[Guest]: doing at all. I think let it do what it's doing. And I think there will be value there. That's

01:12:25.300 --> 01:12:30.260
[Guest]: fine. I mean, it's I'm not in judgment of that. I think it's great. And if people want to play

01:12:30.260 --> 01:12:33.780
[Guest]: the game of those incentives, I understand that as well, because people's livelihoods often are

01:12:33.780 --> 01:12:38.020
[Guest]: also on the line. I mean, you have to sort of do certain kinds of things to then get a certain job

01:12:38.020 --> 01:12:44.660
[Guest]: and then you can do different, more perhaps open ended work. But people like me who have chosen not

01:12:44.660 --> 01:12:49.860
[Guest]: to go down the path of I don't have the talent or the tenacity to finish a PhD in economics,

01:12:49.860 --> 01:12:54.180
[Guest]: I would never be able to do it the way it is structured and done. I have different talents,

01:12:54.180 --> 01:12:57.860
[Guest]: and I have a different kind of tenacity. And then you have to sort of think about where are the

01:12:57.860 --> 01:13:04.340
[Guest]: spaces where I can then apply that. And I think that's where my energies will be better served.

01:13:04.340 --> 01:13:09.780
[Guest]: And I think the onus is now on all of us who recognize that there's something wrong with the

01:13:09.780 --> 01:13:15.780
[Guest]: way, not wrong, but there's a mismatch between the kind of economics that academia is producing

01:13:15.780 --> 01:13:22.100
[Guest]: and generating and deeming legitimate. And are, you know, what we call the more ground realities,

01:13:22.100 --> 01:13:26.180
[Guest]: you know, the real world that we would like to sort of apply and marry with this kind of work.

01:13:27.140 --> 01:13:30.820
[Guest]: And I think the onus is now on us completely to try and create that. It would require people

01:13:30.820 --> 01:13:34.340
[Guest]: who will finance it, it will require people who will actually change their mental models,

01:13:34.340 --> 01:13:37.700
[Guest]: the Brahmanism that I was telling you about, you'll have to stop thinking that only, you know,

01:13:37.700 --> 01:13:42.260
[Guest]: someone with a doctorate degree has something fancy to say. Anyone can have actually anything

01:13:42.260 --> 01:13:45.940
[Guest]: fancy to say. And one of the things I actually really enjoyed when I was writing the book and

01:13:45.940 --> 01:13:50.420
[Guest]: even books that I love reading is everyone has a theory on life. And everyone is actually a

01:13:50.420 --> 01:13:55.700
[Guest]: philosopher. I really believe this. And I think in the book, you find that all the women, I mean,

01:13:55.700 --> 01:13:59.060
[Guest]: when they're talking about Shah Rukh, in a way, what are they doing? They're not actually talking

01:13:59.060 --> 01:14:03.940
[Guest]: about him, nobody really knows him. They are constructing him based on some social philosophy

01:14:03.940 --> 01:14:08.500
[Guest]: that they have about how the world works, what their sort of knowledge systems are,

01:14:08.500 --> 01:14:15.700
[Guest]: what they're drawing on, what they think of the way the world is structured. And I think it is

01:14:15.700 --> 01:14:21.940
[Guest]: now it's completely up to us to try and feed a very different kind of ecosystem. And I'd rather

01:14:21.940 --> 01:14:26.420
[Guest]: just, you know, pay more attention there. I've abandoned with this book, I've 100% abandoned

01:14:26.420 --> 01:14:30.820
[Guest]: the idea that, you know, formal academia, especially academic economists are going to

01:14:30.820 --> 01:14:35.700
[Guest]: suddenly, you know, listen to the things I have to say never. I mean, I sort of know, I know,

01:14:35.700 --> 01:14:39.940
[Guest]: and I think this goes back to the self awareness that you were talking about. I know exactly the

01:14:39.940 --> 01:14:45.300
[Guest]: way people perceive different people and knowledge claims and so on. And I'm not interested in that

01:14:45.300 --> 01:14:49.620
[Guest]: game. I think I'm interested in trying to see if we can cultivate a very different space. And that's

01:14:49.620 --> 01:14:53.300
[Amit Varma]: the space that I like to operate in. Yeah, I mean, if academic economists don't pay attention

01:14:53.300 --> 01:14:57.780
[Amit Varma]: to your book, it's their loss, not your loss. Let's be very clear about that. And yeah, I totally

01:14:57.780 --> 01:15:02.420
[Amit Varma]: agree that you need like, let 1000 flowers bloom, let academia do what it does. But let there be a

01:15:02.420 --> 01:15:07.060
[Amit Varma]: space for heretics to do what they do. And the other point I wanted to double down on is what

01:15:07.060 --> 01:15:11.140
[Amit Varma]: you correctly said that so many people are writing as if they're writing for the government or as if

01:15:11.140 --> 01:15:14.660
[Amit Varma]: they're writing for the, you know, the finance ministry to read or they're writing for think

01:15:14.660 --> 01:15:20.260
[Amit Varma]: tanks who may offer them a job. Yes, to read. That's absolutely right. Yeah. And I always felt

01:15:20.260 --> 01:15:25.940
[Amit Varma]: that if you think your ideas are important, that they express truths about the world that you want

01:15:25.940 --> 01:15:30.580
[Amit Varma]: to get out there, then you don't need to go to the supply end of the political marketplace, you need

01:15:30.580 --> 01:15:35.460
[Guest]: to go to the demand end. Yes. You know, as Andrew Breitbart said, politics is downstream of culture,

01:15:35.460 --> 01:15:41.140
[Amit Varma]: you need to get these ideas out into the culture, which is why I hope that you know, Shah Rukh Khan

01:15:41.140 --> 01:15:46.020
[Amit Varma]: reads your book and decides to do something about this. Has he? Has he read your book? Do you know?

01:15:46.020 --> 01:15:52.020
[Guest]: Oh, Hamid? No, I don't know. I know that my publishers have sent it. Multiple people I

01:15:52.020 --> 01:15:58.020
[Guest]: think have tried. Sadly, I also think he's been through just a hellish crisis in the past few

01:15:58.020 --> 01:16:06.180
[Guest]: months. And so I have no idea. I'm waiting with bated breath. I'd be lying if I didn't

01:16:06.180 --> 01:16:11.140
[Guest]: acknowledge that, that at some point, or maybe at some point, or maybe the acknowledgement will

01:16:11.140 --> 01:16:15.460
[Guest]: never come. And that's okay, as well. I'll tell you a funny story about this, which is I heard

01:16:15.460 --> 01:16:22.100
[Guest]: from an artist who had exhibited this beautiful piece of work at the Delhi Art Fair several years

01:16:22.100 --> 01:16:27.220
[Guest]: ago. And I think now this is a story which could be true or it could be realm of gossip, but I

01:16:27.220 --> 01:16:31.540
[Guest]: think is actually true. But I still want to tell the story, because I think it'll be instructive

01:16:31.540 --> 01:16:37.300
[Guest]: of what you asked me. And the work was essentially a pixelated image of Mr. Khan. And it was

01:16:37.300 --> 01:16:41.460
[Guest]: essentially his face. But you know, there are images of people in there. And it's really

01:16:41.460 --> 01:16:47.700
[Guest]: beautiful. And I think at some point, someone who's known to Mr. Khan was at the gallery when

01:16:47.700 --> 01:16:52.900
[Guest]: this was being exhibited. And then they turned and then they said, but you know, we get these kinds

01:16:52.900 --> 01:16:58.820
[Guest]: of collages every day. And I think it's a joke, but to essentially say that, you know, last year,

01:16:58.820 --> 01:17:03.860
[Guest]: there was this huge hip hop song, which was about him, you know, I think maybe something about how

01:17:03.860 --> 01:17:09.220
[Guest]: this man is also Shah Rukh Khan. I think there are people who write poetry and books and Lord

01:17:09.220 --> 01:17:13.540
[Guest]: knows what, right for him. So I wouldn't be surprised if the book essentially may even

01:17:13.540 --> 01:17:19.220
[Guest]: drown in just the deluge of wonderful things that are, you know, of acts of creativity that his

01:17:19.220 --> 01:17:25.140
[Guest]: fandom has inspired. But I'm hopeful. The one thing I will say, actually, though, about him,

01:17:25.140 --> 01:17:32.260
[Guest]: I'm very grateful for is, I don't think I would have been able to tell this kind of story,

01:17:32.260 --> 01:17:35.540
[Guest]: you know, what she was asked me right in the beginning, I think those two bits, right,

01:17:35.540 --> 01:17:41.620
[Guest]: the empathy and the economics in a way, I think the two E's somewhat, I don't think the two would

01:17:41.620 --> 01:17:48.180
[Guest]: have coexisted so easily, or the people I spoke to would allow themselves to talk about things so

01:17:48.180 --> 01:17:54.500
[Guest]: freely, had it not been for him. And I think that is the power of his icon, because it created

01:17:54.500 --> 01:18:01.220
[Guest]: created this space for all of us to talk about different structures and ways we were feeling

01:18:01.220 --> 01:18:06.660
[Guest]: lonely. And because fandom is not amid just, you know, we tend to think of it just as a,

01:18:06.660 --> 01:18:11.140
[Guest]: it's your personal preference, you like Van Gogh, or you like something else. But actually,

01:18:11.140 --> 01:18:15.300
[Guest]: fandom is an economic activities, it's a social activity, but it's also an economic activity,

01:18:15.300 --> 01:18:22.340
[Guest]: because to be a fan, and to unambiguously adore the work of an artist, you need money,

01:18:22.340 --> 01:18:27.860
[Guest]: you need access to leisure, free time, you need access to markets so that you can consume and buy

01:18:27.860 --> 01:18:33.860
[Guest]: and transact, you need access to media and mobile phones increasingly. And all of these are sort of

01:18:33.860 --> 01:18:38.420
[Guest]: attributes of, you know, formal the statistics of the economy, because their consumption,

01:18:38.420 --> 01:18:42.580
[Guest]: their employment, their liquidity, their purchasing power. But all these women then

01:18:42.580 --> 01:18:46.740
[Guest]: just told such beautiful stories about the way they found them. And I think the only reason

01:18:46.740 --> 01:18:52.740
[Guest]: that happened was because I entered the lives through fun and fandom, as opposed to going down

01:18:52.740 --> 01:18:57.620
[Guest]: another route. And so even if he never reads the book, I mean, I will just I'm always a fan,

01:18:57.620 --> 01:19:01.300
[Guest]: a perpetual fan. I know you want, but we'll talk about that. But...

01:19:02.340 --> 01:19:06.580
[Amit Varma]: My last criticism of him actually was an economic one, that in Raees,

01:19:06.580 --> 01:19:09.220
[Amit Varma]: they didn't understand the concept of the Baptist and the bootlegger.

01:19:10.260 --> 01:19:13.460
[Amit Varma]: If you remember the plot of the film, right, which is such a basic

01:19:13.460 --> 01:19:19.700
[Guest]: kind of, one can't expect too much also. But Amit, I mean, look at that film, right?

01:19:19.700 --> 01:19:25.060
[Guest]: Because what did he do? He took what was, I mean, the book is the movie supposed to be fiction,

01:19:25.060 --> 01:19:30.340
[Guest]: but we know it's based on someone who very much was real and existed. But he took essentially

01:19:30.340 --> 01:19:35.860
[Guest]: history's straightforward bad guy, right? Because, you know, you've been part, but he made him

01:19:35.860 --> 01:19:41.460
[Guest]: complex, and he made him real. And he made him suddenly there was this facet of the Indian Muslim

01:19:41.460 --> 01:19:48.660
[Guest]: experience that I had never thought about in essentially the, it wore the dress of a very

01:19:48.660 --> 01:19:53.060
[Guest]: typical masala slick mob film, like it's a gangster mobster film. That's I think the way he himself

01:19:53.060 --> 01:19:56.980
[Guest]: sees it. I've seen his interviews when he talks about it. So yeah, so I see what you're saying.

01:19:56.980 --> 01:20:01.700
[Guest]: But the film was also doing these really interesting other things as well. But so I

01:20:01.700 --> 01:20:06.260
[Guest]: think going back to your original question, no, he has not read it formally that I don't know,

01:20:06.260 --> 01:20:12.900
[Guest]: inshallah, he will. And even if he doesn't, I'm forever grateful because I don't think this kind

01:20:12.900 --> 01:20:17.140
[Guest]: of you know, it's a labor of love. But it's I don't think it would have happened had it not been

01:20:17.780 --> 01:20:21.220
[Amit Varma]: for the icon that he is. Yeah. And it's very interesting. Like one of the things that you

01:20:21.220 --> 01:20:26.820
[Amit Varma]: point out in your book is how so many women want their men to be like Shah Rukh, but the men are

01:20:26.820 --> 01:20:32.340
[Amit Varma]: actually like Salman. Yes. So if Shah Rukh didn't exist, and like you could actually do a book on

01:20:32.340 --> 01:20:37.780
[Amit Varma]: toxic masculinity, using Salman as a key figure there, desperately seeking Salman would be a book

01:20:37.780 --> 01:20:43.220
[Guest]: exactly about that, right? Yeah, you know, I say this in the book, Amit, which is that of the three

01:20:43.220 --> 01:20:49.140
[Guest]: Khans, right, if you look at their filmography, and I do have to take just one side note to say

01:20:49.140 --> 01:20:53.540
[Guest]: that so many of the intelligent things that I'm able to say, or even seem like I'm saying,

01:20:53.540 --> 01:20:58.820
[Guest]: and I'm writing in the book about film, because I'm not a film scholar, I'm not Jai or Uday or

01:20:58.820 --> 01:21:04.260
[Guest]: any of those guys, right? I don't look at it the way I think they look at it. But I'm so grateful,

01:21:04.260 --> 01:21:09.780
[Guest]: because I was able to interview all these fantastic film critics who are people like Anupama Chopra,

01:21:09.780 --> 01:21:14.420
[Guest]: and so many people who just gave their time. And you know, one thing I realized the book is a sheer

01:21:14.420 --> 01:21:18.740
[Guest]: act of generosity. I didn't know any of these people, Amit. I mean, I literally I was cold

01:21:18.740 --> 01:21:23.940
[Guest]: calling them. And I think they all just thought that the project was a bit odd. And what is this

01:21:23.940 --> 01:21:28.100
[Guest]: girl trying to do? And people were just curious. And so they chatted with me and people can be

01:21:28.100 --> 01:21:32.340
[Guest]: generous. I think that's one thing I learned through the book. So all what I'm about to say

01:21:32.340 --> 01:21:35.780
[Guest]: about the filmography is based on all these things that I've heard and read, I just want to, you know,

01:21:35.780 --> 01:21:41.780
[Guest]: give that caveat. But if you look at the three of them, Salman is, you know, brash, masculine

01:21:41.780 --> 01:21:46.260
[Guest]: confidence, exactly as you said, right, he will beat you up, there's the strong body, there's the

01:21:46.260 --> 01:21:54.100
[Guest]: stoic, traditional masculinity. Aamir's masculinity is one of, you know, productive professionalism,

01:21:54.100 --> 01:21:58.820
[Guest]: because we sort of he is the I think what traditionally Western audiences and increasingly

01:21:58.820 --> 01:22:05.460
[Guest]: now Indian audiences amongst the elite would think an actor is Mr. Aamir Khan conforms to that,

01:22:05.460 --> 01:22:09.940
[Guest]: right? Because he takes these great roles, these great scripts, meaningful cinema, all that jazz.

01:22:11.220 --> 01:22:19.860
[Guest]: Shah Rukh is his icon is one of vulnerability, anxiety, his characters are always vulnerable.

01:22:19.860 --> 01:22:24.420
[Guest]: I write this in the book vulnerable to the gaze of the other, they are very aware of the way they

01:22:24.420 --> 01:22:28.660
[Guest]: are being seen. And is it really and you know, then they shed tears about it, they talk about

01:22:28.660 --> 01:22:34.420
[Guest]: their feelings. And is it really surprising that in a country where women are constantly made to

01:22:34.420 --> 01:22:39.380
[Guest]: feel aware of the way they are being seen the way they're holding their bodies, the way they are

01:22:39.380 --> 01:22:46.100
[Guest]: being scrutinized, that a man who then starts to perform these roles where he's so aware of how

01:22:46.100 --> 01:22:52.980
[Guest]: women are seeing him is everyone's super super hero. I mean, he it's just it's you know, we talk

01:22:52.980 --> 01:22:56.980
[Guest]: about demand and supply. I think this is actually what sets up the demand and supply of his of his

01:22:56.980 --> 01:23:02.900
[Guest]: icon, which is, he's just always been playing men who engage with women, I measure, as you know,

01:23:02.900 --> 01:23:08.020
[Guest]: for the book, I measure how much time women speak in his films compared to his other male

01:23:08.020 --> 01:23:13.860
[Guest]: contemporaries. Another big box office hits in Bollywood, women just speak far more, there are

01:23:13.860 --> 01:23:19.700
[Guest]: more number of female characters, he's interested in what women have to say his characters care,

01:23:19.700 --> 01:23:24.660
[Guest]: they listen, it is not like a lot of these current movies, which apparently are feminist,

01:23:24.660 --> 01:23:28.660
[Guest]: because they're about women's issues. But then you have a man essentially speaking through most

01:23:28.660 --> 01:23:34.100
[Guest]: of them. His films are not interested in that his films may seem candy floss, and they may seem

01:23:34.100 --> 01:23:38.180
[Guest]: soppy. But actually, if you look at them, it's actually a set of interactions between men and

01:23:38.180 --> 01:23:43.060
[Guest]: women who are really trying to understand each other, which is why I think he just he creates

01:23:43.060 --> 01:23:49.140
[Guest]: this space for female love and self reflection. I don't know whether I don't think these characters

01:23:49.140 --> 01:23:53.780
[Guest]: were written with that in mind. But I think if you now look at his body of work, it becomes very

01:23:53.780 --> 01:23:58.740
[Amit Varma]: apparent that that's what's happening. I think at one point, it seemed that you know, I forget

01:23:58.740 --> 01:24:04.340
[Amit Varma]: about whom I made this observation, either Obama or Modi, who are very different people to make

01:24:04.340 --> 01:24:09.540
[Amit Varma]: the same observation about but the observation was something to do with how they are a Rorschach

01:24:09.540 --> 01:24:14.180
[Amit Varma]: test. And, you know, you can look at them. And this was, of course, true of maybe Modi pre 2014,

01:24:14.180 --> 01:24:18.740
[Amit Varma]: obviously not now. But you could look at them and see what you wanted to see in them. And I guess

01:24:18.740 --> 01:24:24.100
[Amit Varma]: to a certain extent it, you know, going through the cross section of all the women in your book

01:24:24.100 --> 01:24:28.660
[Amit Varma]: and their different interior lives and their different social circumstances, you know,

01:24:28.660 --> 01:24:32.660
[Amit Varma]: and he's playing a different role for them, a lot of certain different roles, which would,

01:24:32.660 --> 01:24:36.900
[Amit Varma]: you know, even I think take Shah Rukh by surprise, which is why I wondered if he had read it.

01:24:36.900 --> 01:24:40.260
[Guest]: It's interesting what you just said, because one of the things that I really wanted

01:24:40.260 --> 01:24:45.220
[Guest]: the reader to walk away from, you know, when we think of fandom, and especially when we think of

01:24:45.220 --> 01:24:51.140
[Guest]: fangirls, women who gush immediately, and I've noticed this in some reactions to the book in

01:24:51.140 --> 01:24:55.780
[Guest]: the early phase. Now, I think it's it's sort of ebbed out, but which is that well, if women are

01:24:55.780 --> 01:25:00.980
[Guest]: gushing, it's just silly. And it's it's foolish. And it's not serious. It is there's just a bunch

01:25:00.980 --> 01:25:05.300
[Guest]: of dumb girls. It's so cringe were inducing right that all these girls are sitting and saying all

01:25:05.300 --> 01:25:11.220
[Guest]: these gushy foolish things about some guy who they don't know some actor. But, Amit, one thing I

01:25:11.220 --> 01:25:15.940
[Guest]: realized is, you know, these things that we dismiss as being silly and very unserious, if you start to

01:25:15.940 --> 01:25:19.940
[Guest]: pay attention to them, they'll teach you things that will take you by surprise. And the book,

01:25:19.940 --> 01:25:24.340
[Guest]: I think a lot of things I learned took me by surprise. And you realize that actually,

01:25:24.980 --> 01:25:31.940
[Guest]: beneath all the gushing and the you know, the exuberance, in a way, each one of these women

01:25:31.940 --> 01:25:37.220
[Guest]: are projecting their realities onto him. And I say this in the book, which is his extraordinary

01:25:37.220 --> 01:25:43.220
[Guest]: icon is completely built with the ordinary frustrations of all these women. I mean,

01:25:43.220 --> 01:25:48.100
[Guest]: they are completely projecting. And in the book, you would have noticed when I speak about him

01:25:48.100 --> 01:25:52.420
[Guest]: in public for I call him Mr. Khan, because I don't know him. And he's a real person. And one

01:25:52.420 --> 01:25:56.020
[Guest]: has to sort of maintain respect and dignity and all of that, you know, maintain the fact that I

01:25:56.020 --> 01:26:00.980
[Guest]: don't know this person at all. But in the book, he's always called Shah Rukh. And the reason that

01:26:00.980 --> 01:26:05.380
[Guest]: is, is because none of the women I interviewed, nobody called him Mr. Khan, nobody called him SRK,

01:26:05.380 --> 01:26:09.700
[Guest]: they would always call him Shah Rukh. And I remember watching this interview of his where

01:26:09.700 --> 01:26:14.420
[Guest]: he actually said fans behave like they know you. And even when I talk about him, you know,

01:26:14.420 --> 01:26:19.620
[Guest]: with my friends, when I'm not conscious of myself, I will call him Shah Rukh, like I know him. But

01:26:19.620 --> 01:26:25.540
[Guest]: actually, none of us know him, we have all created him out of our own hopes, aspirations, frustrations,

01:26:25.540 --> 01:26:30.740
[Guest]: lived experience. So the book, as you know, is structured in different parts. And the first part

01:26:30.740 --> 01:26:37.220
[Guest]: is elite, upper middle class women. The principal characters in these stories love him as a sign of

01:26:37.220 --> 01:26:42.820
[Guest]: social mobility, post liberalization, they hate Rahul Gandhi, some of them are Modi voters. And

01:26:42.820 --> 01:26:47.780
[Guest]: now things are shifting. I write about this in the book. And they love him as a person who

01:26:47.780 --> 01:26:54.020
[Guest]: symbolizes someone who has essentially escaped entrenched network wealth, someone who's trying

01:26:54.020 --> 01:26:59.300
[Guest]: to find a house for themselves. These are things that they really look when they see him, that's

01:26:59.300 --> 01:27:05.220
[Guest]: what they see. When you move towards the second part of the book has women from you know, the

01:27:05.220 --> 01:27:09.860
[Guest]: first generation of the middle class, right trader caste families, girls who come from homes where

01:27:09.860 --> 01:27:14.500
[Guest]: they were just expected to get married and stay at home. The women in the book didn't they decided

01:27:14.500 --> 01:27:18.660
[Guest]: to follow professional identities and parts and love and marry based on their own choice.

01:27:19.620 --> 01:27:24.740
[Guest]: They see him essentially for him, he is consolation and comfort because their families

01:27:24.740 --> 01:27:28.740
[Guest]: make it so difficult for them. One of the principal characters in that part runs away

01:27:28.740 --> 01:27:33.380
[Guest]: from her family, because the family makes it so difficult for them to just be who they are.

01:27:34.020 --> 01:27:39.220
[Guest]: And they feel very unloved. And yet they have to put on this front of being very cool and austere.

01:27:39.220 --> 01:27:44.340
[Guest]: And he is essentially the person they cry to. He is essentially the person who's providing them

01:27:44.340 --> 01:27:47.940
[Guest]: comfort because they can't talk about what they're feeling in their extremely conservative

01:27:47.940 --> 01:27:52.900
[Guest]: lives with anybody else. And he plays a very different function. And then when you move to

01:27:52.900 --> 01:27:57.540
[Guest]: the third part of the book, where there are all these women from extremely harsh economic

01:27:57.540 --> 01:28:03.540
[Guest]: circumstances, agarbatti makers within their homes, domestic workers migrating from Jharkhand

01:28:03.540 --> 01:28:10.660
[Guest]: to Jorbag in Delhi, they see him essentially as announcing opportunity and announcing not just

01:28:10.660 --> 01:28:16.100
[Guest]: the opportunity to leave your village, but opportunity to find your own lover. Because

01:28:16.100 --> 01:28:20.580
[Guest]: one of the most interesting stories to me in the book is how I one of the women I follow,

01:28:20.580 --> 01:28:24.180
[Guest]: she's one of the first women I met when I started, you know, the idea of this book.

01:28:24.180 --> 01:28:29.460
[Guest]: She was a unioniser actually in a slum in Ahmedabad. Now, it's no longer a slum anymore.

01:28:29.460 --> 01:28:34.500
[Guest]: It's an upgraded colony. She left her husband, she did very well for herself. And I described

01:28:34.500 --> 01:28:38.900
[Guest]: what she you know, the journey of that within the labour market. And her daughter went to really

01:28:38.900 --> 01:28:44.180
[Guest]: good school and they watch Shah Rukh films together. And I say this in the book that

01:28:44.180 --> 01:28:50.980
[Guest]: actually, if you look at the older woman, she's Zahira in the book, she couldn't read English

01:28:50.980 --> 01:28:56.900
[Guest]: very well. And her daughter could, her daughter's called Meenal. And they watch Dil Toh Pagal Hai

01:28:56.900 --> 01:29:00.660
[Guest]: together often, it's their favourite film, they love the songs, they love everything about it.

01:29:01.540 --> 01:29:06.340
[Guest]: And at the end of Dil Toh Pagal Hai, there's a line that flashes Amit, I forget what the line

01:29:06.340 --> 01:29:09.540
[Guest]: is, I think something about it's an overture to love that people should love, you know,

01:29:09.540 --> 01:29:14.660
[Guest]: you should find someone who loves you, something like that. It was written in English. And Zahira,

01:29:14.660 --> 01:29:19.700
[Guest]: the mother, she loves Mr. Khan, to her, he is a fantastical ideal of just this beautiful,

01:29:19.700 --> 01:29:23.220
[Guest]: fun man, men who are now in cities, you know, things that are happening in cities.

01:29:24.100 --> 01:29:29.140
[Guest]: And, but it was not real for her, she, you know, to her, it was just sublimation. And she could,

01:29:29.140 --> 01:29:33.380
[Guest]: she couldn't read English. So that line really didn't sit with her. Her daughter, on the other

01:29:33.380 --> 01:29:38.900
[Guest]: hand, refuses even now, and I end the book with her, actually, she's still single, she refuses

01:29:38.900 --> 01:29:43.940
[Guest]: to settle. In fact, Zahira is trying to get Meenal married, that you must marry. But she says no,

01:29:43.940 --> 01:29:50.180
[Guest]: she says no, I she read those lines in English, she believes in the totalitarian, you know, idea

01:29:50.180 --> 01:29:56.740
[Guest]: of romance and love that I must love someone who I marry, she will not settle. And and I think for

01:29:56.740 --> 01:30:03.620
[Guest]: them, he is essentially the person who announces that your opportunities and your freedom now is

01:30:03.620 --> 01:30:08.180
[Guest]: unbounded, you can do things that your mother perhaps couldn't. And I think all of these parts

01:30:08.180 --> 01:30:12.180
[Guest]: essentially go to show that people are just constructing him, they're constructing Shah Rukh,

01:30:12.180 --> 01:30:17.700
[Guest]: nobody knows Mr. Khan. But we are all constructing Shah Rukh, I have as well. And he has participated

01:30:17.700 --> 01:30:22.180
[Guest]: in that myth. And I agree with you, I really hope he reads it just to see what he's co created with

01:30:22.180 --> 01:30:26.740
[Guest]: a whole bunch of us this entire generation of women. It's quite special and quite spectacular.

01:30:27.460 --> 01:30:33.460
[Guest]: But it is a creation, it is a construction. And I think the book is in service to understand how

01:30:33.460 --> 01:30:41.300
[Guest]: is it that society and within society, the economy is allowing the space or pushing women to construct

01:30:41.300 --> 01:30:45.700
[Guest]: the Shah Rukh? Why are they doing that? And they're doing that because the economy and their

01:30:45.700 --> 01:30:51.220
[Guest]: society and homes make them feel very unloved in places unsafe in some places. And so they're

01:30:51.220 --> 01:30:57.220
[Amit Varma]: projecting onto this image. In popular culture, one of the interesting sort of shifts that I've

01:30:57.220 --> 01:31:02.580
[Amit Varma]: seen not really a shift, but it's a new development in one sense, is that back in the day, stars would

01:31:02.580 --> 01:31:07.540
[Amit Varma]: be larger than life. So you'd, you know, you'd have temples for stars and blah, blah, blah,

01:31:07.540 --> 01:31:12.340
[Amit Varma]: all of that, you'd worship them, or you'd wait outside the house, just just to catch one glimpse.

01:31:12.340 --> 01:31:17.860
[Amit Varma]: And where does kind of changing in modern times is that there is what people call the economy of

01:31:17.860 --> 01:31:23.700
[Amit Varma]: intimacy, where because of, you know, YouTube streams, or podcasts, you feel like you actually

01:31:23.700 --> 01:31:27.940
[Amit Varma]: know the person like, I did this episode with Abhinandan Sekri, and I got this lovely piece

01:31:27.940 --> 01:31:32.420
[Amit Varma]: of feedback, I think someone tweeted it or wrote to me. And he said that I felt so much like I'm

01:31:32.420 --> 01:31:36.420
[Amit Varma]: sitting on a sofa with you guys, and you guys are talking, and I'm enjoying myself that at

01:31:36.420 --> 01:31:41.060
[Unknown]: one point, I actually interrupted you before realizing that shit, I'm listening to a podcast.

01:31:41.940 --> 01:31:45.700
[Amit Varma]: That's lovely. And the interesting thing about Shah Rukh, as you mentioned, and even I called

01:31:45.700 --> 01:31:50.580
[Amit Varma]: him Shah Rukh, see, is that he seems to straddle both of these. He is on the one hand larger than

01:31:50.580 --> 01:31:54.740
[Amit Varma]: life. But on the other hand, you call him Shah Rukh. And I recently wrote a post about the

01:31:54.740 --> 01:31:59.780
[Amit Varma]: Beatles documentary, Get Back, where at one point I said Paul and Ringo. Yeah. And of course, we know

01:31:59.780 --> 01:32:03.300
[Amit Varma]: that the first time you mentioned someone in a piece, you have to take the full name. Yeah. And

01:32:03.300 --> 01:32:06.980
[Unknown]: then you take the surname. Yeah. But I just said Paul and Ringo, because to me, they're Paul and

01:32:06.980 --> 01:32:12.180
[Guest]: Ringo. Yeah, right. I grew up with them. They're my childhood friends. Yeah. And in the book,

01:32:12.740 --> 01:32:16.900
[Guest]: in fact, it's something that I noticed at the very end, it didn't even occur to me that I was

01:32:16.900 --> 01:32:21.460
[Guest]: doing this. But I was. And I was doing it because all the women who I spoke to were doing it,

01:32:21.460 --> 01:32:26.740
[Guest]: which is we only call him Shah Rukh, because there is this, he's accessible. But you know,

01:32:26.740 --> 01:32:33.540
[Guest]: it's interesting, Amit, because he's like, in a way, he, I think, in India, really revolutionized

01:32:33.540 --> 01:32:38.420
[Guest]: this. I've actually, this economy of intimacy is a great phrase. And I'm going to go look it up. I

01:32:38.420 --> 01:32:43.060
[Guest]: thank you for telling me about it. It's interesting, because if you look back to 1992,

01:32:43.060 --> 01:32:46.500
[Guest]: and I know so many of your shows, you talk about the changes there. And I find those

01:32:46.500 --> 01:32:52.420
[Guest]: conversations really fascinating. It was such an era of promise and so much change, right? Because

01:32:52.420 --> 01:32:58.260
[Guest]: suddenly, there were satellite network televisions, there were, you know, page three, which needed

01:32:58.260 --> 01:33:07.220
[Guest]: Bollywood. And he was the first actor who could be intimate with us in a way on our televisions,

01:33:07.220 --> 01:33:11.700
[Guest]: even before the internet came and completely changed things even further. That I don't even

01:33:11.700 --> 01:33:16.020
[Guest]: think Rajesh Khanna or, you know, none of the actors of the past had who had the temples and,

01:33:16.020 --> 01:33:21.060
[Guest]: you know, mad fandom as well, but in a very different way. And so as a consequence,

01:33:21.060 --> 01:33:25.860
[Guest]: he just seemed like this guy you knew. So when I was watching him on TV, and also then, and then

01:33:25.860 --> 01:33:30.340
[Guest]: it requires talent, because obviously, no celebrities ever really presenting themselves.

01:33:30.340 --> 01:33:34.900
[Guest]: I mean, that's, I don't think that happens. So there's a talent in which he also had this

01:33:34.900 --> 01:33:41.060
[Guest]: facility to engage with media to talk to people. It was just his interviews. I mean, I think

01:33:41.060 --> 01:33:44.260
[Guest]: they're just delicious. Just listen to the things he's saying. And I know you don't,

01:33:44.260 --> 01:33:48.260
[Guest]: you may not like his movies, but highly encourage you to look at some interviews.

01:33:48.260 --> 01:33:54.100
[Guest]: And I mean, I can even give you a list of interviews to start with. But always useful

01:33:54.100 --> 01:34:01.460
[Guest]: things about be it secularism, the economy, work ethic, professionalism. He has this terrific line,

01:34:01.460 --> 01:34:05.940
[Guest]: when someone asked him, this is when the film Dilwale came out, I'm going to say 2015,

01:34:06.500 --> 01:34:11.460
[Guest]: in a big press conference, you know, this young woman got up, you know, young journalist, and

01:34:11.460 --> 01:34:15.460
[Guest]: she said something about actually her working life that apparently she couldn't work and

01:34:15.460 --> 01:34:20.420
[Guest]: she was struggling to hold on to a job, right? This is exactly in link with the theme of the book.

01:34:20.420 --> 01:34:26.100
[Guest]: He said something like, ladies, don't leave your job, your day job for a night husband.

01:34:26.820 --> 01:34:31.940
[Unknown]: You know, who says things like that? I mean, the comments are just and I sometimes you just

01:34:31.940 --> 01:34:37.700
[Guest]: have to listen and the book is full of quotes of his, because I just found that the things he was

01:34:37.700 --> 01:34:43.060
[Guest]: saying and the fact that now telecom and the TV allowed for those things to then be said and

01:34:43.060 --> 01:34:48.260
[Guest]: relayed and then the internet has just amplified that. But I think for a certain generation of us,

01:34:49.300 --> 01:34:55.220
[Guest]: for us, he essentially represents that change, because he was the first star that we saw

01:34:55.220 --> 01:34:59.060
[Guest]: who made that that dramatic shift, which is became much more intimate to us.

01:35:00.020 --> 01:35:04.580
[Guest]: And I actually say this in the book that all the elite fans always call him, you know,

01:35:04.580 --> 01:35:10.180
[Guest]: he's India's first post liberalization superstar. But for women who don't know words, you know,

01:35:10.180 --> 01:35:14.580
[Guest]: like GDP, they don't know what happened with Mr. Manmohan Singh. They know Shah Rukh was

01:35:14.580 --> 01:35:20.500
[Guest]: liberalization to them, his poster, him drinking a Pepsi, him being on top of that truck and,

01:35:20.500 --> 01:35:25.060
[Guest]: you know, dancing with Shahid Kapoor and all of those images, they've seen all of that.

01:35:25.060 --> 01:35:29.700
[Guest]: It's signal to them that their call would always connect now. Suddenly there were powders and

01:35:29.700 --> 01:35:33.380
[Guest]: creams in the local shop and Shah Rukh was, you know, was a little poster there.

01:35:34.420 --> 01:35:36.980
[Guest]: And so I think there is an intimacy that he has with us,

01:35:36.980 --> 01:35:42.100
[Guest]: not just because of course, the TV allowed for it. But I think because he represents this nostalgia

01:35:42.100 --> 01:35:46.420
[Guest]: of this really promising moment, right? And now, of course, we're in a very different moment. And

01:35:46.420 --> 01:35:51.700
[Guest]: I think he is also capturing that. And we'll talk about that later. But I do see that. The other

01:35:51.700 --> 01:35:55.940
[Guest]: thing I noticed when I was talking to women now about, you know, all these actors now available

01:35:55.940 --> 01:36:00.340
[Guest]: to us through YouTube. And one thing that's also happened, I mentioned this in the book,

01:36:00.340 --> 01:36:05.060
[Guest]: and it's a thesis that I can't fully test, but I do think my gut tells me that there's something

01:36:05.060 --> 01:36:12.340
[Guest]: to it, is that I think people like him are they're part of the last generation of umbrella superstars

01:36:12.340 --> 01:36:19.540
[Guest]: who connect people from across classes, languages, regions. Because now when I talk to younger

01:36:19.540 --> 01:36:26.020
[Guest]: people, if you are in Jharkhand, or you're in Kerala, or you're in Delhi, because the media

01:36:26.020 --> 01:36:29.700
[Guest]: market and what's accessible to you has become so fragmented based on your taste, because of the

01:36:29.700 --> 01:36:34.100
[Guest]: internet, right, you can see things that are almost curated to you on YouTube or anywhere else.

01:36:34.100 --> 01:36:41.060
[Guest]: The idea of this one star who everybody likes is actually doesn't hold as much weight anymore.

01:36:41.060 --> 01:36:45.140
[Guest]: The closest I could, you know, sense of that kind of popularity is actually now the female

01:36:45.140 --> 01:36:51.060
[Guest]: actresses I hear a lot about, you know, be it a Deepika Padukone or a Priyanka Chopra. And they

01:36:51.060 --> 01:36:56.260
[Guest]: really seem to now embody feminine aspirations for even younger women in the book, because

01:36:56.260 --> 01:36:59.940
[Guest]: they are independent, they're not ashamed of having boyfriends, they continue to work after

01:36:59.940 --> 01:37:07.300
[Guest]: marriage. But the idea of this star who connects people, be it a boatman, a bureaucrat across

01:37:07.300 --> 01:37:11.860
[Guest]: the country, I think Shah Rukh might actually be that generation might actually be one of the last

01:37:11.860 --> 01:37:16.660
[Guest]: because now we're just living in a very fragmented media system, because of all the forces that you

01:37:16.660 --> 01:37:19.140
[Guest]: mentioned, be it the internet, YouTube, and so on.

01:37:19.140 --> 01:37:23.780
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, that's a fantastic insight and a great term umbrella superstar. I'm going to come back to that

01:37:23.780 --> 01:37:27.940
[Amit Varma]: after the break. But before we go in for the break, I just want to say that I don't think we

01:37:27.940 --> 01:37:33.220
[Amit Varma]: really look at that I disagree with any of what you say about Shah Rukh. I think we're looking at

01:37:33.220 --> 01:37:38.900
[Amit Varma]: the elephant through different lenses. And you might not agree with my lens. See, my lens is that

01:37:38.900 --> 01:37:44.900
[Amit Varma]: like, one of the things I've come to realize is that Indian cinema is a completely different

01:37:44.900 --> 01:37:50.100
[Amit Varma]: beast from cinema anywhere else. There are different incentives. Yeah, and we could just

01:37:50.100 --> 01:37:54.420
[Amit Varma]: break it down economically, but it is just incredibly different. It's catering to something

01:37:54.420 --> 01:38:00.420
[Amit Varma]: else. And therefore our notions of acting also have to take that into account that you cannot

01:38:00.420 --> 01:38:06.260
[Amit Varma]: judge an Indian star through your lens of what a Western actor would be and how they would act and

01:38:06.260 --> 01:38:12.420
[Amit Varma]: play a part and all of that. And Shah Rukh, I think seen from that Western kind of lens is I think

01:38:12.420 --> 01:38:19.380
[Amit Varma]: the worst actor of all time. But that that is, but in a sense that is irrelevant. It's orthogonal.

01:38:19.380 --> 01:38:25.460
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, because it's a category error, perhaps to judge him like that. Because at doing what he is

01:38:25.460 --> 01:38:31.220
[Amit Varma]: doing, which is his build this persona, that persona clearly has a resonance with so many

01:38:31.220 --> 01:38:35.540
[Amit Varma]: different people in so many different ways. And to maintain that persona and take it into all

01:38:35.540 --> 01:38:39.620
[Amit Varma]: these different directions is a phenomenal achievement. I grant him that. And by the way,

01:38:39.620 --> 01:38:43.940
[Amit Varma]: I love some Bollywood. I love Govinda, for example. I know. I'm aware. I'm aware.

01:38:43.940 --> 01:38:51.620
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, private. But I would demonetize me. And as far as his interviews are concerned,

01:38:52.180 --> 01:38:55.540
[Amit Varma]: please do share all the links. I'll put them in the show notes for people to see for themselves.

01:38:56.100 --> 01:39:00.020
[Amit Varma]: But my sense from the little that I've seen is that they're also very skillfully,

01:39:00.020 --> 01:39:05.620
[Amit Varma]: he's built a persona. And he is that persona. And he says some things where he is clearly

01:39:05.620 --> 01:39:10.820
[Amit Varma]: posturing like even in your book, you quote this part where he says that and this is like

01:39:10.820 --> 01:39:15.620
[Amit Varma]: Virtue Signaling Max, where he says that I don't believe in feminism because feminism only says

01:39:15.620 --> 01:39:20.340
[Amit Varma]: that women should be equal to men. And he says, quote, I believe women should be more than us,

01:39:20.340 --> 01:39:28.180
[Guest]: stop quote, like, give me a break. I know, but a couple of things. One, I have friends who are

01:39:28.180 --> 01:39:33.460
[Guest]: trained in like, posh, fancy, you know, drama school. So they went to RADA and all of those

01:39:33.460 --> 01:39:38.740
[Guest]: places. I asked them once, this is like a test. I was doing research. I don't write about it. I

01:39:38.740 --> 01:39:42.500
[Guest]: thought about writing about it. But I didn't finally, because it didn't involve the women.

01:39:43.220 --> 01:39:49.220
[Guest]: I asked them, can you do like that arms wide open, you know, with that, just can you conjure

01:39:49.220 --> 01:39:54.820
[Guest]: that? And it's near impossible. And they all told me that the kind, it requires a kind of talent

01:39:54.820 --> 01:39:58.900
[Guest]: and register, which is quite unique, I think is unique to very Indic traditions of, you know,

01:39:59.460 --> 01:40:03.780
[Guest]: drama and local theatre. And I can tell, you know, when you watch him as well, when he talks

01:40:03.780 --> 01:40:08.820
[Guest]: about acting as a craft, you can tell that he's bringing in all these different elements, right.

01:40:08.820 --> 01:40:13.540
[Guest]: And so I do think that while I, you know, I'm not going to judge anyone, because if we start judging

01:40:13.540 --> 01:40:17.860
[Guest]: Keanu Reeves, for instance, from the perspective of a Western actor, I think we may actually end

01:40:17.860 --> 01:40:21.060
[Guest]: up seeing similar things. In fact, I think there's a strong parallel between the two of them,

01:40:21.060 --> 01:40:26.340
[Guest]: interestingly enough. So maybe on my next will be desperately seeking Keanu. But what I'm trying to

01:40:26.340 --> 01:40:31.940
[Guest]: say to you is that I think there is a kind of talent and technique there. It's just so skillfully

01:40:31.940 --> 01:40:36.100
[Guest]: done that we don't see it for what it is, but it's really difficult to do. And there are trained

01:40:36.100 --> 01:40:39.780
[Guest]: actors who will try and there are trained actors who have tried, there's some very talented actors

01:40:39.780 --> 01:40:44.660
[Guest]: who've tried, but they just can't get that register. So I think we do have to acknowledge

01:40:44.660 --> 01:40:50.500
[Guest]: that while I see your point. And the other thing I will say about him is that even the, you know,

01:40:50.500 --> 01:40:56.260
[Guest]: what we would think is posturing or some of the lip service kind of comments, I still felt when

01:40:56.260 --> 01:41:00.580
[Guest]: I was talking to the women that I was and I think about this myself as well, you would have noticed

01:41:00.580 --> 01:41:04.180
[Guest]: this actually comes up in the book a lot. A lot of women say, well, even if he is just saying it

01:41:04.180 --> 01:41:10.340
[Guest]: as marketing, I appreciate that he's saying it. And one of the places that really keeps coming up

01:41:10.340 --> 01:41:15.940
[Guest]: is he's actually one of our only icons who from a very early stage has been talking about women's

01:41:15.940 --> 01:41:21.540
[Guest]: issues. And even if it is, I don't care, honestly, Amit, if it's a stunt, if it's posturing, whatever

01:41:21.540 --> 01:41:26.580
[Guest]: it is, given the society we live in, given look at where we are when it comes to gender, things

01:41:26.580 --> 01:41:32.660
[Guest]: are incredibly bleak, more power to more powerful messages. I would like him to, you know, shout

01:41:32.660 --> 01:41:36.500
[Guest]: more about lots of things, but, you know, he won't do that. He'll do what he wants to say. And that's

01:41:36.500 --> 01:41:41.780
[Guest]: his prerogative and sovereignty. So I actually appreciate all of that because, you know, one of

01:41:41.780 --> 01:41:46.100
[Guest]: the women said to me, she said, well, have you noticed that he says all these wonderful things

01:41:46.100 --> 01:41:51.540
[Guest]: about, you know, his family, his wife, you know, women. And she says, she said, and it's quoted in

01:41:51.540 --> 01:41:57.700
[Guest]: the book, she said that even if it is an act, I appreciate it, because who else is doing that?

01:41:57.700 --> 01:42:02.020
[Guest]: And I think particularly when he came onto the scene, nowadays, I think there's some cachet to

01:42:02.020 --> 01:42:07.620
[Guest]: being the tender male in sort of, you know, certain kind of appearance on social media.

01:42:08.180 --> 01:42:13.140
[Guest]: But I see that for what it is, he was doing this way before. And I think one of the places where

01:42:13.140 --> 01:42:17.460
[Guest]: he was doing this significantly, which is really interesting is, and I write about it at length in

01:42:17.460 --> 01:42:22.980
[Guest]: the book is, you know, he was always Indian cinema's poster child for marital fidelity,

01:42:22.980 --> 01:42:26.580
[Guest]: which is really interesting, right? Like all the women I met, they would tell me,

01:42:26.580 --> 01:42:30.740
[Guest]: so great, he's always with his wife. And he's so caring and loving for his wife. And you know,

01:42:30.740 --> 01:42:36.020
[Guest]: he's been with her forever, whereas everyone else is sort of seen as some constantly chasing skirt,

01:42:36.020 --> 01:42:41.460
[Guest]: playboy superstar. And he was definitely not that he completely died. He departed from that

01:42:41.460 --> 01:42:48.180
[Guest]: completely. And he in various interviews would constantly say, because people would shamelessly

01:42:48.180 --> 01:42:53.380
[Guest]: then Amit ask him and all people was Tavleen Singh, who asked him in an interview, very serious

01:42:53.380 --> 01:42:58.500
[Guest]: interview, she asks, and I quote this in the book, she says, how come you don't have any affairs?

01:42:58.500 --> 01:43:03.620
[Guest]: Because it's so common for actors to have affairs. And it was I think Rajiv Shukla asked him something

01:43:03.620 --> 01:43:08.260
[Guest]: similar in an interview once on Doordarshan of all places. And he just looked bored. And he said,

01:43:08.260 --> 01:43:13.700
[Guest]: well, I thought that the women I work with, they are my co workers and colleagues, I didn't realize

01:43:13.700 --> 01:43:18.100
[Guest]: that I'm supposed to make love to them. And of course, he's being his beautiful, sarcastic best.

01:43:18.820 --> 01:43:23.540
[Guest]: But so many women just appreciated the fact that he treated women as comrades, as colleagues,

01:43:23.540 --> 01:43:28.580
[Guest]: as friends in the workplace. And this is the pre me to world. And we can only imagine what was

01:43:28.580 --> 01:43:33.860
[Guest]: happening in Bollywood at that time and what kind of space it was. And so even if it is an act,

01:43:33.860 --> 01:43:38.180
[Guest]: Amit, and even if there is posturing, and I think you heard Paramita Vohra say something similar to

01:43:38.180 --> 01:43:44.180
[Guest]: what I'm saying, I think there's the club of women who are so hopelessly in love with this man,

01:43:44.180 --> 01:43:48.900
[Guest]: but we appreciate it. Because I think at the time that he was saying this, no one else at that time

01:43:48.900 --> 01:43:54.580
[Guest]: really was in our culture, the way he was saying it and with the intensity that he was and I think

01:43:54.580 --> 01:43:59.140
[Amit Varma]: that's really appreciated. This is really scary. You seem to have researched me as well as I

01:43:59.140 --> 01:44:03.300
[Amit Varma]: researched you. You're referring to the Paramita episode where I just remembered Paro and I also

01:44:03.300 --> 01:44:08.100
[Amit Varma]: argued about Shahrukh. No, I completely agree with this. And you know, this mirrors what Salman

01:44:08.100 --> 01:44:12.180
[Amit Varma]: Sohs, the Congress politician once said to me, he came on my show and I asked him that is there

01:44:12.180 --> 01:44:17.140
[Amit Varma]: anything about Modi that you like? And he said, I like the Swachh Bharat campaign, because forget

01:44:17.140 --> 01:44:21.780
[Amit Varma]: what the result is the fact that he's preaching the virtue of cleanliness, preaching the virtue

01:44:21.780 --> 01:44:27.860
[Amit Varma]: of something that is desirable itself makes an impact given his massive reach. So now that we

01:44:27.860 --> 01:44:32.420
[Amit Varma]: have established that the Prime Minister Modi has something in common with both Barack Obama

01:44:32.420 --> 01:44:34.900
[Amit Varma]: and Shahrukh Khan, I think it's time we take a break.

