[Amit Varma]: the India Uncut newsletter at indiancut.substack.com. Thank you.

01:46:07.300 --> 01:46:13.380
[Amit Varma]: Economics works, you know, to do that first will I think help if we then zoom in later into a lot

01:46:13.380 --> 01:46:19.060
[Amit Varma]: of the particular stories that you've gotten into because that context is fantastic. Now I did an

01:46:19.060 --> 01:46:23.860
[Amit Varma]: episode a while back a couple of years back about women in the workplace with Amitabh Bhandari.

01:46:23.860 --> 01:46:30.580
[Amit Varma]: And we kind of discussed that really puzzling thing that as our economy has grown, and it was

01:46:30.580 --> 01:46:36.100
[Amit Varma]: growing at that time, as our economy has grown, less women are working. Yes. And you've broken

01:46:36.100 --> 01:46:42.260
[Amit Varma]: this out extremely well in your book. So take me through sort of the four different reasons why we

01:46:42.260 --> 01:46:47.460
[Guest]: see less women in the workplace. Amit, I think the first thing that we need to understand when

01:46:47.460 --> 01:46:52.820
[Guest]: we talk about this is I want to set the context for how the data is collected on the basis of

01:46:52.820 --> 01:46:58.180
[Guest]: which we see that this is happening. And I actually know the episode as well. And I follow your show

01:46:58.180 --> 01:47:03.140
[Guest]: quite regularly. So good, good, good listener. I think you've learned stalking from your hero.

01:47:03.140 --> 01:47:10.100
[Guest]: Amit, don't embarrass me. But a couple of things. One is when the government, this is the NSS data

01:47:10.100 --> 01:47:14.580
[Guest]: on employment and unemployment, it tends to be what I want to just tell everyone is it tends to

01:47:14.580 --> 01:47:18.740
[Guest]: be quite consistent across the periods of time. So it's not like there are some changes in

01:47:18.740 --> 01:47:24.100
[Guest]: methodology, some changes may be in sampling. But broadly, we're talking about it's a broad

01:47:24.100 --> 01:47:29.460
[Guest]: apples to apples comparison. So when I see that female employment rates and labor force participation

01:47:29.460 --> 01:47:35.300
[Guest]: rates have dropped dramatically from 2004 till 2017, that's actually a robust claim,

01:47:35.300 --> 01:47:39.220
[Guest]: because it's a robust claim using a measure that stayed quite standard. I think that's

01:47:39.220 --> 01:47:42.740
[Guest]: very important to know. It's not like we're suddenly changing the way it's designed.

01:47:42.740 --> 01:47:48.020
[Guest]: The second thing I want everyone to know is that when we measure women's work, in fact,

01:47:48.020 --> 01:47:55.060
[Guest]: statisticians and I, a community that I have deep admiration for is more than economists is

01:47:55.060 --> 01:47:59.460
[Guest]: statisticians, because they really get into the nuts and bolts of how do you construct these numbers,

01:47:59.460 --> 01:48:03.700
[Guest]: which try and convey something about reality, right, much like film. And one of the things that

01:48:03.700 --> 01:48:08.260
[Guest]: you learn when you look at the history of Indian employment statistics, and I get into that a little

01:48:08.260 --> 01:48:13.220
[Guest]: bit just for the reader to have some context in the book, is that they were very concerned about

01:48:13.220 --> 01:48:18.660
[Guest]: the fact that Indians hold multiple jobs, the nature of our labor market is segmented, very

01:48:18.660 --> 01:48:23.140
[Guest]: fluid, you could be doing something one hour or something else the next hour, you could be paid

01:48:23.140 --> 01:48:27.940
[Guest]: for it, you could be helping your family with something productive. And so actually, the measure

01:48:27.940 --> 01:48:33.220
[Guest]: that they use is fairly broad and inclusive. So I often get asked, is my domestic worker counted?

01:48:33.220 --> 01:48:38.740
[Guest]: Technically, yes, someone who is a part time domestic worker, or full time domestic worker,

01:48:39.380 --> 01:48:42.900
[Guest]: even if you're not working, you know, the traditional office job, nine to five,

01:48:42.900 --> 01:48:47.700
[Guest]: you will be counted. So casual workers, self employed workers, and so on, I just want

01:48:47.700 --> 01:48:52.500
[Guest]: all of us to just be clear that it's not that this is just salaried workers were often counted,

01:48:52.500 --> 01:48:57.540
[Guest]: because I get questions like that all the time. Now, given that we see the sharp drop,

01:48:57.540 --> 01:49:02.100
[Guest]: and you're absolutely right, I think there's been a lot written about, even with economic growth,

01:49:02.100 --> 01:49:06.900
[Guest]: we see this complete drop, which actually makes India quite an exception from other countries,

01:49:06.900 --> 01:49:10.900
[Guest]: even in a Turkey and China, where you see stagnating female employment, you don't see

01:49:10.900 --> 01:49:16.500
[Guest]: the same sharp drop that we've seen. And if you look at all the literature, there are sort of

01:49:16.500 --> 01:49:23.700
[Guest]: broadly four buckets of things that are going on. One is what I think many people call the income

01:49:23.700 --> 01:49:31.300
[Guest]: effect. And it's quite worrying, but essentially, the data suggests is that as families start to

01:49:31.300 --> 01:49:39.060
[Guest]: earn more money, they are able to purchase more conservative values. And this is particularly

01:49:39.060 --> 01:49:44.500
[Guest]: seen amongst the upper caste. So for example, in the book, upper caste well to do families in

01:49:44.500 --> 01:49:51.060
[Guest]: particular, where if in fact, if you look at the top 10% of India right now using the CMI data for

01:49:51.060 --> 01:49:57.780
[Guest]: 2019, and I mentioned this in the book, of all married women, I think in the richest cohort,

01:49:57.780 --> 01:50:04.580
[Guest]: only 6.5% hold a job. And so the income effect is giving you a flavour of why this is happening. And

01:50:04.580 --> 01:50:10.820
[Guest]: what this body of literature suggests is that because families now earn more, there's no need

01:50:10.820 --> 01:50:15.380
[Guest]: for an additional income earner. So women don't need to go out of the home to work. So they can

01:50:15.380 --> 01:50:20.900
[Guest]: now retreat into full time mothering, caring, right. And this explains why seven out of 10 women

01:50:20.900 --> 01:50:25.780
[Guest]: between the ages of 15 to 59 are full time working within the home, they're attending to household

01:50:25.780 --> 01:50:30.340
[Amit Varma]: duties. That's what it's called statistically. That's one. So just to just to sort of double

01:50:30.340 --> 01:50:35.140
[Amit Varma]: click on that itself. Yeah, one more time. But the psychological aspect of that is very important,

01:50:35.140 --> 01:50:41.460
[Amit Varma]: like interesting, the phrase you used is, once the income goes up, they can buy more conservative

01:50:41.460 --> 01:50:47.140
[Amit Varma]: values. And therefore, the way I would interpret that is that the traditional notion is that a

01:50:47.140 --> 01:50:51.700
[Unknown]: woman's place is in the house, she should be looking after the kitchen, after the children,

01:50:51.700 --> 01:50:57.300
[Amit Varma]: so on and so forth. And somehow the owner of the house is stained if the woman has to go out and

01:50:57.300 --> 01:51:01.780
[Amit Varma]: work. But you know, when you have constraints of income, and she absolutely has to work,

01:51:01.780 --> 01:51:05.860
[Guest]: what do you do? Yeah. But once that is gone, the women get back into the house.

01:51:05.860 --> 01:51:09.780
[Guest]: And Amit, in fact, you're seeing that play out right now, because what many people are expecting,

01:51:09.780 --> 01:51:14.580
[Guest]: and you would have seen in the recent round of the periodic labor force survey, we see female

01:51:14.580 --> 01:51:19.220
[Guest]: employment rates actually rose a bit and then have stabilized. And one of the things that people

01:51:19.220 --> 01:51:23.700
[Guest]: are now trying to understand, and we need to dig into it much deeper is that is it that crisis is

01:51:23.700 --> 01:51:27.860
[Guest]: now creating this need for women to step out of the home? We don't know, it's a mixed bag.

01:51:27.860 --> 01:51:33.060
[Guest]: But you're absolutely right. There is this notion that women's work is flexible, women's labor is

01:51:33.060 --> 01:51:37.380
[Guest]: flexible. So women are, remember, women are always working. We say they're not employed for money,

01:51:37.380 --> 01:51:42.580
[Guest]: but women are always working. If you look at time poverty numbers of women, women are always busy

01:51:42.580 --> 01:51:47.780
[Guest]: cooking, cleaning, collecting water, creating firewood, all kinds of work in rural areas.

01:51:47.780 --> 01:51:53.140
[Guest]: In urban areas, women are working, managing domestic roles. Not everyone has a maid. I

01:51:53.140 --> 01:51:57.140
[Guest]: think that's a fallacy. We need to sort of have some vision correction. It's the really wealthy

01:51:57.140 --> 01:52:03.060
[Guest]: who do and the real upper middle class that does. Most women are always working. But I think when

01:52:03.060 --> 01:52:08.100
[Guest]: we're talking about these sharp drops, it's for paid employment, of course. Now, given that,

01:52:08.100 --> 01:52:12.500
[Guest]: if women are seen as a flexible resource for the household, you then realize that if you really

01:52:12.500 --> 01:52:16.260
[Guest]: need it, then women can work outside the home. And so what the income effect is saying is post

01:52:16.260 --> 01:52:20.420
[Guest]: liberalization, post this big boom in the economy, essentially many households said,

01:52:20.420 --> 01:52:24.980
[Guest]: we don't need you to work. Now, I want to just caveat that also by saying that there's a little

01:52:24.980 --> 01:52:29.620
[Guest]: bit nuance there, because that may not always be a bad thing, because there may actually be women,

01:52:29.620 --> 01:52:33.940
[Guest]: you encounter them in the book, who actually say that I don't want to be working outside

01:52:33.940 --> 01:52:38.900
[Guest]: because I'm working inside all the time. Now I need to go out and earn in the world, which is

01:52:38.900 --> 01:52:44.580
[Guest]: so unsafe and horrid to women in public spaces anyway. Why is the man in my life not meeting the

01:52:44.580 --> 01:52:48.980
[Guest]: breadwinning end of his contract in the marriage? And so many women actually would say that if he's

01:52:48.980 --> 01:52:53.060
[Guest]: doing well enough, I'm happy to be at home and care full time within the home. That's something

01:52:53.060 --> 01:52:57.860
[Guest]: that actually is an empowered choice in a way for some women. So while this effect is existing,

01:52:57.860 --> 01:53:01.700
[Guest]: and we're seeing women drop out, there's a sense of nuance there, which is part of it could actually

01:53:01.700 --> 01:53:06.420
[Guest]: be welfare enhancing for some women, and part of it couldn't be as well. So it's both. So that's

01:53:06.420 --> 01:53:10.980
[Guest]: the income effect. The second is, of course, an underestimation effect on it. And that I think,

01:53:10.980 --> 01:53:15.860
[Guest]: when I started by discussing the way these numbers are constructed, I myself, when I was working for

01:53:15.860 --> 01:53:20.740
[Guest]: the Institute of Social Studies Trust, this is a paper which was published in EPW, we did a survey

01:53:20.740 --> 01:53:26.420
[Guest]: of women's employment in Delhi. And what we realised was the moment you use female surveyors,

01:53:26.420 --> 01:53:31.140
[Guest]: volunteer students, who will essentially, these are young students, they're interested to probe

01:53:31.140 --> 01:53:36.500
[Guest]: more, ask more questions, they will pick up women's employment. Whereas if you just go

01:53:36.500 --> 01:53:40.580
[Guest]: standard and ask, do you work? Most women will just say no. So many women will say,

01:53:41.140 --> 01:53:48.740
[Guest]: I don't have a job, but I'm working, right? I'm helping my family. And so when someone asks as

01:53:48.740 --> 01:53:52.820
[Guest]: a statistical entity, are you working, the temptation may just be to not report their work.

01:53:52.820 --> 01:53:58.340
[Guest]: So there is a kind of underestimation because of misreporting, not capturing women's work well,

01:53:58.340 --> 01:54:03.620
[Guest]: not asking enough probing questions to do full justice to a very good survey instrument that

01:54:03.620 --> 01:54:06.980
[Guest]: the government does implement through its statistical machinery. I think it's quite

01:54:06.980 --> 01:54:11.540
[Guest]: robust. So there's an underestimation effect there, which continues to hold and it's not just

01:54:11.540 --> 01:54:15.700
[Guest]: our paper, then this has been corroborated by several other pieces of work by different

01:54:15.700 --> 01:54:19.860
[Guest]: organizations and different scholars essentially saying that women's work tends to be misunderstood

01:54:19.860 --> 01:54:23.860
[Guest]: and underreported. So that's the second. The third is more hopeful, is what I think people

01:54:23.860 --> 01:54:28.420
[Guest]: like Surjeet Bhalla, Ravinder Kaur, they call it the education effect. And the idea is that because

01:54:28.420 --> 01:54:35.220
[Guest]: younger girls and young women are studying more, are spending more time in college or in continuing

01:54:35.220 --> 01:54:39.940
[Guest]: to finish school, they are essentially not working in the early part of their career. Well, these

01:54:39.940 --> 01:54:43.460
[Guest]: aren't careers, these are typically, you know, people doing ad hoc jobs, given the kind of

01:54:43.460 --> 01:54:47.060
[Guest]: milieu, the social milieu we're talking about, because they're studying more, they're not

01:54:47.060 --> 01:54:50.020
[Guest]: working. And so that's, that's actually quite good, which is that, you know, you're studying

01:54:50.020 --> 01:54:54.260
[Guest]: more, then you immediately get married, and then your marriage is your job, in a way. So that's

01:54:54.260 --> 01:54:58.180
[Guest]: the third. The fourth, which I actually find the most interesting, and I don't think enough

01:54:58.180 --> 01:55:03.140
[Guest]: is said about this, this is work by Martin Rama and Rinku Murgai and Urmila Chatterjee,

01:55:03.140 --> 01:55:07.060
[Guest]: in fact, colleagues of mine at the bank, others have been doing this work as well,

01:55:07.060 --> 01:55:11.860
[Guest]: essentially saying, they call it the structural transformation effect in a way, or the structural

01:55:11.860 --> 01:55:15.700
[Guest]: transformation of the economy. And one of the things, I'd really encourage everyone to look

01:55:15.700 --> 01:55:18.900
[Guest]: at this paper, not only because I think it has really beautiful insights on what's happening

01:55:18.900 --> 01:55:23.620
[Guest]: to women's work, but the data work is really nicely done. It's just a very good work of

01:55:23.620 --> 01:55:29.300
[Guest]: econometrics, using government data sets. One of the things they find is that the way the Indian

01:55:29.300 --> 01:55:33.940
[Guest]: economy has changed with the move away from agriculture, the boost to construction, certain

01:55:33.940 --> 01:55:39.940
[Guest]: kinds of services, sectors that traditionally used to employ women, such as agriculture,

01:55:39.940 --> 01:55:44.420
[Guest]: or flexible work within the home, small scales, cottage industries, for instance,

01:55:44.420 --> 01:55:48.820
[Guest]: those have been in deep decline. And the transformation of the economy seems to have

01:55:48.820 --> 01:55:53.620
[Guest]: really helped men because there's a study by scholars of the ILO, what they find is if you

01:55:53.620 --> 01:56:00.180
[Guest]: look at the top 10 fastest growing sectors in the economy, post liberalisation, women have only

01:56:00.180 --> 01:56:05.700
[Guest]: received 19% of the jobs, one nine, which means most of the employment gains of that growth and

01:56:05.700 --> 01:56:10.020
[Guest]: the transformation in the Indian economy have been cornered by men. And it's a bit different

01:56:10.020 --> 01:56:14.500
[Guest]: from the others, because instead of a demand story, sorry, instead of a supply story that

01:56:14.500 --> 01:56:18.340
[Guest]: the household is unwilling to let women supply their labour outside the home, this is looking

01:56:18.340 --> 01:56:23.380
[Guest]: much more at sectors who demand labour. And what they're saying is that the economy is moving and

01:56:23.380 --> 01:56:27.140
[Guest]: changing in such a way that sectors that would typically demand women's time and their labour

01:56:27.140 --> 01:56:31.620
[Guest]: and pay them no longer exist. And in fact, you see this playing out in the book, Amit, I met

01:56:31.620 --> 01:56:36.740
[Guest]: all these home based garment workers and Agarbati workers in 2006. This is a time when there was a

01:56:36.740 --> 01:56:42.260
[Guest]: slight, you know, bump up right around that period. Immediately after slowly and particularly

01:56:42.260 --> 01:56:47.700
[Guest]: post demonetisation, these home based industries and it's all essentially, it's a depressed sector

01:56:47.700 --> 01:56:52.340
[Guest]: now, because incense sticks, garments have moved to either special economic zones, or they're much

01:56:52.340 --> 01:56:56.660
[Guest]: more organised and clustered in certain areas. And so in fact, some of this flexible work that

01:56:56.660 --> 01:57:00.180
[Guest]: women were doing, and they enjoyed this work, because it allowed them to combine their

01:57:00.180 --> 01:57:05.220
[Guest]: reproductive work as well as their work outside for the market, those opportunities are shrinking,

01:57:05.220 --> 01:57:09.540
[Guest]: the wages that are shrinking as well. And so that's the structural transformation story.

01:57:09.540 --> 01:57:14.020
[Guest]: There's a specific, so these are the four broad buckets. And there's one very interesting,

01:57:14.020 --> 01:57:18.820
[Guest]: I find the paper just fascinating, this is by Farzana Afridi, she's at ISI and her colleagues,

01:57:18.820 --> 01:57:23.540
[Guest]: and what they find looking at rural women, because one of the things that we have to realise about

01:57:23.540 --> 01:57:28.340
[Guest]: this drop is that it's while urban female employment rates has always stayed around 13%,

01:57:28.340 --> 01:57:33.780
[Guest]: 14%. It's always that it's been fairly stable. So the gap actually has been fairly stable over

01:57:33.780 --> 01:57:39.380
[Guest]: the past 30 years. It's actually rural areas where the sharp drop in female employment has

01:57:39.380 --> 01:57:44.100
[Guest]: been acutely seen as a rural phenomena. And part of it is that agriculture structural transformation

01:57:44.100 --> 01:57:49.300
[Guest]: story that I told you, part of is the education story, underestimation, households are earning

01:57:49.300 --> 01:57:53.300
[Guest]: more money, you see this in the book, there's a character who's in rural Uttar Pradesh,

01:57:53.300 --> 01:57:57.780
[Guest]: her husband is an electrician and a carpenter, post liberalisation, suddenly government wants

01:57:57.780 --> 01:58:02.660
[Guest]: to give out PWD contracts, right to all these young men, they're earning much more. So the

01:58:02.660 --> 01:58:06.660
[Guest]: expectation is now the woman doesn't need to work, that's the income effect. And you see all of this

01:58:06.660 --> 01:58:10.980
[Guest]: playing out. But in rural areas, there's one additional factor which people like Farzana and

01:58:10.980 --> 01:58:15.300
[Guest]: others are trying to sort of unpack more. And I think it's just really interesting work. What

01:58:15.300 --> 01:58:21.620
[Guest]: they're saying is that with more primary education, women's role as unpaid caregivers who

01:58:21.620 --> 01:58:27.300
[Guest]: will improve the human capital of their children, because they've studied more so they can manage

01:58:27.300 --> 01:58:32.500
[Guest]: children better, invest in their nutrition better, teach them better. So the kids can grow up to be

01:58:32.500 --> 01:58:38.420
[Guest]: more productive members of the labour market, the value to the home of women as unpaid workers

01:58:38.420 --> 01:58:43.300
[Guest]: is actually much higher than the wage that they would earn outside doing, you know, low end

01:58:43.300 --> 01:58:48.580
[Guest]: agriculture work or other kinds of work. And so women are retreating, because it's almost a way

01:58:48.580 --> 01:58:53.380
[Guest]: to improve the productivity of the household at the margin, I think is really interesting. And

01:58:53.380 --> 01:58:58.660
[Guest]: they find this specifically in rural areas. And so I think these are broadly the big theories.

01:58:58.660 --> 01:59:05.140
[Guest]: And I think three messages around that, right, one, which we all know, motherhood and marriage

01:59:05.140 --> 01:59:10.500
[Guest]: are typically what are just kicking women out of the workforce constantly. And I say kicking,

01:59:10.500 --> 01:59:14.340
[Guest]: but then I want to again, nuance that because many times just a voluntary withdrawal as well.

01:59:14.340 --> 01:59:18.660
[Guest]: And I think we have to just acknowledge that, that many women would just say that I'd prefer

01:59:18.660 --> 01:59:23.860
[Guest]: and I find more meaning in just being at home being a mother caring, and that's that's a choice.

01:59:23.860 --> 01:59:31.300
[Guest]: And I think the other is that if you look at the way women are interacting with the job market,

01:59:31.300 --> 01:59:36.340
[Guest]: essentially, if you look at manufacturing, for instance, I think 64% of women involved in

01:59:36.340 --> 01:59:41.780
[Guest]: manufacturing work from home, the home even before the pandemic before work from home became a you

01:59:41.780 --> 01:59:47.060
[Guest]: know, public health measure. The home was the principal workplace. And for men, it's about 15%.

01:59:47.060 --> 01:59:53.220
[Guest]: So there is this very important schematic, I want all of us in fact, read the book,

01:59:53.220 --> 01:59:56.580
[Guest]: when you consume these numbers, when you read the studies to recognize that actually often

01:59:56.580 --> 02:00:00.980
[Guest]: when we're talking about women who are working, who is the working woman, she's at home, she may

02:00:00.980 --> 02:00:05.860
[Guest]: not be going out of the home, she may be making something at home, she may be cooking and cleaning

02:00:05.860 --> 02:00:13.300
[Guest]: on another person's home. But the home as a site for female labor, that's a very enduring aspect of

02:00:13.300 --> 02:00:18.020
[Guest]: women's presence in the economy that hasn't really changed that significantly. And so I think these

02:00:18.020 --> 02:00:23.060
[Guest]: are the five buckets of theories. There's marriage motherhood, which I think is often talked about.

02:00:23.060 --> 02:00:28.260
[Guest]: And the fact that the home is the key site, if you want to really impact the labor conditions

02:00:28.260 --> 02:00:32.660
[Guest]: of women, you're not going to do that through policies that don't attack the home, be it

02:00:32.660 --> 02:00:35.860
[Guest]: shelter security, I think I talked about this earlier, be it shelter security, childcare

02:00:35.860 --> 02:00:40.980
[Guest]: investments, thinking about improved access to water, and you're seeing these dynamics play out.

02:00:40.980 --> 02:00:44.740
[Guest]: And the last thing I will say, this is sort of emerging work, which is not really a theory,

02:00:44.740 --> 02:00:48.740
[Guest]: but I think it will intuitively make sense to everyone, which is that India has grown in such

02:00:48.740 --> 02:00:53.620
[Guest]: a way that there are clusters where jobs and opportunities exist, right? Jobs don't exist

02:00:53.620 --> 02:00:57.780
[Guest]: everywhere equally. That's just not the case. That's not at all the case. What's happening is

02:00:57.780 --> 02:01:04.100
[Guest]: men can migrate out to find jobs from Bhuvaneshwar, they can go to Bombay from anywhere else, they can

02:01:04.100 --> 02:01:09.300
[Guest]: go anywhere, public spaces safe for them, housing is safe for them for really, you know, low income

02:01:09.300 --> 02:01:13.860
[Guest]: men, even, you know, sleeping on the streets is potentially a possibility, sadly, and that does

02:01:13.860 --> 02:01:19.460
[Guest]: happen. And you have these labor chalks and so on. For women, though, educated, even those who

02:01:19.460 --> 02:01:26.100
[Guest]: come from very difficult backgrounds, the idea of migrating en masse to follow economic opportunity,

02:01:26.100 --> 02:01:32.180
[Guest]: the benefit to that is just not worth families incurring the social cost, because they're

02:01:32.180 --> 02:01:37.220
[Guest]: worried about girl safety. What if she finds a boyfriend? What if you know, something happens,

02:01:37.220 --> 02:01:41.220
[Guest]: there are all these concerns. And so often what ends up happening is the few stories we hear of

02:01:41.220 --> 02:01:45.620
[Guest]: women migrating for work often now with, you know, special economic zones, they migrate through a

02:01:45.620 --> 02:01:50.580
[Guest]: contractor or domestic workers who migrate through contractor are harrowing stories of harassment,

02:01:50.580 --> 02:01:55.380
[Guest]: because often the contractor and many of these factories and SECs are treating women the way a

02:01:55.380 --> 02:02:00.100
[Guest]: benevolent patriarch would write like extremely rigid rules about where you can go out, whether

02:02:00.100 --> 02:02:04.500
[Guest]: you can use your phone, all these kinds of things about domestic workers, we know there's issues

02:02:04.500 --> 02:02:10.020
[Guest]: about withholding wages, not being paid on time, abuse, harassment again. And so hearing these

02:02:10.020 --> 02:02:16.420
[Guest]: stories, listening to these experiences, migration out to follow jobs is not something that women can

02:02:16.420 --> 02:02:21.700
[Guest]: safely and freely do. And I think that's really important. And the last thing on this, I will say,

02:02:21.700 --> 02:02:29.940
[Guest]: I realized I've said a lot is that caste continues to be the most important, not barrier, but

02:02:29.940 --> 02:02:34.580
[Guest]: mediator of jobs. And what I mean by that is that there was a Pew survey recently,

02:02:34.580 --> 02:02:39.780
[Guest]: which essentially found that even in 2021, in the middle of the pandemic, when people asked Indians,

02:02:39.780 --> 02:02:44.420
[Guest]: are you comfortable with your daughter marrying outside of her caste community? Most Indians said

02:02:44.420 --> 02:02:49.780
[Guest]: no. And they're extremely worried about who the woman marries, this obsession with female sexual

02:02:49.780 --> 02:02:56.740
[Guest]: purity is just doesn't seem to change. And that fear around caste purity plays itself out in the

02:02:56.740 --> 02:03:00.900
[Guest]: labor market. Because why is it that all these families are so scared of women going even to

02:03:00.900 --> 02:03:04.820
[Guest]: Gurgaon in the book, you actually talk about a character, her father's willing to let her work

02:03:04.820 --> 02:03:09.060
[Guest]: in the Delhi secretariat, because he thinks that's government and it's understood. But the idea of

02:03:09.060 --> 02:03:13.780
[Guest]: her going and taking up perhaps a higher paying job in a private company in Gurgaon is very worrying,

02:03:13.780 --> 02:03:19.300
[Guest]: because he's immediately associating it with boyfriends, love affairs, Lord knows who she

02:03:19.300 --> 02:03:25.460
[Guest]: will suddenly end up with. And this fear around female sexuality, what will women do with their

02:03:25.460 --> 02:03:29.300
[Guest]: bodies and their hearts? We don't think of sexuality when we think of the labor market,

02:03:29.300 --> 02:03:33.620
[Guest]: but actually, the two are extremely connected. And you see this in the book. And I think caste is

02:03:33.620 --> 02:03:38.420
[Guest]: the reason why because there are such scripts of womanhood needs to bear, as you mentioned earlier,

02:03:38.420 --> 02:03:42.500
[Guest]: not just the honor of the home, but the caste honor of the home, right. And that is the reason

02:03:42.500 --> 02:03:47.540
[Guest]: why women's access to jobs just remains so severely compromised. Because even if options

02:03:47.540 --> 02:03:53.620
[Guest]: exist, families will make women feel so tense and unhappy about following them up that many women

02:03:53.620 --> 02:03:57.540
[Guest]: will just say, well, to hell with it. Whereas in the book, in fact, there are stories of women who

02:03:57.540 --> 02:04:01.540
[Guest]: say no, we want to still pursue and then the stories tell you what happens when they try and

02:04:01.540 --> 02:04:08.740
[Amit Varma]: fight their families to just go find a job. Lucid illustration of social pressures having,

02:04:08.740 --> 02:04:13.220
[Amit Varma]: you know, an impact on the labor market. It's people wouldn't often connect the two. Before

02:04:13.220 --> 02:04:17.860
[Amit Varma]: I move on to my next question, I want to not double click but mouse over perhaps on what you

02:04:17.860 --> 02:04:21.540
[Amit Varma]: said about the structural transformation effect that can you give me examples of some of these

02:04:21.540 --> 02:04:26.420
[Guest]: new industries which are coming up, which tend to attract more men? Construction and often and in

02:04:26.420 --> 02:04:30.900
[Guest]: fact, imagine and I mean, the thing that we also realize need to realize is these are all interacting

02:04:30.900 --> 02:04:35.300
[Guest]: effects. So for example, with construction, sometimes wives may follow men, but because of

02:04:35.300 --> 02:04:39.300
[Guest]: the underestimation effect, many times that work is perhaps not even captured. But and also many

02:04:39.300 --> 02:04:43.220
[Guest]: of the times women are not paid independently, they're essentially following for care purposes.

02:04:43.220 --> 02:04:47.540
[Guest]: And many times men just migrate out on their own. If you look at the sectors that have really boomed

02:04:47.540 --> 02:04:52.980
[Guest]: post liberalization, it's construction, it's retail, it's transport and majority of employment

02:04:52.980 --> 02:04:57.460
[Guest]: gains here. And this should not surprise us intuitively. These are jobs that require movement.

02:04:57.460 --> 02:05:01.460
[Guest]: These are jobs that require interacting with public space. These are jobs that require a fair

02:05:01.460 --> 02:05:06.980
[Guest]: amount of haggling and negotiating and interacting with lots of strangers. These are all jobs that

02:05:06.980 --> 02:05:12.020
[Guest]: largely men have essentially found and and also the nature of the skill and the what what's

02:05:12.020 --> 02:05:17.540
[Guest]: required. And it's frustrating. I think for a lot of women in rural India, I think the urban

02:05:17.540 --> 02:05:20.900
[Guest]: landscape is still different. I actually think the urban landscape hasn't dramatically changed.

02:05:20.900 --> 02:05:25.140
[Guest]: I think the jobs have changed and women are the kinds of families who would support women to work

02:05:25.140 --> 02:05:28.980
[Guest]: like mine, for instance, will continue to do so. And it's just the nature of the job may change.

02:05:28.980 --> 02:05:33.860
[Guest]: You know, we may not work in a bank much more than perhaps just be a teacher. But we should

02:05:33.860 --> 02:05:39.220
[Guest]: remember teaching nursing. These are actually the core occupations that urban women are involved in.

02:05:39.220 --> 02:05:43.380
[Guest]: But in rural areas, it's very frustrating. And this is a frustration that finds its way in

02:05:43.380 --> 02:05:48.420
[Guest]: the book is that many of these girls are the first generation to study in a school. They

02:05:48.420 --> 02:05:52.420
[Guest]: after Sarveshiksha Abhiyan, which was the previous the district primary education program,

02:05:52.420 --> 02:05:56.740
[Guest]: the predecessor of Sarveshiksha Abhiyan, they are educated. I say this, they're numerate,

02:05:56.740 --> 02:06:01.860
[Guest]: they're literate, and they're ready to go somewhere. But they can't. And their brothers

02:06:01.860 --> 02:06:07.780
[Guest]: take up jobs as contractors, plumbers, electricians, all kinds of things that are available

02:06:07.780 --> 02:06:11.940
[Guest]: to them. And to them, that's an adventure, you know, moving from even a village in Rampur to

02:06:11.940 --> 02:06:15.540
[Guest]: the city of Bareilly, moving from Bareilly, then perhaps to Dubai, like all that these are all

02:06:15.540 --> 02:06:19.300
[Guest]: transitions that are happening in the book. But for girls, it's still, you need to be married,

02:06:19.300 --> 02:06:24.100
[Guest]: if you want to go somewhere. I think the structural transformation story is really

02:06:24.100 --> 02:06:29.860
[Guest]: bears itself out, particularly in rural India, because suddenly you had jobs in building roads,

02:06:30.500 --> 02:06:35.300
[Guest]: trading, transporting, those jobs just were not available to women at scale.

02:06:35.300 --> 02:06:39.300
[Amit Varma]: And what you said about women having to be married to go somewhere. One of the best books I've read

02:06:39.300 --> 02:06:43.380
[Amit Varma]: in the last few years while doing the scene and the unseen was India moving by Chinmay Tumbe.

02:06:43.380 --> 02:06:49.140
[Amit Varma]: And my great TIL moment there was that the maximum internal migration happens in India

02:06:49.140 --> 02:06:53.220
[Amit Varma]: because of women getting married, because women get married, and then they just go with their

02:06:53.220 --> 02:06:57.860
[Unknown]: husband, which just tells you so much about the lack of agency and so on and so forth.

02:06:57.860 --> 02:07:01.940
[Guest]: You know, in fact, there's a beautiful line, I forget, Indian author in her book, she says,

02:07:01.940 --> 02:07:05.620
[Guest]: once you're married, you're free to do anything your husband wants you to do.

02:07:06.660 --> 02:07:12.020
[Guest]: And, you know, in the book, this finds in my book, this it's interesting, I see that play out,

02:07:12.020 --> 02:07:17.780
[Guest]: but there's a particular woman I met in rural Uttar Pradesh in the district of Rampur, she makes

02:07:17.780 --> 02:07:23.060
[Guest]: embroidery work at home. And one of the things she says is that for her marriage is her ticket

02:07:23.060 --> 02:07:26.500
[Guest]: to malls. And she says, you know, if you marry someone who let you watch Shah Rukh movies,

02:07:26.500 --> 02:07:32.100
[Guest]: wouldn't that be great? You know, so marriage, the tyranny of marriage in mediating women's

02:07:32.100 --> 02:07:37.780
[Guest]: access, and social sanction to access public space, still continues. And Amit, I mean,

02:07:37.780 --> 02:07:41.380
[Guest]: it's not just women in rural Rampur. I mean, you look at me, and I've been mentioning this

02:07:41.380 --> 02:07:45.860
[Guest]: example constantly while I've been talking about the book, but I live in a really plush neighborhood

02:07:45.860 --> 02:07:51.780
[Guest]: in Delhi, I am extremely well to do in the economic pyramid of our country. But even for me,

02:07:51.780 --> 02:07:56.980
[Guest]: Amit, to find a house on my own without being married is hideously difficult. I mean, it's it's

02:07:56.980 --> 02:08:01.140
[Guest]: not easy. There are all these, you know, conversations, lots of grumbling. This is true

02:08:01.140 --> 02:08:05.460
[Guest]: for women and friends of mine in Bombay and many other cities in the country. What always surprises

02:08:05.460 --> 02:08:11.380
[Guest]: me is how internalized the lack of female agency has become that we don't even talk about these

02:08:11.380 --> 02:08:15.380
[Guest]: things that much. We're not out on the streets protesting any of this, right? I mean, we protest

02:08:15.380 --> 02:08:19.540
[Guest]: when comedians say things that are just innocuous, and actually don't even say things that are

02:08:19.540 --> 02:08:24.660
[Guest]: innocuous. And, you know, we get upset about those things. But but the sheer lack of freedom

02:08:24.660 --> 02:08:29.540
[Guest]: that women have, I just don't see anyone getting really agitated and angry about it. And I'm

02:08:29.540 --> 02:08:34.740
[Guest]: really angry. I think you find that anger in the book. But I just, I don't see that you're right,

02:08:34.740 --> 02:08:38.340
[Guest]: the tyranny of marriage and the tyranny of motherhood. And to me, these are scripts of

02:08:38.340 --> 02:08:44.900
[Guest]: womanhood. There's a kind of Indian womanhood that has just been reified and constantly

02:08:44.900 --> 02:08:50.980
[Guest]: affirmed again and again. And all the women in the book, Amit, are all deviating from these

02:08:50.980 --> 02:08:55.540
[Guest]: standard scripts in their own ways, the very different ways. And I think the appeal of Mr.

02:08:55.540 --> 02:09:00.260
[Guest]: Khan is when you're deviating from these scripts, and you're looking for fun, escape, comforts,

02:09:00.260 --> 02:09:05.860
[Guest]: you know, something else, a man who will support that deviation, he's essentially who they find.

02:09:05.860 --> 02:09:10.020
[Guest]: I think you're absolutely right, which is I think marriage and the lack of agency is just,

02:09:10.020 --> 02:09:13.620
[Amit Varma]: it's an enduring characteristic. And just thinking aloud, you mentioned protesting,

02:09:13.620 --> 02:09:18.900
[Amit Varma]: and I just thought that this, you know, we live in a country that wants to lock up Manavar Faruqi

02:09:18.900 --> 02:09:25.140
[Amit Varma]: and acquit Mahmood Faruqi. Yeah, that's also an issue. So continuing with the theme of women

02:09:25.140 --> 02:09:30.980
[Amit Varma]: working, you also point out in your book, that women working outside the home also face so many

02:09:30.980 --> 02:09:34.340
[Amit Varma]: problems, like you've quoted, you know, Senthil Mullainathan talking about the hidden taxes,

02:09:34.340 --> 02:09:38.260
[Amit Varma]: I'll just quote that bit out, because I think it's so illuminating. Quote,

02:09:38.260 --> 02:09:42.900
[Amit Varma]: the working world is unfair to many women, yet even when they succeed, they must confront another

02:09:42.900 --> 02:09:48.180
[Amit Varma]: series of challenges, or their hard won successes are taxed in ways that men's are not. The taxes

02:09:48.180 --> 02:09:52.260
[Amit Varma]: I'm talking about aren't paid in dollars and cents, or imposed by the government. They take

02:09:52.260 --> 02:09:58.100
[Amit Varma]: the form of annoyance and misery, and are levied by individuals very often by loved ones. I call

02:09:58.100 --> 02:10:04.020
[Amit Varma]: these impositions taxes, because it take away some of what an individual earns, diminishing

02:10:04.020 --> 02:10:09.860
[Amit Varma]: the joys of success, stop quote. And what you sort of demonstrate so movingly in your book

02:10:09.860 --> 02:10:15.220
[Amit Varma]: is that it's almost as if women are condemned to be lonely. They're lonely in the workplace,

02:10:15.220 --> 02:10:20.340
[Amit Varma]: they're lonely in the kitchen, as you point out. So can you expand a little bit more on this from

02:10:20.340 --> 02:10:25.780
[Amit Varma]: your conversations and your experiences and so on? Just make this concrete for me in terms of

02:10:25.780 --> 02:10:30.900
[Amit Varma]: what are these hidden taxes, like one would imagine, like the typical way one would think

02:10:30.900 --> 02:10:35.620
[Amit Varma]: about this is that women are working, that's great. It's one step further to empowerment

02:10:35.620 --> 02:10:41.140
[Amit Varma]: and to agency and all of that. But it's more complicated. Yeah. And I think that's also why

02:10:41.140 --> 02:10:45.300
[Guest]: women are dropping out of the workforce. That's I think that's the contention that I make doesn't,

02:10:45.300 --> 02:10:49.540
[Guest]: it can't be tested statistically, because it's a sociological claim, but it's different. But

02:10:50.340 --> 02:10:55.540
[Guest]: you know, what's happening is, and this links back to the conversation of how do we tackle

02:10:55.540 --> 02:11:00.660
[Guest]: this crisis of jobs for women. And what I really believe listening to all these stories and

02:11:00.660 --> 02:11:05.940
[Guest]: following these women for 15 years is that behind the crisis of jobs, there's a crisis of love.

02:11:05.940 --> 02:11:14.260
[Guest]: And what I mean by that is that each of the women in the book, any time they try and have their own

02:11:14.260 --> 02:11:20.660
[Guest]: bank account, have an independent space, which is completely private to them. Each time they are

02:11:20.660 --> 02:11:25.780
[Guest]: asserting something about themselves as an economic agent and economic individual, because there's

02:11:25.780 --> 02:11:29.540
[Guest]: something about the market where it really highlights the individuality of yourself,

02:11:29.540 --> 02:11:36.180
[Guest]: because it is your labor fundamentally, they are always made to feel unworthy, unloved,

02:11:36.180 --> 02:11:40.980
[Guest]: second guest. And there are different ways this is playing out through the book, depending on

02:11:40.980 --> 02:11:46.500
[Guest]: your class position and where you are. So for instance, amongst the upper class elite women

02:11:46.500 --> 02:11:50.420
[Guest]: that I was speaking to most of whom, in fact, during the time that I knew them, many of whom

02:11:50.420 --> 02:11:56.020
[Guest]: just dropped out of the workforce, it plays out in even if you have a maid, even if you have a

02:11:56.020 --> 02:12:01.300
[Guest]: nanny, even if you have, you know, cook cleaner, all of that, women are exclusively responsible

02:12:01.300 --> 02:12:04.980
[Guest]: for keeping track of what is happening in the household. And I think some economists call this

02:12:04.980 --> 02:12:09.940
[Guest]: the cost of keeping track, you're constantly keeping track. And men just aren't expected to

02:12:09.940 --> 02:12:13.300
[Guest]: keep track that way. And the statistical data that bears that out, which is in the book that

02:12:13.300 --> 02:12:18.660
[Guest]: women just constantly labor on lists and following up and all of those things. Men are not doing that

02:12:18.660 --> 02:12:23.060
[Guest]: men are out in the world, and then they come back and they have this clean separation between leisure

02:12:23.060 --> 02:12:30.580
[Guest]: time and working time, women are always working. And the other place where this hidden tax on women

02:12:30.580 --> 02:12:37.300
[Guest]: plays out is, in fact, in the romantic market, where what I kept hearing from women is that

02:12:38.420 --> 02:12:45.060
[Guest]: men are not comfortable marrying, loving, caring for and supporting women who perhaps are more

02:12:45.060 --> 02:12:51.540
[Guest]: economically successful than them, or perhaps even their economic equals, that while femininity,

02:12:51.540 --> 02:12:56.500
[Guest]: particularly amongst the English speaking elite and upper middle class has changed to the point

02:12:56.500 --> 02:13:01.140
[Guest]: that, you know, women expect a Shah Rukh, right, they want someone who will be a partner and a

02:13:01.140 --> 02:13:08.100
[Guest]: supporter. Men and masculinity is yet to transform that radically. And you see this playing out in

02:13:08.100 --> 02:13:14.100
[Guest]: different ways. So then men lash out at successful women, by either cheating on them, making them

02:13:14.100 --> 02:13:20.500
[Guest]: feel bad about their bodies, all kinds of really bad emotional behavior, which makes women feel

02:13:20.500 --> 02:13:26.100
[Guest]: very unworthy, you know, about their bodies about themselves about their ambitions. And I kept

02:13:26.100 --> 02:13:31.460
[Guest]: hearing from a lot of very successful women, and I'm one of them. In fact, I think my chapter in

02:13:31.460 --> 02:13:36.100
[Guest]: the book is a very is an illustration of this, which is that you will be made to feel bad if

02:13:36.100 --> 02:13:41.220
[Guest]: you happen to have a professional identity, which you even display and wear. I mean, it's not like

02:13:41.220 --> 02:13:46.100
[Guest]: you're showing it off. It's just something you wear. And I was told by people I was with that

02:13:46.100 --> 02:13:50.580
[Guest]: you better just hide that don't talk about your work. Men are supposed to talk about work. So I

02:13:50.580 --> 02:13:54.340
[Guest]: think those are the hidden taxes and sort of the upper crust in that milieu. If you look at the

02:13:54.340 --> 02:13:58.740
[Guest]: hidden taxes when it comes to sort of this emerging trader caste, middle class, right,

02:13:58.740 --> 02:14:03.060
[Guest]: there are women in the book like that a woman who decides to pursue a career in government,

02:14:03.060 --> 02:14:07.460
[Guest]: despite the fact that her family just wants her to get married. I mean, marriage is the only thing

02:14:07.460 --> 02:14:11.940
[Guest]: that her family believes she can do with herself. And she believes actually, she can do accounts,

02:14:11.940 --> 02:14:16.420
[Guest]: and she can do government accounts, and she loves doing them. She finds such joy in them.

02:14:16.420 --> 02:14:20.980
[Guest]: I was actually just so moved. And I think I was privileged to just know her life because

02:14:21.780 --> 02:14:28.580
[Guest]: how much her immediate cousin's father just would ignore her professional achievements to the point

02:14:28.580 --> 02:14:32.340
[Guest]: that you know, she once said to me, and I write about this in the book that I would like to talk

02:14:32.340 --> 02:14:37.380
[Guest]: about what I'm doing at work, but everybody makes me feel like a bit of a show off if I do. So I

02:14:37.380 --> 02:14:42.020
[Guest]: just stay quiet. And we talk about Shah Rukh and films, right. And the other place in her life

02:14:42.020 --> 02:14:46.180
[Guest]: where these hidden taxes are playing out, Amit, is she's earning a lot of money, she's earning

02:14:46.180 --> 02:14:50.980
[Guest]: more money, in fact, than many of the other male cousins in her family are. She buys one of the

02:14:50.980 --> 02:14:56.180
[Guest]: cousins a bike, because you know, he needs it. And they hide the fact the family hides the fact

02:14:56.180 --> 02:15:00.980
[Guest]: that it was her and her money that it was a gift. And her family tells her No, if we announce that

02:15:00.980 --> 02:15:05.460
[Guest]: it was your gift, it won't look good that a girl is giving this gift, you know, the girl is

02:15:05.460 --> 02:15:11.380
[Guest]: essentially supporting financially. And so you make someone's successes feel so small. And I

02:15:11.380 --> 02:15:16.020
[Guest]: think she desperately in her life wanted someone. I actually think this is why she actually

02:15:16.020 --> 02:15:21.140
[Guest]: participated in my project. I really do believe this. I think she enjoyed talking to me because

02:15:21.140 --> 02:15:26.820
[Guest]: she felt that I was validating some of her decisions. Because I was a stranger. And I was

02:15:26.820 --> 02:15:32.100
[Guest]: a stranger who had certain credentials that she did respect. And she felt that she needed someone

02:15:32.100 --> 02:15:38.180
[Guest]: to tell her that valuing accounts over the marriage market was a valid way of being.

02:15:39.060 --> 02:15:42.180
[Guest]: And no one in her immediate family was doing that. And I think that's, again,

02:15:42.180 --> 02:15:46.820
[Guest]: sort of a hidden tax that is only and these are taxes that are only imposed in our interpersonal

02:15:46.820 --> 02:15:51.540
[Guest]: domain, right. And when it comes to I think, low income communities, you know, what we call the

02:15:51.540 --> 02:15:56.100
[Guest]: working class, then the taxes are hidden, but they're not that hidden, because it actually

02:15:56.100 --> 02:16:02.180
[Guest]: plays out as sheer violence. And it's in the book, where, when men start to drink, they are

02:16:02.180 --> 02:16:06.340
[Guest]: uncomfortable with women being out, there's this constant fear that she will run away with another

02:16:06.340 --> 02:16:12.820
[Guest]: man, a lot of mocking. And not only that, what's fascinating to me is even the largest labor unions

02:16:12.820 --> 02:16:18.260
[Guest]: in the world, I talked about this in the book, when they unionize, many of them want families,

02:16:18.260 --> 02:16:22.500
[Guest]: and perhaps sensibly so they want men and families to support the decisions that women are making.

02:16:22.500 --> 02:16:29.140
[Guest]: And in these communities, families are almost letting women work out of sheer dire need. So I

02:16:29.140 --> 02:16:33.780
[Guest]: think this goes back to that conversation of the income effect, right? So there's this big grudging,

02:16:33.780 --> 02:16:39.060
[Guest]: well, we let you go do this job, but we're not very comfortable. And we constantly watch you.

02:16:39.060 --> 02:16:44.260
[Guest]: And there's this constant surveillance. But I think there the taxes play out just very directly

02:16:44.260 --> 02:16:48.420
[Guest]: in economic taxes on women, how much they will earn if they don't have a man with them.

02:16:48.420 --> 02:16:51.860
[Guest]: You can't survive as a single female household, although one of the principal characters in my

02:16:51.860 --> 02:16:56.660
[Guest]: book does. And it's a really remarkable story of the sets of negotiations that she has to go

02:16:56.660 --> 02:17:01.220
[Guest]: through to do that, and how she earns her own money. And you have to negotiate violence. And

02:17:01.220 --> 02:17:05.860
[Guest]: violence was just seen as such an accepted way of life. And in some of these neighborhoods that I

02:17:05.860 --> 02:17:11.460
[Guest]: was visiting that I really didn't, I didn't know how to get my head around it. To be honest, I

02:17:11.460 --> 02:17:15.620
[Guest]: think the only way I could do it is to just write faithfully what was told to me without

02:17:15.620 --> 02:17:20.660
[Guest]: without adding my own analysis or adding anything that I had to say, because it was just so telling

02:17:20.660 --> 02:17:25.460
[Guest]: that it was just something you had to live with. Or if you chose to run walk out of your husband,

02:17:25.460 --> 02:17:30.260
[Guest]: you better have economic resources to walk out of a violent marriage. And I think just to end

02:17:30.260 --> 02:17:34.020
[Guest]: there, Amit, which is that yes, so these hidden taxes are playing out in different ways across

02:17:34.020 --> 02:17:41.140
[Guest]: class groups is that when we think of intimate relationships, we don't recognize that actually,

02:17:41.140 --> 02:17:48.180
[Guest]: so much of our economic decision making is occurring and being mediated through intimacy,

02:17:48.180 --> 02:17:52.020
[Guest]: right? Because you don't want to do things that your loved ones will not support you in doing.

02:17:53.060 --> 02:17:57.220
[Guest]: And one of the things I realized when I was talking to all these women was, you know,

02:17:57.220 --> 02:18:01.380
[Guest]: when we talk about gender discrimination, we're always talking about the other, right? So it's

02:18:01.380 --> 02:18:07.540
[Guest]: the bhakts, the dented, painted, no, all it's always the other. But I wrote this book out of

02:18:07.540 --> 02:18:11.140
[Guest]: this book out of the sheer frustration, because actually, I realized the problem is all with us,

02:18:11.140 --> 02:18:16.180
[Guest]: it's number one, what women as themselves can expect and will push themselves to expect from

02:18:16.180 --> 02:18:20.820
[Guest]: people, will you stand up for yourself? I mean, will you stand up for what you really want to do

02:18:20.820 --> 02:18:26.820
[Guest]: for yourself? And then in your daily lives, the people who claim to love you and who do love you,

02:18:26.820 --> 02:18:32.580
[Guest]: but you realize that in very strange ways, we're all very violent to each other and to ourselves.

02:18:32.580 --> 02:18:37.700
[Guest]: And that plays out in the way we're engaging with the market, because so many of the women

02:18:37.700 --> 02:18:41.220
[Guest]: just felt that they would not be supported if they decided to pursue what they professionally

02:18:41.220 --> 02:18:47.540
[Amit Varma]: wanted to pursue. So a couple of things struck me about what you just said. And one was the notions

02:18:47.540 --> 02:18:52.660
[Amit Varma]: of love that drive this. And the other was that you said that the accountant was actually happy

02:18:52.660 --> 02:18:58.180
[Amit Varma]: to speak to you, because in a sense, it gave her validation that the sort of things that she was

02:18:58.180 --> 02:19:02.900
[Amit Varma]: the sort of things that she was talking about, they were not unique to her, that they were valid,

02:19:02.900 --> 02:19:08.500
[Amit Varma]: they were legitimate. And that brings me to the question of how do we understand the world we live

02:19:08.500 --> 02:19:13.780
[Amit Varma]: in? Right? And you and I being elites, you know, growing up the way we did, you know, we're reading

02:19:13.780 --> 02:19:19.140
[Amit Varma]: a lot of books, we have access to the best media, all of that. We have so many ways to understand

02:19:19.140 --> 02:19:24.340
[Amit Varma]: the world so many ways to build frames of seeing, but not everyone is that privileged. In fact,

02:19:24.340 --> 02:19:29.380
[Amit Varma]: most of the country doesn't have access to most of those frames, for no fault of their own. And

02:19:29.380 --> 02:19:34.500
[Amit Varma]: that brought me to this quote of yours, where you write about love and how Hindi films show love,

02:19:34.500 --> 02:19:38.980
[Amit Varma]: where you write, quote, despite the intensity of their passions, you will never truly understand

02:19:38.980 --> 02:19:44.180
[Amit Varma]: why people in Hindi films love each other as much as they do. Love is youthful and naive and popular

02:19:44.180 --> 02:19:50.420
[Amit Varma]: Hindi cinema, it becomes an attribute or a noun, not an action or verb. In these images, it is an

02:19:50.420 --> 02:19:56.340
[Amit Varma]: innate immutable feeling within a person catalyzed by another not a series of ever changing interactions

02:19:56.340 --> 02:20:02.740
[Amit Varma]: between two ever changing people. In the standard Hindi film format, love usually leads to marriage

02:20:02.740 --> 02:20:08.740
[Amit Varma]: and sex, stop quote. And this is like you point out, it's a limited view of love. And it's

02:20:08.740 --> 02:20:14.740
[Amit Varma]: understandable if this view of love should prevail. Because that's it, that where are they getting

02:20:14.740 --> 02:20:18.660
[Amit Varma]: their knowledge of the world from they're getting their knowledge of the world from the limited

02:20:18.660 --> 02:20:23.940
[Amit Varma]: lived experience around them. And from Bollywood? Yes. Do you think that number one that this is

02:20:23.940 --> 02:20:28.020
[Amit Varma]: understated? And I wouldn't say that the causality goes one way, the causality may even go the other

02:20:28.020 --> 02:20:32.340
[Amit Varma]: way that films are, of course, a reflection of what society wants, and so on and so forth.

02:20:32.340 --> 02:20:39.140
[Amit Varma]: And it could become a vicious circle in that sense. But is this also why Shah Rukh in a sense,

02:20:39.140 --> 02:20:46.420
[Amit Varma]: Mr. Khan, in a sense, is it's so important that at least at some tiny levels in terms of being

02:20:46.420 --> 02:20:50.660
[Amit Varma]: kind to women and being in the kitchen and talking to them like they are normal people,

02:20:50.660 --> 02:20:55.780
[Guest]: he's a little bit of a step ahead? Yeah, I think two things. And this actually,

02:20:55.780 --> 02:21:00.500
[Guest]: funnily goes back to almost where we started, which was about power, right? And in fact,

02:21:00.500 --> 02:21:04.740
[Guest]: that line that you just quoted is heavily me thinking about the writers I was talking about

02:21:04.740 --> 02:21:08.260
[Guest]: in the beginning, be it Eric Fromm, people who theorize about love. And I think what's happened

02:21:08.260 --> 02:21:14.180
[Guest]: is, we've all become in sadly, commodities and love has become transactional. And I end the book

02:21:14.180 --> 02:21:18.900
[Guest]: essentially by saying that the reason why women in our country are so exhausted is because we're

02:21:18.900 --> 02:21:22.980
[Guest]: constantly hustling for love. I think men are hustling too. They're hustling probably much more

02:21:22.980 --> 02:21:27.300
[Guest]: for money than they are for love and for a kind of status that men are supposed to have. That's

02:21:27.300 --> 02:21:31.620
[Guest]: the script of masculinity. Women should have love and they're hustling for it, be it what they're

02:21:31.620 --> 02:21:36.820
[Guest]: doing to their bodies, the constant compromising, the constant negotiating, the constant settling,

02:21:36.820 --> 02:21:43.460
[Guest]: right? And in this current framework, love has become especially for men, and even within

02:21:43.460 --> 02:21:50.020
[Guest]: families has become power. So love is I control you. So I love you. I allow myself to be controlled

02:21:50.020 --> 02:21:55.700
[Guest]: by you. So I must love you as well. It's this very strange, codependent, power centric notion

02:21:55.700 --> 02:22:03.540
[Guest]: of what love is. And in that world, the love that we are seeing all these women seek, it's almost

02:22:03.540 --> 02:22:07.860
[Guest]: like they're being taxed for saying, well, I don't want that kind of love. I just want to love who I

02:22:07.860 --> 02:22:11.300
[Guest]: am at work. I love myself. In a way, that's actually what all these women are doing. They're

02:22:11.300 --> 02:22:14.820
[Guest]: choosing to love what they want to do with their bodies, their hearts, their minds. And I think Mr

02:22:14.820 --> 02:22:20.820
[Guest]: Khan is very powerful, because in a way, what he says is, you are fine the way you are, I will love

02:22:20.820 --> 02:22:28.580
[Guest]: you the way you are. And by women finding money and their own free time to watch something that

02:22:28.580 --> 02:22:33.780
[Guest]: gives them pleasure, which is Mr. Khan, they are saying I love myself. So it's both, right? So it's

02:22:33.780 --> 02:22:38.260
[Guest]: yes, you're right, which is that it's his imagery of being in the kitchen, talking to women,

02:22:38.260 --> 02:22:43.220
[Guest]: listening to them. But also fandom being an economic act, the fact that these women are

02:22:43.220 --> 02:22:47.700
[Guest]: spending money the way they want to, to see something that they want to, to see an actor

02:22:47.700 --> 02:22:52.500
[Guest]: that they enjoy watching. It's also a way for them to say, well, it doesn't matter what my family

02:22:52.500 --> 02:22:56.900
[Guest]: thinks. And many families, as you know, are very uncomfortable with fandom for Mr. Khan,

02:22:56.900 --> 02:23:02.100
[Guest]: because it signals all these things about female sexuality, and people think it's silly. But the

02:23:02.100 --> 02:23:05.780
[Guest]: fact that these women just said, well, to hell with it, we want to just watch him and we will,

02:23:05.780 --> 02:23:09.940
[Guest]: it was also an act of self love. So it's both. And I think that's why he's important.

02:23:09.940 --> 02:23:16.420
[Guest]: On the broader conversation around, you know, where are we in the state of love? And I write

02:23:16.420 --> 02:23:20.660
[Guest]: about this, which is, I think, the one place where the economy or economics should not be,

02:23:21.220 --> 02:23:25.460
[Guest]: we now have become all hyper rational economists when it comes to love, I actually, I write about

02:23:25.460 --> 02:23:31.540
[Guest]: this. And what I mean by that is, we are constantly loving people conditioning it based on what it

02:23:31.540 --> 02:23:35.540
[Guest]: does for our welfare. That is actually now what the state of love not only in our country,

02:23:35.540 --> 02:23:41.620
[Guest]: I think globally has become. And we love people for the parties they take us to, we love people

02:23:41.620 --> 02:23:48.500
[Guest]: for what their body signals about us. We love people for status, we love people based on CVs,

02:23:48.500 --> 02:23:53.060
[Guest]: we love people for all these, there are lots of conditionalities, we love people if you behave a

02:23:53.060 --> 02:23:57.460
[Guest]: certain way. And I think for the women in the book, all of them were being told, we will love

02:23:57.460 --> 02:24:03.860
[Guest]: you more as families, as men, as husbands, as fathers, mothers, whoever, if you conform to

02:24:03.860 --> 02:24:08.900
[Guest]: this script of womanhood, that is acceptable to us, which is you either, you know, you don't go

02:24:08.900 --> 02:24:13.700
[Guest]: work outside for so many hours, you may be work an hour, but mostly you spend your time on ritual,

02:24:14.420 --> 02:24:20.340
[Guest]: on on caregiving, on marrying someone that we tell you to marry. And all of these women

02:24:20.340 --> 02:24:26.820
[Guest]: are victims of this new kind of conditional commoditized culture of love, where they are

02:24:26.820 --> 02:24:32.180
[Guest]: constantly being told you have to behave a certain way to earn it. And, and if you don't,

02:24:32.180 --> 02:24:36.900
[Guest]: your own worth is questioned. And so you feel bad about yourself and you feel bad about the

02:24:36.900 --> 02:24:41.940
[Guest]: shape of love that you're receiving. And I think Mr. Khan, there's this kind of existential

02:24:41.940 --> 02:24:45.460
[Guest]: loneliness, honestly, Amit, and you know, philosophers have been talking about this

02:24:45.460 --> 02:24:49.220
[Guest]: forever. But I think it's become very acute. And it's very acute in the stories in the book,

02:24:49.220 --> 02:24:53.860
[Guest]: because these are truly women on the surface, you would think it's a very banal thing to just

02:24:53.860 --> 02:24:58.580
[Guest]: want to watch a movie want to just go and you know, giggle at an actor want a mobile phone

02:24:58.580 --> 02:25:02.340
[Guest]: want a job. It sounds very like there's nothing revolutionary about any of this.

02:25:03.140 --> 02:25:07.060
[Guest]: But what I realized when you actually start to listen and pay attention to these stories is

02:25:07.060 --> 02:25:12.740
[Guest]: each one of them is essentially saying we are not happy with this current culture of love that

02:25:12.740 --> 02:25:18.420
[Guest]: expects us to constantly condition ourselves a certain way and behave in certain ways to deserve

02:25:18.420 --> 02:25:22.580
[Guest]: love. We should just be loved irrespective. We should be loved for who we are and what we want

02:25:22.580 --> 02:25:27.780
[Guest]: to do. And we shouldn't be taxed for it. And so I think there is an existential loneliness in our

02:25:27.780 --> 02:25:33.700
[Guest]: culture right now. And different cultures then find different ways of dealing with it. The women

02:25:33.700 --> 02:25:39.540
[Guest]: I follow, including myself, turn to Mr. Khan as sort of relief as respite. And then we also turn

02:25:39.540 --> 02:25:44.100
[Guest]: to ourselves. And we're trying to navigate this culture right now that we have in this crisis of

02:25:44.100 --> 02:25:50.500
[Guest]: love. And he then because of his imagery is a great conduit and a foil for that, right. But

02:25:50.500 --> 02:25:55.140
[Guest]: there are others who would turn to some other forms of art, I do believe I think this is actually

02:25:55.140 --> 02:25:59.380
[Guest]: the function of art, given that we have just destroyed the state of love to the point that

02:25:59.380 --> 02:26:04.180
[Guest]: I don't know where we recover, where we recover that concept from, to the point that, you know,

02:26:04.180 --> 02:26:08.260
[Guest]: so many people will tell me with the only place which is, you know, pure love is between mother

02:26:08.260 --> 02:26:12.980
[Guest]: and the offspring. But even there, I would contend, it's look at what's happening, it's again

02:26:12.980 --> 02:26:17.300
[Guest]: becomes so conditional, you behave, you are successful x way, I love you a certain way,

02:26:17.300 --> 02:26:23.140
[Guest]: I love you based on x, y, z. And I think all of us just want an out from that. So some people

02:26:23.140 --> 02:26:29.140
[Guest]: listen to Beethoven, and some people watch Mr. Khan. And I think the book is essentially a study

02:26:29.140 --> 02:26:35.860
[Guest]: of that existential loneliness that this culture of hustling for love is creating. And sadly,

02:26:35.860 --> 02:26:40.420
[Guest]: the economy is not helping. In some cases, it does, because there are stories that actually

02:26:40.420 --> 02:26:44.820
[Guest]: what happens when you say, well, I will just create my own community. So there's a character

02:26:44.820 --> 02:26:49.060
[Guest]: in the book called gold, who's an in-flight attendant, who runs away from her family,

02:26:49.060 --> 02:26:53.300
[Guest]: because she realizes that they will never love her for who she really is. And she decides that she's

02:26:53.300 --> 02:26:57.540
[Guest]: just going to go do what she wants to do. She feels extremely lonely. I think it's one of the

02:26:57.540 --> 02:27:01.140
[Guest]: chapters a lot of people have told me I've had calls from people saying that they've cried while

02:27:01.140 --> 02:27:04.980
[Guest]: they've reading it, because it is a I can sense it. And I think it's because of the way she told

02:27:04.980 --> 02:27:08.980
[Guest]: the stories to me and my relationship with her. We have, we were very close and we are very close.

02:27:09.620 --> 02:27:15.060
[Guest]: And I think that when you see her story, what's happening is there the job, the service sector,

02:27:15.060 --> 02:27:19.380
[Guest]: the fact that these jobs opened up and they were very well paying. She works for an airline,

02:27:19.380 --> 02:27:23.700
[Guest]: which is a good recruiter, they are, you know, good about social security, she feels

02:27:24.500 --> 02:27:30.420
[Guest]: stable somewhat. And as a consequence, she's able to love herself. And so the economy can help in

02:27:30.420 --> 02:27:34.740
[Guest]: funny ways, right? Like you a job can help you love yourself and your family won't, you'll feel

02:27:34.740 --> 02:27:38.820
[Guest]: meaningful there. You might meet someone through your job who will make you feel loved, you may

02:27:38.820 --> 02:27:43.860
[Guest]: feel loved. I mentioned this in the book being an aid manager for files than an unpaid manager

02:27:43.860 --> 02:27:48.740
[Guest]: of dishes in your family. But I think each of the women is just responding to this culture of

02:27:48.740 --> 02:27:53.620
[Guest]: constantly having to haggle for love. And I call it laveria. I mean, this is a new kind of laveria

02:27:53.620 --> 02:27:59.380
[Guest]: that we have right now, not Shah Rukh's laveria. And I think the solution to that is part escape,

02:27:59.380 --> 02:28:04.340
[Guest]: which Mr. Khan provides the women in the book, and partly it's yourself and resolve within.

02:28:04.340 --> 02:28:07.460
[Guest]: And I think each one of the women is just demonstrating that in her own ways.

02:28:08.020 --> 02:28:11.940
[Amit Varma]: So before we get back to the economics, one more question about love. But before that,

02:28:11.940 --> 02:28:16.500
[Amit Varma]: an aside, you mentioned that even the love between a mother and a child may not be quite so pure. So

02:28:16.500 --> 02:28:22.100
[Amit Varma]: I recorded a superb episode with Mrinal Pandey yesterday, which will probably release after this

02:28:22.100 --> 02:28:27.060
[Amit Varma]: because it's more timeless. But there's this little snippet from her book, which I read out and we

02:28:27.060 --> 02:28:32.580
[Amit Varma]: discussed that where she talks about how she was with a bunch of her woman friends. And they read

02:28:32.580 --> 02:28:37.300
[Amit Varma]: this news piece about this mother who murdered her third born or fourth born in the hospital

02:28:37.300 --> 02:28:42.420
[Amit Varma]: after giving birth. And then she and all her friends started discussing whether they ever

02:28:42.420 --> 02:28:48.020
[Amit Varma]: felt like that. And each of them was confessing that, man, there was a time when I really wanted

02:28:48.020 --> 02:28:52.660
[Amit Varma]: to murder my child, each of them. And just today morning before coming to the recording,

02:28:52.660 --> 02:28:57.380
[Amit Varma]: I was discussing this with one of my hosts where I'm staying in Delhi. And she said that, yeah,

02:28:57.380 --> 02:29:02.820
[Amit Varma]: that there was a time where at one point, my mother-in-law and I looked at each other.

02:29:02.820 --> 02:29:05.860
[Amit Varma]: And she said to me, you feel like throwing him in the dustbin, don't you?

02:29:05.860 --> 02:29:09.540
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, she said, yeah, I do. Yeah. So but my question about love is this,

02:29:09.540 --> 02:29:13.220
[Amit Varma]: which is a difficult question, because I couldn't possibly answer it. So it's unfair. But I wonder

02:29:13.220 --> 02:29:17.700
[Amit Varma]: what you think of it. And it's a two part question, which is that you spoke about how the nature of

02:29:17.700 --> 02:29:23.780
[Amit Varma]: love is changing and we love for different reasons. So number one, is love always transactional?

02:29:23.780 --> 02:29:29.620
[Amit Varma]: And number two, the second part to that is that if so, is it then the case that all

02:29:30.260 --> 02:29:34.580
[Amit Varma]: we are aspiring towards is changing the nature of that transaction?

02:29:34.580 --> 02:29:40.740
[Guest]: I think it depends on what you actually think is the end goal of love, to be honest,

02:29:40.740 --> 02:29:45.460
[Guest]: I mean, if there is an end goal. So for instance, you know, there's a body of work,

02:29:45.460 --> 02:29:50.420
[Guest]: which is religion, right, which just says that we should love all I mean, in a very funny way.

02:29:51.060 --> 02:29:55.700
[Guest]: And then it tells you that there is this one, you know, way of loving and it's very prescriptive.

02:29:55.700 --> 02:29:59.860
[Guest]: So in a way, in fact, people, why do people love religion, they love religion, because it gives

02:29:59.860 --> 02:30:04.580
[Guest]: them very clear markers of how to live. And if you live x way, you will be loved, right, you will be

02:30:04.580 --> 02:30:09.140
[Guest]: loved by someone or the other mystical forces, people around you, the structures of religion,

02:30:09.140 --> 02:30:15.220
[Guest]: I think families have their own versions of that. One of the most horrifying pieces of art I saw

02:30:15.220 --> 02:30:21.460
[Guest]: recently was this documentary on the murders in Delhi, where it was the Burari killings, I think,

02:30:21.460 --> 02:30:26.580
[Guest]: if I'm not mistaken, it's a Netflix documentary. The name is escaping me. But essentially, it was

02:30:26.580 --> 02:30:30.980
[Guest]: essentially the family was following an occult practice where they believed the male head was

02:30:31.940 --> 02:30:37.220
[Guest]: channeling the dead father or patriarch. And then at some point, they basically committed mass

02:30:37.220 --> 02:30:42.580
[Guest]: suicide. And it is a horrifying, stunning documentary. But if you watch it, one of the

02:30:42.580 --> 02:30:46.180
[Guest]: things you realize is that even in families, what was the structure, the structure was,

02:30:46.180 --> 02:30:50.340
[Guest]: if you adhere to this belief, we will all love you, and we will take care of each other, right.

02:30:50.340 --> 02:30:57.460
[Guest]: So if the point of all of this is material security, feeling stable economically, which

02:30:57.460 --> 02:31:02.180
[Guest]: we should remember in our country, which is so economically harsh for most is a very important

02:31:02.180 --> 02:31:07.380
[Guest]: goal to have, then in that case, love will always be transactional. So it's it's linked to our

02:31:07.380 --> 02:31:12.740
[Guest]: finally into our economic circumstances, right? Because the more difficult life is materially,

02:31:13.380 --> 02:31:19.300
[Guest]: how will you then move beyond a transactional love because you're always tied to having to

02:31:19.300 --> 02:31:24.260
[Guest]: find love so that someone will take care of you when the state and market won't right now.

02:31:24.260 --> 02:31:28.980
[Guest]: And I think that's a comment on where we are. I think there's another kind of love,

02:31:28.980 --> 02:31:34.820
[Guest]: which perhaps operates amongst people who have those privileges of certainties, right,

02:31:34.820 --> 02:31:40.660
[Guest]: that they can life can be stable people like me, where then I think the real question you have to

02:31:40.660 --> 02:31:45.700
[Guest]: ask yourself is, it's a question of, you know, if you want love, which is a love that helps you grow

02:31:45.700 --> 02:31:49.380
[Guest]: as a person and as a person who then is a sentient being in the world,

02:31:50.180 --> 02:31:54.900
[Guest]: then marriage is perhaps not the way perhaps for that, you know, that you may have to then

02:31:54.900 --> 02:31:59.380
[Guest]: explore very different ways of living your life. I mean, and I don't I don't know whether being

02:31:59.380 --> 02:32:03.460
[Guest]: single is a way to do that, but I think there are different ways people can come to that.

02:32:03.460 --> 02:32:08.820
[Guest]: But I do think that what's happening in our current culture is that we have really conflated

02:32:08.820 --> 02:32:14.900
[Guest]: even amongst the elites who have the privilege of certainties. We have completely conflated love

02:32:14.900 --> 02:32:23.380
[Guest]: with this idea of power, of status. I think Amiya Srinivasan has this and it's just a wonderful

02:32:23.380 --> 02:32:28.580
[Guest]: book of essays, Right to Sex, I think everybody must read it. She says that are our desires

02:32:28.580 --> 02:32:34.100
[Guest]: mutable? Are we constantly just mirroring what society wants us to aspire for? Or are we able

02:32:34.100 --> 02:32:38.980
[Guest]: to actually disengage and think critically for ourselves? And her answers are not a little bleak,

02:32:38.980 --> 02:32:43.060
[Guest]: because actually what you realize is that we're all so socialized. But I think that's changing.

02:32:43.060 --> 02:32:46.900
[Guest]: I mean, you look at, you know, the queer movements, non-binary people, I think people are

02:32:46.900 --> 02:32:53.620
[Guest]: questioning scripts of love and what love entails. But I would argue, Amit, and maybe it is a bit

02:32:53.620 --> 02:32:58.660
[Guest]: depressing to say it, and I hate to be the, I don't want to be gloomy, but I want to just say,

02:32:58.660 --> 02:33:03.540
[Guest]: this is actually a fact. As long as our country continues to be as unequal in the economy works

02:33:03.540 --> 02:33:08.340
[Guest]: the way it does, where most people in the country live lives of complete uncertainty and you need

02:33:08.340 --> 02:33:13.380
[Guest]: and you need material security, particularly women, because they cannot be materially secure

02:33:13.380 --> 02:33:18.740
[Guest]: on their own, love will be transactional, because you will constantly rely in interpersonal

02:33:18.740 --> 02:33:23.700
[Guest]: dimensions, you will constantly need people to love you to feel secure materially. And then

02:33:23.700 --> 02:33:28.020
[Guest]: within that, there's, of course, fantasy and escape. And that's a very different kind of,

02:33:28.020 --> 02:33:32.900
[Guest]: you know, love, you love yourself in that fantasy, you find love in odd kinds of fantasies,

02:33:32.900 --> 02:33:37.780
[Guest]: everybody daydreams, it doesn't matter which economic echelon you come from. So I guess my

02:33:37.780 --> 02:33:43.300
[Guest]: answer to you is, love will be transactional, depending on one's material security, and love

02:33:43.300 --> 02:33:49.380
[Guest]: will be transactional as long as we conflate it with the status game. And I think we need to take

02:33:49.380 --> 02:33:55.380
[Guest]: a deep, hard look at our own personal preferences. And I, in the book, I'm very transparent about

02:33:55.380 --> 02:34:01.540
[Guest]: this. Why was I involved with someone who essentially was, you know, had more status,

02:34:01.540 --> 02:34:05.940
[Guest]: he signaled something about me in the book, The Gentleman I Call The One, he signaled something

02:34:05.940 --> 02:34:10.820
[Guest]: about me. So he made me feel good in that very transactional way. And at the end of the chapter,

02:34:10.820 --> 02:34:14.420
[Guest]: I actually write this, you know, he just became a prize, right? For me, I mean, it felt like,

02:34:14.420 --> 02:34:18.820
[Guest]: well, I didn't feel worthy. So now I'm with this person. So now maybe I'll feel better about

02:34:18.820 --> 02:34:24.340
[Guest]: myself. And then I had to do the really hard work of just keeping myself company and figuring out

02:34:24.340 --> 02:34:29.780
[Guest]: what kind of love do I want on my own terms. And I think the more we start to take a step back and

02:34:29.780 --> 02:34:34.660
[Guest]: think a bit critically about those preferences, as opposed to entering the rat race for status,

02:34:34.660 --> 02:34:38.180
[Guest]: which is often conflated with love as well. I think until that happens, I don't think things

02:34:38.180 --> 02:34:42.820
[Guest]: will change too much for this transactional nature of love. So that's my long philosophical.

02:34:43.380 --> 02:34:46.980
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, but you call yourself gloomy. I object to that because everything is relative. You're

02:34:46.980 --> 02:34:50.900
[Amit Varma]: sitting in a room with me right now. No one can be gloomier than me. Like earlier when

02:34:50.900 --> 02:34:55.860
[Amit Varma]: you were talking about how women, you know, seek meaning from say a job, a job can make their life

02:34:55.860 --> 02:34:59.700
[Amit Varma]: seem meaningful when family doesn't. And I was just thinking to myself that life is basically

02:34:59.700 --> 02:35:04.980
[Amit Varma]: meaningless. We all know that we are just choosing our own illusion. So perhaps we're hunting for a

02:35:04.980 --> 02:35:09.300
[Guest]: better. Yeah, no, that's one philosophy. And that's a way of looking at life. And then there's

02:35:09.300 --> 02:35:14.020
[Guest]: another way, which is well, even in all that churn, and you construct meaning. Yeah, you've

02:35:14.020 --> 02:35:18.020
[Guest]: got to assume there is meaning even if there is none. Yeah, no, I mean, or that meaning is

02:35:18.020 --> 02:35:23.300
[Guest]: something it's for you, right? And I think that, and it's fine. I think people will find that in

02:35:23.300 --> 02:35:29.860
[Guest]: their own ways. And that's okay. What I guess I'm worried about when I talk to younger women,

02:35:29.860 --> 02:35:36.900
[Guest]: and even women in their 30s and 40s, is that I really think that we have this and I actually

02:35:36.900 --> 02:35:41.220
[Guest]: write about this in the book when I talk about the upper class mating market that it sometimes

02:35:41.220 --> 02:35:46.900
[Guest]: feels like you have this world of men with unwarranted self confidence and women with

02:35:46.900 --> 02:35:52.740
[Guest]: unwarranted self doubt. I mean, amid the mental health crisis that love is creating for women,

02:35:52.740 --> 02:35:57.220
[Guest]: and I get into this a little bit in parts of the book is remarkable. And I'm sure that there is a

02:35:57.220 --> 02:36:01.860
[Guest]: corollary to this for men as well. It's just not something that I've studied, particularly,

02:36:01.860 --> 02:36:06.740
[Guest]: and there are people who will, and I'm very curious about, but the women I speak to,

02:36:06.740 --> 02:36:10.900
[Guest]: because they find this meaning, they've constructed this meaning out of these gender scripts around

02:36:10.900 --> 02:36:15.380
[Guest]: love and a certain kind of heteronormative. I mean, the book starts with the line that my life

02:36:15.380 --> 02:36:20.340
[Guest]: is heteronormative. Hell, this is a very heteronormative take of what love is and marriage.

02:36:20.340 --> 02:36:23.860
[Guest]: And there are people like Paramita Vohra, I was recently on a panel with her, and she basically

02:36:23.860 --> 02:36:27.940
[Guest]: said on this panel was about love and sexuality. And she essentially said that, you know, until

02:36:27.940 --> 02:36:33.700
[Guest]: marriage is just not as an institution, we just don't dismiss it. This is just going to be the

02:36:33.700 --> 02:36:38.260
[Guest]: way it is. But we are we do live in the reality that currently we live in, I can't dive off a,

02:36:38.260 --> 02:36:42.180
[Guest]: you know, a deep end where we live in completely different constructed realities. Right now,

02:36:42.180 --> 02:36:46.660
[Guest]: we live in a life where there is a tyranny of marriage in the way women's lives are organized.

02:36:46.660 --> 02:36:51.540
[Guest]: Some of us try and resist it. I mean, I don't expect that of everyone, because people may find

02:36:51.540 --> 02:36:57.860
[Guest]: meaning. But given that these women find meaning in marriage, motherhood, love, given that just

02:36:57.860 --> 02:37:04.980
[Guest]: the sheer onus, the burden, the harassment and abuse that all of that is generating. I don't

02:37:04.980 --> 02:37:10.020
[Guest]: know whether men, I'm sure men are feeling cut up as well. But I just don't see it as,

02:37:10.660 --> 02:37:15.380
[Guest]: at least amongst the elite. I just see a bunch of men feeling very good about themselves and

02:37:15.380 --> 02:37:20.820
[Guest]: then pretending to be brash when I think they're just trying to cover up insecurities. And I don't

02:37:20.820 --> 02:37:25.540
[Guest]: think they suffer as much in love as I think women are right now. But that's my contention.

02:37:26.100 --> 02:37:29.540
[Amit Varma]: Okay, I'm allowed one dad joke per episode. Go for it. Here's my one,

02:37:29.540 --> 02:37:35.300
[Amit Varma]: that if the one was actually cut up, what would it be? You know the answer. Come on.

02:37:35.300 --> 02:37:37.540
[Amit Varma]: Two. The two. Anyway,

02:37:37.540 --> 02:37:43.620
[Guest]: so actually depends on how much you cut him up. Although because he gave me, he allowed me to

02:37:43.620 --> 02:37:50.660
[Guest]: write about this, I would not want to be cut up. Okay, we'll spare him the cutting up. And I love

02:37:50.660 --> 02:37:55.780
[Amit Varma]: that sentence of yours about how the upper class mating market seem neatly divided between males

02:37:55.780 --> 02:38:00.580
[Amit Varma]: with unwarranted self-confidence and females with unwarranted self-doubt, which is superb.

02:38:00.580 --> 02:38:06.420
[Amit Varma]: And our mutual friend Shruti Rajagopalan once put up this cartoon on Twitter of there is this man

02:38:06.420 --> 02:38:10.980
[Amit Varma]: sitting with a woman and telling her, let me interrupt your expertise with my confidence.

02:38:10.980 --> 02:38:15.940
[Guest]: Of course, exactly. And you know, Amit, my God, I write about it in a very sort of

02:38:15.940 --> 02:38:20.340
[Guest]: trying to be light in touch when I write about it. But people get very angry when this happens.

02:38:20.340 --> 02:38:26.500
[Guest]: I know women who've been on dates and told your business idea is foolish. Your, you know,

02:38:26.500 --> 02:38:34.020
[Guest]: what are you doing? Leave your job. From men who barely have jobs. And all the sort of, you know,

02:38:34.020 --> 02:38:38.900
[Guest]: and of course, there's the converse of that, which I absolutely abhor, which is anytime a woman is

02:38:38.900 --> 02:38:43.860
[Guest]: getting ahead and she has male mentors, oh, there must be something funny going on between the two

02:38:43.860 --> 02:38:49.460
[Guest]: of them. Like this constant scrutiny of female success. I just don't see male success ever

02:38:49.460 --> 02:38:55.620
[Guest]: scrutinised in that manner. It might be scrutinised a bit the way, you know, about nepotism, but not

02:38:55.620 --> 02:38:59.460
[Guest]: in like questioning a person's character, right? You inherit something from your family, you

02:38:59.460 --> 02:39:04.500
[Guest]: inherited, men do and women do, all of us do. But women's success, especially when they're then

02:39:04.500 --> 02:39:09.940
[Guest]: showing up in romantic encounters, the kind of nonsense that you just have to deal with. And

02:39:09.940 --> 02:39:16.500
[Guest]: I think, you know, in 2021, surely this should be retired. But it isn't. I do believe, Amit,

02:39:16.500 --> 02:39:22.340
[Guest]: we are in a crisis of, there is a deeply wounded masculinity because, and in fact, Mr. Khan's

02:39:22.340 --> 02:39:27.460
[Guest]: films recently seem to echo that, you know, he's playing these really narcissistic men who are

02:39:27.460 --> 02:39:33.060
[Guest]: very worried about the fact that they've fallen for women who have higher status than him. And I

02:39:33.060 --> 02:39:38.020
[Guest]: think my sense is when I talk to all these women in the upper class mating market, the stories that

02:39:38.020 --> 02:39:42.980
[Guest]: are in the book, my own experience is that I think men are yet to actually adapt to the fact that

02:39:42.980 --> 02:39:47.060
[Guest]: there is now this new generation of extremely confident women who can do potentially without

02:39:47.060 --> 02:39:50.900
[Guest]: them. Because again, the economy has allowed them to do so because their parents have done well,

02:39:51.460 --> 02:39:56.100
[Guest]: they may be able to find land to just live on their own in small enclaves, it might be possible

02:39:56.100 --> 02:40:02.100
[Guest]: for you to live as a single woman. And the fact that these women are very vociferous about what

02:40:02.100 --> 02:40:08.260
[Guest]: they expect from men, I think is a big shift. And I think men are still struggling en masse to be

02:40:08.260 --> 02:40:12.660
[Guest]: able to deal with that. And I think the stories in the book are illustrating that a bit.

02:40:13.300 --> 02:40:16.820
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, I read an interesting essay, I'll try and link that if I can find the link from the

02:40:16.820 --> 02:40:22.740
[Amit Varma]: show notes about how, you know, this has actually been measured this crisis in confidence among

02:40:22.740 --> 02:40:26.420
[Unknown]: women. Like I think there was some study where, you know, within an organization,

02:40:26.420 --> 02:40:31.380
[Amit Varma]: people were asked to apply for a particular position. And there were 10 prerequisites for it.

02:40:31.380 --> 02:40:36.900
[Amit Varma]: And no woman applied unless she met all 10. But men, if they met even six of them,

02:40:36.900 --> 02:40:43.140
[Amit Varma]: happily, they are applying. And the gap just keeps on increasing as this kind of happens.

02:40:43.140 --> 02:40:48.180
[Guest]: And in fact, Amit, I would contend that this in the romantic area, I mean, you're talking about

02:40:48.180 --> 02:40:52.580
[Guest]: the professional arena. In the romantic arena, this is even more remarkable, because I write

02:40:52.580 --> 02:40:57.940
[Guest]: about, you know, supermodels being made to feel bad by, you know, men. I don't want to make comments

02:40:57.940 --> 02:41:02.580
[Guest]: on the way people's physical appearances are, but like a man giving a supermodel a hard time about

02:41:02.580 --> 02:41:04.900
[Amit Varma]: You wrote it in his book, he was 5 foot 2.

02:41:04.900 --> 02:41:11.460
[Guest]: Yeah, this is for people. And then it's, it's just remarkable to me, the confidence with which

02:41:11.460 --> 02:41:16.500
[Guest]: so many men and this I will, I will keep, of course, nuancing this, which is this is men very

02:41:16.500 --> 02:41:23.140
[Guest]: much typically upper caste, upper class, I can't say what's going on in sort of different communities,

02:41:23.140 --> 02:41:28.900
[Guest]: I'm looking forward to books that do and research that does. But the mating market that I know so

02:41:28.900 --> 02:41:34.260
[Guest]: intimately well, and the mating market that gold, one of the characters in the book is occupying,

02:41:35.300 --> 02:41:40.100
[Guest]: it's a men's market. And it's quite remarkable that it's a men's market. I think Mukul Kesavan

02:41:40.100 --> 02:41:45.300
[Guest]: had that hilarious essay, right about the ugliness of the Indian male. I would actually I think John

02:41:45.300 --> 02:41:49.780
[Guest]: Abraham has has ended that because he was talking about the ugliness of the Indian actors relative

02:41:49.780 --> 02:41:55.700
[Guest]: to a Madhuri Dixit or so on. But I think once now men in movies are actually probably as sort of

02:41:55.700 --> 02:41:59.700
[Guest]: aesthetically pleasing as objects as well as women, I think they're now quite equal.

02:41:59.700 --> 02:42:04.020
[Amit Varma]: But Indian men are actually much worse looking than Indian women. It is true, right?

02:42:04.020 --> 02:42:07.540
[Guest]: I'm not going to I'm not going to participate in that claim because Shah Rukh Khan is an Indian

02:42:07.540 --> 02:42:13.220
[Amit Varma]: man. So he's an outlier. But I you know, I don't want this is this is actually this is not the kind

02:42:13.220 --> 02:42:19.140
[Guest]: of statistic. I will not adhere to or abide by, I would believe in a complexity here. But what I

02:42:19.140 --> 02:42:24.100
[Guest]: will say is that the confidence is quite remarkable. And the lack of confidence that girls are growing

02:42:24.100 --> 02:42:29.940
[Guest]: up with is just something that, you know, and I face it, all the women in the book face it,

02:42:29.940 --> 02:42:34.740
[Guest]: you're constantly made to feel unsure about knowing yourself. And, you know, we were we

02:42:34.740 --> 02:42:38.100
[Guest]: started this conversation, we're talking about people who hide from themselves, right.

02:42:38.900 --> 02:42:47.700
[Guest]: And I think women are almost socialized as they're growing up to hide from their own desires,

02:42:47.700 --> 02:42:54.340
[Guest]: conform to a script that will earn them security status survival. And that takes very different

02:42:54.340 --> 02:43:00.260
[Guest]: shapes based on where you are and your circumstances. It really worries me that

02:43:00.260 --> 02:43:06.580
[Guest]: this is now unfortunately, this crisis of confidence is just it seems to just get compounded

02:43:06.580 --> 02:43:12.020
[Guest]: professionally and romantically. There are studies that measure depression rates and

02:43:12.660 --> 02:43:16.980
[Guest]: suicide rates amongst women. And there's some India has one of the global highs when it comes

02:43:16.980 --> 02:43:21.940
[Guest]: to some of this, and I quote some of the data in the book, and it's a tough one to crack through

02:43:21.940 --> 02:43:26.100
[Guest]: policy. I think that's where I'm really struggling when I hear these stories. And

02:43:26.660 --> 02:43:30.660
[Guest]: I think the book is essentially trying to communicate these experiences to just a larger

02:43:30.660 --> 02:43:36.500
[Guest]: public. But then how do you start to resolve them is think is a very tricky ask, because I think a

02:43:36.500 --> 02:43:43.540
[Guest]: lot of it will perhaps require women to exit some of the structures that are incentivizing them to

02:43:43.540 --> 02:43:48.980
[Guest]: just conform. And I don't know whether the economy and public space currently will allow for that.

02:43:49.700 --> 02:43:53.700
[Amit Varma]: So I have, again, a deeper question coming from this observation about,

02:43:53.700 --> 02:43:59.300
[Amit Varma]: you know, in your book, you made this observation about how you went to talk with a bunch of women,

02:43:59.300 --> 02:44:03.220
[Amit Varma]: but they weren't saying anything, and they were all clammed up, and there were men around. But

02:44:03.220 --> 02:44:07.620
[Amit Varma]: when the men leave, then they start talking, which indicates that there was one persona they

02:44:07.620 --> 02:44:11.780
[Amit Varma]: were maintaining that was socially acceptable in that milieu. And the moment they found that they

02:44:11.780 --> 02:44:18.100
[Amit Varma]: could speak, they spoke. But it also seems to me that some of them would have become the persona

02:44:18.100 --> 02:44:23.780
[Amit Varma]: in the way a mask can become a face. Yeah, right. And so, in your experience, how much does that

02:44:23.780 --> 02:44:29.620
[Amit Varma]: happen? Like how much? Like, on the one hand, I can see some people kind of internalizing all of

02:44:29.620 --> 02:44:33.700
[Amit Varma]: this. So they also believe it's okay, they don't have an issue with it that he was right to hit me,

02:44:33.700 --> 02:44:38.340
[Amit Varma]: I must have done something wrong. Or, you know, my husband works for the family, I must spend all day

02:44:38.340 --> 02:44:42.820
[Amit Varma]: cooking good food for him, and all of those things. But on the other hand, there would be

02:44:42.820 --> 02:44:47.940
[Amit Varma]: people who realize that they are trapped, and this is what it is. And they live in Thoreau's words,

02:44:47.940 --> 02:44:52.500
[Amit Varma]: lives of quiet desperation. So you know, which of these you think is more prevalent? Are they all

02:44:52.500 --> 02:44:57.700
[Guest]: true? They're all true. Although what I have noticed, based on just the stories I know,

02:44:57.700 --> 02:45:01.780
[Guest]: and the people I've met, I'm not going to make more of a generalized statement beyond that.

02:45:02.340 --> 02:45:06.180
[Guest]: What I have noticed is that there is a class distinction here. I noticed anytime you talk

02:45:06.180 --> 02:45:13.460
[Guest]: about a Me Too case, anytime you talk about men treating women poorly, I noticed that

02:45:13.460 --> 02:45:19.060
[Guest]: upper class women tend to be much quicker to apologize and explain for men sometimes.

02:45:20.340 --> 02:45:25.300
[Guest]: In that there's a lot of internalized misogyny, the boys will be boys, a little bit of bullying,

02:45:25.300 --> 02:45:28.900
[Guest]: and I actually mentioned this. And in fact, sometimes Mr. Khan's characters himself,

02:45:28.900 --> 02:45:32.900
[Guest]: and certainly the characters Ranbir Kapoor's plays, all of them are like this, which is they're

02:45:32.900 --> 02:45:39.780
[Guest]: all these so seemingly charming men. But actually, they're just man children who need to be coddled

02:45:39.780 --> 02:45:46.020
[Guest]: and constantly validated and their narcissism needs to be encouraged and cultured in a way.

02:45:46.020 --> 02:45:50.020
[Guest]: And women that are constantly in these movies playing the burden of someone who will do that

02:45:50.020 --> 02:45:54.500
[Guest]: for these men. There's a scene which I mentioned in the book, which is in Ae Dil Hai Mushkil,

02:45:54.500 --> 02:45:57.860
[Guest]: which by the way, is one of my favorite Hindi films. I actually love that film.

02:45:57.860 --> 02:46:01.860
[Guest]: Ranbir Kapoor was just fantastic in it. But you know, there's a scene between him and this

02:46:01.860 --> 02:46:06.580
[Guest]: stunning Aishwarya Rai. And they've had this encounter, they've slept together. And then

02:46:06.580 --> 02:46:10.180
[Guest]: the next morning, I think they're trying to figure out where they stand. And you know,

02:46:10.180 --> 02:46:14.020
[Guest]: he asks for her poetry, because he's a musician, she says, sure. And then she turns to him and she

02:46:14.020 --> 02:46:17.380
[Guest]: says, well, if I give you your poetry, and I get you, you know, you're sort of recovering from a

02:46:17.380 --> 02:46:22.980
[Guest]: heartache, and I'm helping you with that. What do I get in return being with you? And he pulls

02:46:22.980 --> 02:46:29.460
[Guest]: her towards himself and says, am I not enough? And I think what's happening is this am I not

02:46:29.460 --> 02:46:33.860
[Guest]: enough is seen as charming amongst upper class women that oh, this is a confident man, how you

02:46:33.860 --> 02:46:38.420
[Guest]: know, there's a kind of man who's considered charming, right amongst some of us. And actually,

02:46:38.420 --> 02:46:43.860
[Guest]: if you look at him closely, he's a bully and a child. You see this a lot. I mean, hushed whispers,

02:46:43.860 --> 02:46:47.300
[Guest]: anytime you talk about a Me Too case in India, you will notice there are lots of hushed whispers

02:46:47.300 --> 02:46:52.260
[Guest]: coming from women who will say, well, you know, maybe the guy was misunderstood, all that nonsense.

02:46:52.980 --> 02:46:57.540
[Guest]: I have no patience for that. And I noticed that amongst largely upper class women, I wonder if

02:46:57.540 --> 02:47:03.220
[Guest]: that's because upper class men hold so much power, money and prestige that women are locked into

02:47:03.220 --> 02:47:08.260
[Guest]: those networks. And then the internalised misogyny is even higher. I wonder if there's an economics

02:47:08.260 --> 02:47:12.660
[Guest]: of this as well could be some people who write about it say that there is, but in working class

02:47:12.660 --> 02:47:19.700
[Guest]: communities, Amit, I actually noticed much stronger will and desire amongst the women I know,

02:47:19.700 --> 02:47:26.980
[Guest]: to fight, to fight against anytime a woman is told, you know, your place is at the home or

02:47:26.980 --> 02:47:32.660
[Guest]: is made to feel inferior. One of my favourite quotes in the book is the daughter of a domestic

02:47:32.660 --> 02:47:39.140
[Guest]: worker. The domestic worker's name is Sandhya in the book. She's Bengali, loves Shah Rukh. Her

02:47:39.140 --> 02:47:43.300
[Guest]: story in the book is about how she basically buys a television so she can watch Shah Rukh all the

02:47:43.300 --> 02:47:47.700
[Guest]: time. And her daughter said to me, her daughter loves Shah Rukh, but she really loves Priyanka

02:47:47.700 --> 02:47:52.900
[Guest]: Chopra. And when I asked her, so what do you like about her? And we were talking about her.

02:47:53.460 --> 02:47:58.580
[Guest]: She said to me, she said, Well, did you see that she married a foreigner? And she married a foreigner

02:47:58.580 --> 02:48:04.500
[Guest]: because no Indian man would ever be okay with a girl as successful as her. And so you see this is

02:48:04.500 --> 02:48:11.220
[Guest]: the first generation girl who's gone to school speaks English in her family, living in the slums

02:48:11.220 --> 02:48:17.780
[Guest]: of Delhi, growing up, actively articulating and very much encouraged by her mother, because these

02:48:17.780 --> 02:48:21.380
[Guest]: are intergenerational things. She's learning all of this, because also what she's seeing around her,

02:48:22.100 --> 02:48:27.300
[Guest]: that men are not supportive, and one should talk about that. And she is criticising her brother,

02:48:27.300 --> 02:48:34.900
[Guest]: she's an agentic being. And I wonder if it's because they're the gains from being associated

02:48:34.900 --> 02:48:39.940
[Guest]: with a male prestige network are actually low now, because men, how much security can men now

02:48:39.940 --> 02:48:44.260
[Guest]: provide you in the current labour market that we have amongst working class communities where jobs

02:48:44.260 --> 02:48:50.740
[Guest]: are so insecure? I often wonder if this internalised misogyny and almost coddling this

02:48:51.620 --> 02:48:58.420
[Guest]: child of a man who treats women really poorly and is abusive to women. I wonder if the desire that

02:48:58.420 --> 02:49:02.660
[Guest]: I've noticed to sort of coddle to this man and call him charming amongst the upper classes is

02:49:02.660 --> 02:49:07.780
[Guest]: because of the economics of it, because there is there are gains of material security there.

02:49:07.780 --> 02:49:12.100
[Guest]: Whereas I think in working class communities where everyone now is in this economic churn,

02:49:12.980 --> 02:49:19.300
[Guest]: I wonder if now women are out there speaking out a lot more because beyond physical safety,

02:49:19.300 --> 02:49:24.100
[Guest]: which if you can negotiate for yourself somehow through communities, through brothers,

02:49:24.100 --> 02:49:28.900
[Guest]: through other kinds of families, maybe you can speak out more because now the gains of sticking

02:49:28.900 --> 02:49:35.300
[Guest]: with a man in some circumstances are not as high. And this goes back to why I think women in jobs

02:49:35.300 --> 02:49:41.140
[Guest]: is such a critical policy issue, because actually we don't realise it, but women in the economy will

02:49:41.140 --> 02:49:46.340
[Guest]: start to fundamentally alter all of these dynamics around love, how you feel about yourself,

02:49:46.900 --> 02:49:51.700
[Guest]: how masculinity has to reform, because then women standing on their own two feet can critique

02:49:51.700 --> 02:49:58.100
[Guest]: credibly so and can exit harmful relationships and can censure men when men need to be censured.

02:49:58.740 --> 02:50:02.420
[Guest]: Right now, I think the economy is not fully allowing for that. And of course, as you said,

02:50:02.420 --> 02:50:07.060
[Guest]: the economy is a subset of society is not allowing for that. But I think if the economy starts to

02:50:07.060 --> 02:50:12.340
[Guest]: shift, if we had a world in which we suddenly said, and this is a radical notion that I really

02:50:12.340 --> 02:50:17.940
[Guest]: abide by, which is that in some jobs were just for women, what would happen then? Because then

02:50:17.940 --> 02:50:22.020
[Guest]: families would have to adapt, men would have to adapt, right? This is a thought experiment. I

02:50:22.020 --> 02:50:25.700
[Guest]: think about things like that. And I think that that would then change the terms of intimacy,

02:50:25.700 --> 02:50:29.780
[Guest]: it would change the terms of that would trigger social change, right? So I think to answer your

02:50:29.780 --> 02:50:35.700
[Guest]: question, I felt that this mask and this internalization, I found it much more amongst

02:50:35.700 --> 02:50:40.660
[Guest]: upper class women where I think that the economic incentive to do so is very strong.

02:50:40.660 --> 02:50:44.100
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, I agree with you. But I'm wondering if there's a selection bias in play, because obviously

02:50:44.100 --> 02:50:48.500
[Amit Varma]: the first people who come to mind are the sort of upper class Delhi liberals who jumped to the

02:50:48.500 --> 02:50:54.260
[Amit Varma]: defense of Mahmood Faruqi and Tarun Tejpal and all of those and one immediately thinks of them.

02:50:54.260 --> 02:50:58.580
[Amit Varma]: A couple of questions arise from this. And this is really I think we started digressing eight

02:50:58.580 --> 02:51:03.860
[Amit Varma]: questions ago. So, you know, eventually maybe we'll come round back to the economy and gender,

02:51:03.860 --> 02:51:07.940
[Amit Varma]: which I will eventually come back to. But a couple of interesting digressions and

02:51:09.380 --> 02:51:17.220
[Amit Varma]: one is this whole question of adulthood that is anyone truly adult? Like one thing I have

02:51:17.220 --> 02:51:23.300
[Amit Varma]: kind of realized is that, you know, I don't know where I read it, but I agree with it completely,

02:51:23.300 --> 02:51:28.020
[Amit Varma]: which is that no one's ever really an adult, we're all just winging it. Right? And you wing

02:51:28.020 --> 02:51:33.220
[Amit Varma]: it in different ways. It's like I think one of the people you spoke to, you know, encountered

02:51:33.220 --> 02:51:38.580
[Amit Varma]: someone when she was in her 30s. And this person said to her, oh, you're still a fan of Shah Rukh

02:51:38.580 --> 02:51:41.780
[Unknown]: Khan. What shit is this? I thought you would outgrow that. Yeah. And it's like, why should

02:51:41.780 --> 02:51:48.100
[Amit Varma]: you outgrow anything? And equally, all these men who are behaving like big babies, and part of the

02:51:48.100 --> 02:51:54.020
[Amit Varma]: reason is probably intellectually still big babies. So do you think there's something to that? Do you

02:51:54.020 --> 02:52:00.020
[Amit Varma]: think that, you know, this whole notion of, and this is, of course, not related at all to your

02:52:00.020 --> 02:52:05.300
[Amit Varma]: book or to India, but just in general, that, you know, do we misunderstand adulthood at all? Should

02:52:05.300 --> 02:52:10.500
[Amit Varma]: we just embrace the fact that we are all struggling to understand and figure shit out and we don't

02:52:10.500 --> 02:52:18.100
[Guest]: need to pretend? Yes. But I think that, to me, adulthood is, I sort of see it somewhat differently.

02:52:18.100 --> 02:52:24.740
[Guest]: I think of adulthood as this phase in your life where you can no longer blame anybody else for the

02:52:24.740 --> 02:52:30.740
[Guest]: choices you've made. And I think the reason why we call some men babies or even some women babies

02:52:31.700 --> 02:52:35.860
[Guest]: is that everything that's happening to them is always someone else's fault. You will never hold

02:52:35.860 --> 02:52:39.700
[Guest]: yourself accountable for what you have done, right? And the circumstances in your life. And to me,

02:52:39.700 --> 02:52:45.140
[Guest]: adulthood is a milestone, perhaps a philosophical one, a psychological one, whatever you'd like to

02:52:45.140 --> 02:52:49.140
[Guest]: call it. I don't think it's a ritual. I don't think it's 18 and you're an adult. I think I

02:52:49.140 --> 02:52:54.340
[Guest]: became an adult when I started to just own up for my own choices, right? To own and hold myself

02:52:54.340 --> 02:52:58.420
[Guest]: accountable for them, for my own wellbeing, as opposed to constantly thinking it was because

02:52:58.420 --> 02:53:03.220
[Guest]: of my boyfriend or my father or, you know, these other circumstances. Yes, of course, they shape

02:53:03.780 --> 02:53:08.340
[Guest]: what is happening to you, but you are playing some role in it. And I think to me, that is

02:53:08.340 --> 02:53:16.660
[Guest]: adulthood. And I think going to that, I feel that we live in a world particularly co-created by men

02:53:16.660 --> 02:53:21.220
[Guest]: and women, where I think women are, and anthropologists call this the patriarchal

02:53:21.220 --> 02:53:27.380
[Guest]: bargain. Essentially, the idea is that because women know that they need to make sure men love

02:53:27.380 --> 02:53:32.020
[Guest]: them enough that they will always take care of them, be it as a son, be it as a husband,

02:53:32.020 --> 02:53:37.460
[Guest]: that there is this mollycoddling of men done by women, and women are complicit in it,

02:53:38.420 --> 02:53:44.340
[Guest]: where essentially, the man is never really accountable. The woman barely holds him

02:53:44.340 --> 02:53:47.540
[Guest]: accountable for his own choices. It's always, oh, you know, something happened at office,

02:53:47.540 --> 02:53:51.860
[Guest]: someone else has done something. And so much family drama, if you look at television shows,

02:53:51.860 --> 02:53:56.980
[Guest]: right? What is all that family drama showing you? It's showing you scripts of how women will

02:53:56.980 --> 02:54:02.420
[Guest]: constantly make excuses for men, because they want to maintain a decent term of relationship,

02:54:02.420 --> 02:54:07.700
[Guest]: so that when they're elderly, or when things are bad, a man is insurance, marriage is insurance,

02:54:07.700 --> 02:54:13.060
[Guest]: right? Now, in that world, do we ever expect anyone to be adult in the way I defined it,

02:54:13.060 --> 02:54:17.060
[Guest]: where you will hold yourself accountable? I don't think so. I don't think the social

02:54:17.060 --> 02:54:22.900
[Guest]: terms of it will sustain. And I think for women, it's a strange thing, because you're

02:54:22.900 --> 02:54:28.660
[Guest]: seeing, you always see yourself in this constant relationship of dependence and overt dependence,

02:54:28.660 --> 02:54:34.420
[Guest]: it's not interdependence, it's not an equal dependence, you will invariably then hold

02:54:34.420 --> 02:54:39.940
[Guest]: this other person responsible for your welfare, right? So we do have an equilibrium of big babies,

02:54:39.940 --> 02:54:44.820
[Guest]: because our social structures, because of the way particularly the family is set up,

02:54:45.540 --> 02:54:50.180
[Guest]: and the way resources and land in particular is set up, it's still in male name. I mean,

02:54:50.180 --> 02:54:54.100
[Guest]: while the Supreme Court has made these changes, they're still yet to be fully adhered to and

02:54:54.100 --> 02:54:58.820
[Guest]: families have all kinds of ways. I have people in my own family who are taking cousins to court,

02:54:58.820 --> 02:55:03.300
[Guest]: because the land is in the woman's name suddenly, and then people are fighting about it, right?

02:55:03.300 --> 02:55:09.860
[Guest]: This happens a lot. And essentially, till you don't start changing, I hate to sound like a

02:55:09.860 --> 02:55:15.380
[Guest]: good old Bengali communist, but but I guess this is where I will end up where if you don't change

02:55:15.380 --> 02:55:22.420
[Guest]: the terms of land asset distribution, how in the world we continue to have these terms of overt

02:55:22.420 --> 02:55:27.940
[Guest]: dependence, men will be mollycoddled, women will constantly rely on men for welfare. And we will

02:55:27.940 --> 02:55:33.940
[Guest]: have an equilibrium of babies. And I think we're seeing that look at our politics, it is a politics

02:55:33.940 --> 02:55:39.060
[Guest]: of big babies pretending to be big men. I think that adulthood, that whole notion of holding

02:55:39.060 --> 02:55:43.060
[Guest]: yourself accountable will only happen when you feel that, you know, these terms of dependence

02:55:43.060 --> 02:55:48.420
[Guest]: are changing, but that's yet to happen. Yeah, I love your definition of adulthood,

02:55:48.420 --> 02:55:52.340
[Amit Varma]: though it is so narrow that very few people fit, but it's better than mine, because I was,

02:55:52.340 --> 02:55:57.140
[Amit Varma]: I was practically saying no one can be. So go back to my next question.

02:55:58.020 --> 02:56:02.580
[Guest]: I will say one thing, though, which is that, you know, I think the way you meant adulthood in one

02:56:02.580 --> 02:56:08.020
[Guest]: way when you were talking about it in the context of Shahrukh, is that there's this like delight

02:56:08.020 --> 02:56:14.260
[Guest]: and joy when you're a child, right? There's the delight of wonder, and just, just delight. And

02:56:14.260 --> 02:56:20.020
[Guest]: there's such freedom in that. And to me, that's not, that's not a child. I mean, I think all of

02:56:20.020 --> 02:56:24.580
[Guest]: us, even into our 40s, we should be delighted, we should be living lives where we are doing things,

02:56:24.580 --> 02:56:29.380
[Guest]: and we are with people who delight us. I think it's very important. And one of the reasons why

02:56:29.380 --> 02:56:34.500
[Guest]: I think I was able to sustain this project is because Mr. Khan delights me, and I am able to

02:56:34.500 --> 02:56:39.620
[Guest]: hold on to that aspect, what you would probably call the child within us. I just think of it as

02:56:39.620 --> 02:56:43.780
[Guest]: part of, you know, you can be an adult and still have those sources of complete wonderment and

02:56:43.780 --> 02:56:48.340
[Guest]: delight. So I do agree with you when you say, I think if I understood you correctly, there is a

02:56:48.340 --> 02:56:54.820
[Guest]: part of this one being curious about the world, being open eyed, being open to experiences,

02:56:54.820 --> 02:56:58.260
[Guest]: which I don't think we should only associate with childhood. I think, you know, you can enter

02:56:58.260 --> 02:57:01.700
[Guest]: adulthood and still have that. But we need to nurture that now.

02:57:01.700 --> 02:57:06.500
[Amit Varma]: No, one, I agree with the delight part of it also. I mean, one of the things I kind of realized as I

02:57:06.500 --> 02:57:10.340
[Amit Varma]: went through middle age is that, you know, what brings you happiness is a small joys.

02:57:10.340 --> 02:57:11.780
[Guest]: Yes. Right. That's it. Exactly.

02:57:11.780 --> 02:57:16.340
[Amit Varma]: That basic delight. But I think what I also meant by adulthood was that there is this notion that

02:57:16.340 --> 02:57:22.100
[Amit Varma]: an adult has stuff figured out. Right. And therefore, that leads to this sense of people

02:57:22.100 --> 02:57:26.420
[Amit Varma]: posturing that they have everything figured out at false confidence, which actually men have so

02:57:26.420 --> 02:57:31.860
[Amit Varma]: much more of. And that at many levels to me is toxic because nobody has anything figured out.

02:57:31.860 --> 02:57:37.460
[Amit Varma]: The world is complex. And when we behave like we have things figured out, our certainties lead us

02:57:37.460 --> 02:57:43.460
[Amit Varma]: to be judgmental about the world. And a lot of the delight then diminishes. Because I think we can

02:57:43.460 --> 02:57:48.820
[Amit Varma]: find delight in every other human being because from every person, we have so much to learn.

02:57:48.820 --> 02:57:54.100
[Amit Varma]: But if you're always putting labels on them or tags on them or othering them or whatever,

02:57:54.100 --> 02:57:56.580
[Amit Varma]: then just so much is lost. And that's so tragic.

02:57:56.580 --> 02:57:59.380
[Guest]: But, you know, actually, it's fascinating to hear you say this. And I never thought

02:57:59.380 --> 02:58:03.380
[Guest]: about it this way, which is that often when I was telling people that I was working on

02:58:03.380 --> 02:58:08.100
[Guest]: this book project about women who gush about an actor and what that tells us about society,

02:58:08.900 --> 02:58:12.660
[Guest]: everybody gave me this really puzzled look. And then they said, but what is this?

02:58:12.660 --> 02:58:17.060
[Guest]: This is a child's work. Somebody actually told me it's a child's work. What are you doing?

02:58:17.060 --> 02:58:22.180
[Guest]: I think this actually goes to what you were trying to say, which is that I don't think

02:58:22.180 --> 02:58:27.060
[Guest]: I would have been able to attempt the book or these conversations if I just assumed that I

02:58:27.060 --> 02:58:32.500
[Guest]: knew this feminist text and I knew what the scripts of life were and I've got this figured out.

02:58:32.500 --> 02:58:36.580
[Guest]: I think maybe because of heartache, because of Mr. Khan, because of multiple experiences,

02:58:36.580 --> 02:58:41.060
[Guest]: sometimes heartache opens you up in a funny way. You're just open to, in the tradition of all

02:58:41.060 --> 02:58:45.060
[Guest]: lonely people, you want to find wisdom and comfort in the lives and experiences of others.

02:58:45.060 --> 02:58:49.220
[Guest]: So you're very open to the lives of others. And I think in a way, actually, that's what

02:58:49.220 --> 02:58:55.140
[Guest]: fandom is. It's this, you know, unambiguously adoring someone in our current civilization of

02:58:55.140 --> 02:59:00.900
[Guest]: cynicism and this ironic distance that all of us are supposed to maintain amongst each other.

02:59:00.900 --> 02:59:05.140
[Guest]: To say that I absolutely love someone and I don't know them, but I really love what they do.

02:59:05.140 --> 02:59:09.140
[Guest]: It's childish to many people. And I know that sometimes when people react to what I'm trying

02:59:09.140 --> 02:59:12.420
[Guest]: to do with the book, I could sense that that was initially, you know, sometimes a reaction,

02:59:12.420 --> 02:59:15.460
[Guest]: I guess. So I completely agree with you, Amit, I think on what you were trying to say.

02:59:15.460 --> 02:59:21.380
[Guest]: I just, I guess what I feel is that we have now, and I think this is going back to that notion of

02:59:21.940 --> 02:59:26.900
[Guest]: particularly around the masculine, for men to say they don't know something and for men to say that

02:59:26.900 --> 02:59:30.820
[Guest]: they don't have it all together. In fact, women are allowed to break down. In fact, women are

02:59:30.820 --> 02:59:34.660
[Guest]: encouraged to break down sometimes because you should not fully know yourself. You should be

02:59:34.660 --> 02:59:40.980
[Guest]: a bit scattered, that damsel in distress kind of, you know, that dynamic. But men being saying that

02:59:40.980 --> 02:59:45.940
[Guest]: we don't have this, I think that goes back to that crisis of the masculine, right? That you

02:59:45.940 --> 02:59:51.700
[Guest]: are supposed to have it all figured out. So I hear you and I agree with you. And I'm glad that at

02:59:51.700 --> 02:59:56.500
[Guest]: least as a woman, I'm allowed a little bit of space to be foolish. And I think society is

02:59:56.500 --> 03:00:00.500
[Guest]: comfortable with foolish women. In fact, we like it when girls are a little sort of, you know,

03:00:00.500 --> 03:00:05.940
[Guest]: like that. But I think had I not been a little foolish and a bit open, this line of inquiry

03:00:05.940 --> 03:00:10.020
[Guest]: would never have happened. And it's such a seminal project for my life. And I wouldn't have been able

03:00:10.020 --> 03:00:14.100
[Amit Varma]: to do it. And I just... No, thank you for being foolish. And I would encourage all my listeners

03:00:14.100 --> 03:00:19.060
[Amit Varma]: to be similarly foolish and go down these roads. Let's get back to serious subjects now. Those

03:00:19.060 --> 03:00:23.700
[Amit Varma]: serious but fascinating. So in your book about the accountant, you had this sort of fascinating

03:00:23.700 --> 03:00:28.180
[Amit Varma]: story where she talks about how when she was in her second year of college, she goes to see

03:00:28.180 --> 03:00:32.900
[Amit Varma]: Mohabbatein. And the thing is, she wins some money in a college academic competition. And she buys a

03:00:32.900 --> 03:00:38.260
[Amit Varma]: ticket for the film with that. Then she's being dropped home by a friend and her brother. And her

03:00:38.260 --> 03:00:42.820
[Amit Varma]: parents are so pissed off when they see her that they slap her. And one of the things they are more

03:00:42.820 --> 03:00:48.180
[Amit Varma]: in, of course, pissed off that she went out in a public space. And they're also pissed off that

03:00:48.180 --> 03:00:54.100
[Amit Varma]: she spent the money on something as frivolous as a film. And this was, it's one of those moments

03:00:54.100 --> 03:00:58.660
[Amit Varma]: where in all my privilege and my kind of good luck, I have to kind of sit back and think about

03:00:58.660 --> 03:01:03.620
[Amit Varma]: this for a moment, that the money that you win from an academic competition that goes to buy a

03:01:03.620 --> 03:01:08.740
[Amit Varma]: film theatre ticket can actually be so significant for people that your parents are saying, why the

03:01:08.740 --> 03:01:12.900
[Guest]: hell are you wasting this on whatever? Yeah. And it wouldn't have been more than 300 400 bucks.

03:01:13.540 --> 03:01:19.700
[Guest]: It was around 1000. But whatever. I mean, come on. Yeah, yeah. That's one thing. And speaking

03:01:19.700 --> 03:01:25.380
[Amit Varma]: of public spaces later in the chapter, you write quote, India is busy modernizing for its men.

03:01:25.380 --> 03:01:30.340
[Amit Varma]: Women occupy a different experience. As per the India Human Development Survey in 2012,

03:01:30.340 --> 03:01:36.580
[Amit Varma]: 80% of India Indian women need approval from a family member to go outside the home to visit a

03:01:36.580 --> 03:01:41.060
[Amit Varma]: health center. Three out of five women need permission to visit the local grocery store.

03:01:41.060 --> 03:01:48.020
[Amit Varma]: In 2015, only 47% of urban women could go on chaperone to a public space. Even within loving

03:01:48.020 --> 03:01:52.500
[Amit Varma]: families, women are always made to account for what they do, where they go, what they eat,

03:01:52.500 --> 03:01:59.300
[Amit Varma]: and who they see, stop quote. And a little later, you then write quote, claiming comfort in public

03:01:59.300 --> 03:02:04.660
[Amit Varma]: space being at ease with one's body in the company of strangers remains an everlasting hurdle for

03:02:04.660 --> 03:02:09.780
[Amit Varma]: Indian women. According to a large scale survey by Save the Children in 2018. Three in every five

03:02:09.780 --> 03:02:14.980
[Amit Varma]: adolescent girls felt unsafe in crowded spaces. One in four feared being abducted, physically

03:02:14.980 --> 03:02:20.100
[Amit Varma]: assaulted or even raped. If she ventured outside a home. Two out of three adolescent girls were

03:02:20.100 --> 03:02:24.500
[Amit Varma]: worried about being verbally abused, stalked or being inappropriately touched in public.

03:02:24.500 --> 03:02:30.580
[Amit Varma]: In urban areas, 41% of adolescent girls felt unsafe in local markets, while nearly half feared

03:02:30.580 --> 03:02:36.500
[Amit Varma]: using public transport. Only a third of urban women dared to venture out to local markets alone,

03:02:36.500 --> 03:02:42.980
[Amit Varma]: stop quote. And I just found it important to read this out because most men simply do not get this.

03:02:42.980 --> 03:02:48.340
[Amit Varma]: Like I keep saying that, you know, until a few years ago, I did not realize the experience for

03:02:48.340 --> 03:02:54.100
[Amit Varma]: women in public was so different. I can walk out at midnight and I can go for a walk and it's cool.

03:02:54.100 --> 03:02:58.820
[Amit Varma]: I can enter a lift and not have to see who are the other five people in it. It's it's just

03:02:58.820 --> 03:03:03.780
[Amit Varma]: completely different. Tell me a little bit about what you have seen of this and how much do you

03:03:03.780 --> 03:03:10.820
[Amit Varma]: think this is also not just the whole the social pressures in the way our society is, but also a

03:03:10.820 --> 03:03:15.700
[Amit Varma]: failure of the state and providing a rule of law and how much do they feed into each other and why

03:03:15.700 --> 03:03:20.740
[Amit Varma]: don't do we not take it more seriously because it is women and their places in their home anyway.

03:03:20.740 --> 03:03:26.900
[Guest]: Amit, let me start by saying that I'm quite disillusioned with the political will behind

03:03:26.900 --> 03:03:33.380
[Guest]: these issues. I mean, even in states that talk a very progressive talk, we're yet to see money,

03:03:34.100 --> 03:03:40.180
[Guest]: sustained implementation focus on this. I'm still hopeful, but I'm tired of waiting, I think,

03:03:40.180 --> 03:03:44.420
[Guest]: for the state. You know, Urvashi Batalia in the book said to me that all the gains that women have

03:03:44.420 --> 03:03:49.460
[Guest]: had, they've grabbed them and then they've held on to them. And I think that might actually have

03:03:49.460 --> 03:03:53.220
[Guest]: to this is what's probably going to end up happening to public space. It's going to be a

03:03:53.220 --> 03:03:58.580
[Guest]: social movement more than the state that will make things change. Public space played a very

03:03:58.580 --> 03:04:03.460
[Guest]: interesting role in the book. I had not expected it to come up as much when we were talking about

03:04:03.460 --> 03:04:06.980
[Guest]: watching Mr. Khan's films. You know, typically the first thing that would come up is I don't

03:04:06.980 --> 03:04:10.980
[Guest]: have money and all of that and I don't have free time to watch a movie that I want to.

03:04:10.980 --> 03:04:15.060
[Guest]: My brother or my husband might. So I won't go. Then a lot of women started telling me these

03:04:15.060 --> 03:04:19.700
[Guest]: stories about and in fact, the accountant is not the only one to receive censure to go to a cinema

03:04:19.700 --> 03:04:24.020
[Guest]: hall on her own. There's another set of characters in the book who also face similar things.

03:04:24.980 --> 03:04:32.740
[Guest]: The cinema hall is seen as a place for masculine leisure, where men take their crude desires.

03:04:33.540 --> 03:04:39.700
[Guest]: For a woman to be occupying the cinema hall is quite remarkable and unusual. And there's a study

03:04:39.700 --> 03:04:47.060
[Guest]: by Ormax, which Film Companion had published, essentially saying that six out of 10 people

03:04:47.060 --> 03:04:54.660
[Guest]: in a cinema hall are men. And so the cinema hall is a masculine space. And I recognize that for

03:04:54.660 --> 03:04:58.500
[Guest]: many people who are listening to us right now, that's a bit odd, because that's, you know,

03:04:58.500 --> 03:05:02.340
[Guest]: people like you and me, I go to the cinema hall alone. And I actually mentioned this in the book.

03:05:02.340 --> 03:05:06.420
[Guest]: And it's so interesting to me because I start the book by being in a cinema hall with someone else

03:05:06.420 --> 03:05:10.820
[Guest]: who's of my own class background. And for us, a cinema hall is actually a place for a woman to

03:05:10.820 --> 03:05:15.060
[Guest]: just, you know, ease up, it's dark, you watch Shah Rukh, it's like, you know, it's your star

03:05:15.060 --> 03:05:20.260
[Guest]: gazing, it's lovely. For all the other women in the book, I started to realize as I was talking

03:05:20.260 --> 03:05:24.660
[Guest]: to them and hearing their stories, accessing something that seems so innocuous to me,

03:05:24.660 --> 03:05:29.700
[Guest]: like a cinema hall is so ridiculously tough, because it is seen as a place of male sleaze,

03:05:29.700 --> 03:05:36.980
[Guest]: largely, and men go there. And also this social sanction of women spending on leisure, how why

03:05:36.980 --> 03:05:42.180
[Guest]: are you spending on things that are fun and frivolous, you should save that money for the

03:05:42.180 --> 03:05:48.340
[Guest]: good of your family and for other kinds of things, right. And so public space came up in very unusual

03:05:48.340 --> 03:05:54.100
[Guest]: ways in the book that even to access fun, you have to access public space. And if public space

03:05:54.100 --> 03:05:59.780
[Guest]: is so uncomfortable with women occupying it, if we think of public space is actually a being,

03:05:59.780 --> 03:06:05.860
[Guest]: right? How in the world are women going to have fun? And I think the data bears this out. And I

03:06:05.860 --> 03:06:12.420
[Guest]: think when it comes to solutions, I don't think the solution is going to come sadly from courts

03:06:12.420 --> 03:06:17.140
[Guest]: and judges that seem to be as patriarchal and worried about, you know, the hetero not what is

03:06:17.140 --> 03:06:21.620
[Guest]: in the normative way that women behave and all this kind of rubbish that's coming out of courts,

03:06:21.620 --> 03:06:28.420
[Guest]: particularly lower courts. And I'm not expecting to be perfectly honest, big scale changes coming

03:06:28.420 --> 03:06:34.900
[Guest]: from the police on its own. I think what will start to happen is as and we're seeing this in

03:06:34.900 --> 03:06:39.780
[Guest]: some places. So the south is safer for women. Why? Because women are out and about much more,

03:06:39.780 --> 03:06:44.340
[Guest]: they're out for work, they're out for ritual, they're out to collect grains, they're out just

03:06:44.340 --> 03:06:48.580
[Guest]: participating in public space, treating it a certain way. This is true also of Southeast Asia.

03:06:48.580 --> 03:06:53.140
[Guest]: There is no reason why that cannot be true of the north. I don't think you know, people saying is

03:06:53.140 --> 03:06:57.780
[Guest]: the north immutable to change? No, I mean, there are parts of Delhi that have changed, in fact,

03:06:57.780 --> 03:07:02.500
[Guest]: where I do see women being out and about much more than they used to in the past. And then as women

03:07:02.500 --> 03:07:07.380
[Guest]: are out and about, then the rule of law, the state will have to it's almost, you know, this demand

03:07:07.380 --> 03:07:13.780
[Guest]: and supply equation, right? As people start to occupy space, then authorities and legal structures

03:07:13.780 --> 03:07:19.220
[Guest]: will have to then start to accommodate the needs and shifts that that involves. Right now we have

03:07:19.220 --> 03:07:24.500
[Guest]: this odd equilibrium where using the language of safety, and Naila Kabir, in fact, who's

03:07:24.500 --> 03:07:29.060
[Guest]: interviewed in the book says this, that she says using the language of safety, we just want to

03:07:29.060 --> 03:07:34.180
[Guest]: shackle women. We use that language to say, well, you don't go out because it's so unsafe.

03:07:35.140 --> 03:07:40.900
[Guest]: And I think a lot of women, including myself, would risk being out. I take walks at midnight

03:07:40.900 --> 03:07:44.740
[Guest]: and there are movements, right? I'm forgetting the name, but there are movements about

03:07:44.740 --> 03:07:50.020
[Guest]: occupying space in India, about being out on streets, women, just large groups of women.

03:07:50.020 --> 03:07:54.820
[Guest]: I remember after the mass, I mean, in India, only we have things like mob molestation. I mean,

03:07:54.820 --> 03:07:59.220
[Guest]: and that term, I'm quite certain has come up first, you know, in South Asia, India. Now we saw

03:07:59.220 --> 03:08:05.700
[Guest]: cases in Pakistan. The mob molestation in Bangalore, I remember one year during the New Year

03:08:05.700 --> 03:08:10.500
[Guest]: celebrations on a very crowded, popular street in the city. I forget which street, Amit, but

03:08:11.380 --> 03:08:15.940
[Guest]: immediately after that, there was a whole group of civil society organizations and just women,

03:08:15.940 --> 03:08:21.060
[Guest]: regular women just saying, no, this is our city. We will walk the streets. And so my hope when it

03:08:21.060 --> 03:08:28.020
[Guest]: comes to public safety and public spaces is not from institutions of governance. I think it's from

03:08:28.020 --> 03:08:36.340
[Guest]: women themselves. And there again, my hope is as markets open late, as jobs maybe trigger women to

03:08:36.340 --> 03:08:42.420
[Guest]: be out and about more, the dynamic of that public space will start to shift as well. And I think

03:08:42.420 --> 03:08:47.540
[Guest]: that's where my feeling, looking at the data, knowing what I know about what's happening in

03:08:47.540 --> 03:08:52.820
[Guest]: the economy and in society broadly, I think here I would actually rely much more on communities

03:08:52.820 --> 03:08:57.460
[Guest]: and communities of women who will come out and occupy space. And then I think in response to

03:08:57.460 --> 03:09:01.860
[Guest]: that, then structures will have to react and accommodate that.

03:09:02.420 --> 03:09:07.220
[Amit Varma]: I think one movement I recall from a decade and a half ago to reclaim public spaces for women was

03:09:07.220 --> 03:09:09.540
[Amit Varma]: by Jasmeen Patheja of the Blank Noise Project.

03:09:09.540 --> 03:09:12.340
[Guest]: Yes, that's right. Yes, that's exactly. Yes, that's. And, you know, there's,

03:09:12.340 --> 03:09:16.580
[Guest]: I think there's a wonderful book also called Why Loiter, which is written by Shilpa Bhatke.

03:09:17.380 --> 03:09:24.660
[Guest]: And so when I look at what's going on, I think this is where I really think consumption,

03:09:24.660 --> 03:09:30.660
[Guest]: the consumer economy, the market can really play a huge role in shifting social norms, because

03:09:31.220 --> 03:09:37.860
[Guest]: if women are out and about taking taxis or are out and about, yes, there will be cases of violence.

03:09:37.860 --> 03:09:43.700
[Guest]: It's very unfortunate. And then the state will be called upon to essentially do what is right

03:09:43.700 --> 03:09:48.180
[Guest]: and what is required. And I think in India, the current track record of the state and

03:09:48.180 --> 03:09:54.980
[Guest]: responding to those claims is quite abysmal. But my view really is that there must be places

03:09:54.980 --> 03:09:59.380
[Guest]: and there are, I've seen them, which you do not hear about in the news, maybe because things are

03:09:59.380 --> 03:10:03.300
[Guest]: not going grotesquely wrong there, where suddenly women are occupying more space.

03:10:03.300 --> 03:10:08.820
[Guest]: It could be fish markets in Bengal. It could be coastal communities in Odisha. I've seen them

03:10:08.820 --> 03:10:12.420
[Guest]: where suddenly there are more and more women because the nature of the jobs require now more

03:10:12.420 --> 03:10:17.460
[Guest]: women to be out doing the trading and the selling. Men have migrated out to do construction work,

03:10:17.460 --> 03:10:22.900
[Guest]: right? The economy is allowing for that. And that shift has happened and it's happened seamlessly

03:10:22.900 --> 03:10:29.380
[Guest]: and they are part of space and they are occupying it. And so I really here, I really do believe that

03:10:29.380 --> 03:10:35.620
[Guest]: the market and the way retail markets are organized and jobs are organized can really

03:10:35.620 --> 03:10:41.060
[Guest]: be a very important catalyst in the way space is occupied and we hold it together.

03:10:41.060 --> 03:10:46.580
[Guest]: And the last thing I will say on this is there are economists and sociologists who talk a lot about

03:10:46.580 --> 03:10:51.860
[Guest]: essentially counseling for men about how to hold public space. You know what you just said,

03:10:51.860 --> 03:10:55.700
[Guest]: being conscious of how easy it is for you to hold space. And I think that's actually a very

03:10:55.700 --> 03:11:02.740
[Guest]: evolved view. Many men don't realize that. And there is interest in thinking about can we get

03:11:02.740 --> 03:11:09.140
[Guest]: schoolboys to just be more conscious of these scripts and there are curricula around that.

03:11:09.140 --> 03:11:13.940
[Guest]: I'm very hopeful with that because I think you start young and I think things start to change.

03:11:14.900 --> 03:11:18.900
[Guest]: But the last thing on this that I will say, I don't know if the earlier thing was the last thing

03:11:18.900 --> 03:11:23.060
[Guest]: I said I would say, but this is the last thing I will say on this, which is that all the data

03:11:23.060 --> 03:11:30.820
[Guest]: from feminist economists, from sociologists, tells us that boys who see their mothers

03:11:30.820 --> 03:11:36.180
[Guest]: occupying space and working outside the home, the way they treat women out in public space

03:11:36.180 --> 03:11:39.700
[Guest]: is radically different. They're much more comfortable with women holding space with them.

03:11:39.700 --> 03:11:43.380
[Guest]: They're much more respectful. There are norms that are negotiated because they've seen

03:11:43.380 --> 03:11:47.700
[Guest]: their mothers have to make those negotiations with other men. And they've learned from that

03:11:47.700 --> 03:11:52.580
[Guest]: sometimes and they've heard about it. And so again, my faith is in the perhaps such an economist

03:11:52.580 --> 03:11:57.060
[Guest]: thing for me to say, but my faith is in the economy where I really think as women start to

03:11:57.060 --> 03:12:01.460
[Guest]: participate and not just the economy, but also local politics, community work, as women start

03:12:01.460 --> 03:12:08.180
[Guest]: to step out of the home for these different reasons, I hope that even men then start to adapt

03:12:08.180 --> 03:12:12.740
[Guest]: in the way they deal with women being in public space because they're used to it. And I think

03:12:12.740 --> 03:12:16.660
[Amit Varma]: that will take some time. Yeah, I absolutely agree with you. I mean, it's not just the economy.

03:12:16.660 --> 03:12:21.140
[Amit Varma]: I mean, it's society, right? Because economy is a subset of society and you know, the market being

03:12:21.140 --> 03:12:26.980
[Amit Varma]: just one mechanism of the voluntary actions of people within society. So I also do believe that

03:12:26.980 --> 03:12:31.940
[Amit Varma]: you know, any social change cannot happen in a top down way through the state, it's got to be

03:12:31.940 --> 03:12:36.020
[Amit Varma]: bottom up. And you know, even on the subject of kids learning, I think it will happen through

03:12:36.020 --> 03:12:40.020
[Amit Varma]: culture, it won't happen through curricula. It will happen through culture and peers and you

03:12:40.020 --> 03:12:43.860
[Amit Varma]: know, the films they watch and the music they listen to and all of that coming together.

03:12:43.860 --> 03:12:47.140
[Guest]: You know, Amit, there's a bit in the book and I really believe this. There are very few things

03:12:47.140 --> 03:12:52.660
[Guest]: that I think are like absolute truths, but I really do think that social change is intimate

03:12:52.660 --> 03:12:58.500
[Guest]: and it's incremental. I don't think I know the structures can change very quickly in a flash,

03:12:58.500 --> 03:13:02.900
[Guest]: there could be you know, governments that are toppled down, but social change in the way I treat

03:13:02.900 --> 03:13:09.380
[Guest]: you because of your identity because of your gender because of who you are. That is an intimate and

03:13:09.380 --> 03:13:18.500
[Guest]: incremental process. And I fundamentally believe that to make those changes, we have to start in

03:13:18.500 --> 03:13:24.420
[Guest]: our own as you just said, your own interpersonal realm, right? Like who are you taxing people when

03:13:24.420 --> 03:13:31.540
[Guest]: you see them treat women poorly? Are you paying your domestic worker enough? What in your immediate

03:13:31.540 --> 03:13:36.500
[Guest]: home? What are the practices that you are setting up for yourself? And that's why in the book,

03:13:36.500 --> 03:13:41.220
[Guest]: I mean, the book is it doesn't take a macro view, because it's actually extreme. The book is full

03:13:41.220 --> 03:13:46.660
[Guest]: of stories, minutiae of people's lives, precisely because I was very interested in this idea that

03:13:46.660 --> 03:13:53.060
[Guest]: if you follow people over a decade, what are the incremental changes in their intimate space? And

03:13:53.060 --> 03:13:56.180
[Guest]: I'm actually the one thing that has made me very hopeful is each of the women in the book,

03:13:56.180 --> 03:14:00.580
[Guest]: they've negotiated a different equilibrium for themselves. And that makes me very hopeful that

03:14:00.580 --> 03:14:06.900
[Guest]: yes, as jobs in this case, livelihoods, allow for women to interact with the world more,

03:14:07.700 --> 03:14:12.500
[Guest]: there will be changes that then happen for the better through a very messy process.

03:14:12.500 --> 03:14:17.220
[Guest]: But there will be changes for the better that allow for them to own more space and to feel

03:14:17.220 --> 03:14:20.980
[Guest]: better about themselves, be more loved. And that's an intimate process. And it's an incremental

03:14:20.980 --> 03:14:26.660
[Amit Varma]: process. It's an incremental process. And I'd add to that by saying that if the increments compound,

03:14:26.660 --> 03:14:31.220
[Amit Varma]: yeah, I think what often happens is that, you know, it's said about futurists or science

03:14:31.220 --> 03:14:36.020
[Amit Varma]: fiction writers, and I say it about creators, that we tend to overestimate the short term and

03:14:36.020 --> 03:14:40.260
[Amit Varma]: underestimate the long term. Yeah, so there will be no radical change, there will be no revolution

03:14:40.260 --> 03:14:45.380
[Amit Varma]: that, you know, suddenly women will be free in five years, and so on and so forth. But I think

03:14:45.380 --> 03:14:50.660
[Amit Varma]: that in, you know, change compounds, and so my god, I'm sounding hopeful. This is completely

03:14:50.660 --> 03:14:57.780
[Guest]: I'm so happy to hear this. This is fabulous. I've come in and Mr. Khan and I have converted you into

03:14:57.780 --> 03:15:02.500
[Guest]: an optimist. But what I was going to say, though, is, you know, this is precisely why Amit, and now

03:15:02.500 --> 03:15:07.860
[Guest]: I'll get gossipy a little bit, or maybe complain, which is that I hate all this kind of, you know,

03:15:07.860 --> 03:15:14.580
[Guest]: the smashing the patriarchy kind of feminism. Because everything that I have seen and read

03:15:14.580 --> 03:15:20.580
[Guest]: and witnessed tells me that social change will not be one noisy smash, I write about this,

03:15:20.580 --> 03:15:30.660
[Guest]: it will be a slow melting, it may be very quiet. And I actually contend real social change is not

03:15:30.660 --> 03:15:34.660
[Guest]: happening on Twitter. I know that there are hashtags and there's all this stuff. And it's

03:15:34.660 --> 03:15:39.620
[Guest]: great because I realized how toxic the internet is for women. So power to women who hold that space.

03:15:40.660 --> 03:15:46.020
[Guest]: But social change is happening in places we are not studying. I was very happy the book is doing

03:15:46.020 --> 03:15:50.420
[Guest]: well among sociology students. And one of the things I'm really hopeful for, is that I think

03:15:50.420 --> 03:15:54.260
[Guest]: we should just go back to doing very traditional sociology. We don't do that anymore. You know,

03:15:54.260 --> 03:15:57.540
[Guest]: the kind of work that I'm ensuring we know Srinivasan and others were doing, which is,

03:15:57.540 --> 03:16:01.860
[Guest]: you just study homes, you see what's happening, you know, in these local communities. And

03:16:01.860 --> 03:16:05.540
[Guest]: there is so much changing. I mean, the patwari wearing jeans suddenly, you know,

03:16:06.100 --> 03:16:11.300
[Guest]: there is a lot going on, which we don't document enough and what that means. One of the things

03:16:11.300 --> 03:16:15.380
[Guest]: that's very important, at least to me as an analytical prism, maybe for this book, and what

03:16:15.380 --> 03:16:21.540
[Guest]: I will do in the future is I think looking at the real minutia of things that seem utterly banal.

03:16:22.580 --> 03:16:26.980
[Guest]: Someone wearing jeans is utterly banal. Someone having a job is utterly banal. But actually,

03:16:26.980 --> 03:16:30.580
[Guest]: if you start to study it for what it is, someone liking Mr. Khan is utterly banal. It's very

03:16:30.580 --> 03:16:34.900
[Guest]: obvious. It's like what is there to study there. But if you start to study that, I actually think

03:16:34.900 --> 03:16:41.380
[Guest]: you'll learn a lot more about the big shifts that are happening in our society, much more than any

03:16:41.380 --> 03:16:45.940
[Guest]: loud, you know, interaction on the internet ever will. And I'm grateful that at least I had the

03:16:45.940 --> 03:16:49.620
[Guest]: opportunities and experiences to be able to do that. I'm looking forward to that kind of

03:16:49.620 --> 03:16:55.380
[Guest]: scholarship. I love that kind of work. And the one thing on this, which I will also add is that

03:16:55.380 --> 03:17:02.820
[Guest]: the there's a kind of belief I find even amongst my own friends, well intentioned feminism,

03:17:02.820 --> 03:17:09.220
[Guest]: which seems to believe that you have to conform that there's a standard script of what a feminist

03:17:09.220 --> 03:17:15.300
[Guest]: life is. And that's not true, because all the women in the book, they will not hold up to the

03:17:15.300 --> 03:17:21.060
[Guest]: label, because they don't see I don't see feminism as a label as a practice. And all of these women

03:17:21.060 --> 03:17:26.500
[Guest]: in their own ways are just fighting for a different reality for themselves. And they're doing it in

03:17:26.500 --> 03:17:33.620
[Guest]: ways that may subscribe to feminist scripts may upset feminist scripts, but they are attacking

03:17:33.620 --> 03:17:39.780
[Guest]: structures in terms of dependence. And I think our society will be better for it. And I noticed

03:17:39.780 --> 03:17:44.820
[Guest]: that in a lot of writing around women, there's like there's this writing that we tend to focus

03:17:44.820 --> 03:17:49.140
[Guest]: a lot on the heroes, right? So the big business women, women who really made it and those are

03:17:49.140 --> 03:17:54.180
[Guest]: great stories. And then we also tend to focus on victims of brutal crimes, because obviously,

03:17:54.180 --> 03:17:59.460
[Guest]: those are very important stories to tell. My interest with this was to look at the missing

03:17:59.460 --> 03:18:04.100
[Guest]: middle mean where the things happening and they don't seem particularly interesting on the surface

03:18:04.100 --> 03:18:08.660
[Guest]: of it. But I'd like to believe and I hope when people read the book, they find that what's going

03:18:08.660 --> 03:18:13.620
[Guest]: on is actually quite remarkable that there's a lot of change happening in places without protests

03:18:13.620 --> 03:18:17.940
[Guest]: with a capital P, there are subtle ways in which people are changing norms. And what's important

03:18:17.940 --> 03:18:22.180
[Amit Varma]: about the point that you just made, and which I'd love to underscore is that, you know, we should

03:18:22.180 --> 03:18:28.180
[Amit Varma]: not go by conventional notions of what is worthy of study or not, you know, the textures of everyday

03:18:28.180 --> 03:18:32.580
[Amit Varma]: life, the interior lives of women, you know, what do people feel when they go inside a cinema

03:18:32.580 --> 03:18:37.380
[Amit Varma]: theater, and they watch a star come on the screen, all these also reveal so much about us. And that's

03:18:37.380 --> 03:18:43.300
[Amit Varma]: kind of one of the areas that you've covered so well. So another fascinating aspect of the book,

03:18:43.300 --> 03:18:48.820
[Amit Varma]: for me, is that in a sense, your book contains multitudes, like people often complain about

03:18:48.820 --> 03:18:54.420
[Amit Varma]: nonfiction books, that it's one idea, and it somebody published it as an essay somewhere.

03:18:54.420 --> 03:18:58.980
[Amit Varma]: And then publisher said, idea is good, make a book, and they make a book. And it's basically

03:18:58.980 --> 03:19:03.220
[Amit Varma]: two, three interesting chapters, and the rest is filler. And your book is not like that at all,

03:19:03.220 --> 03:19:08.740
[Amit Varma]: because with every chapter, it's like you're adding on layers. So you have that first section

03:19:08.740 --> 03:19:14.500
[Amit Varma]: on upper class women, and then you kind of go down the line. And a lot of it is eye opening,

03:19:14.500 --> 03:19:20.100
[Amit Varma]: because these social realities also are so different from each other. I'm particularly

03:19:20.100 --> 03:19:25.460
[Amit Varma]: struck by a couple of those examples, you say about the working women of Bapu Nagar, quote,

03:19:25.460 --> 03:19:30.420
[Amit Varma]: the working women of Bapu Nagar had many theories on men and marriage, a good husband was divine

03:19:30.420 --> 03:19:35.620
[Amit Varma]: intervention and sheer luck, even the best man's character would eventually curdle and rot.

03:19:35.620 --> 03:19:40.180
[Amit Varma]: Life was tough on men, and they took it out on the women and children losing interest in being

03:19:40.180 --> 03:19:45.380
[Amit Varma]: devout, kind and courteous. Women were protected from the harshness of the world outside. So they

03:19:45.380 --> 03:19:50.100
[Amit Varma]: remained hopeful and God fearing, stop code. And then you write about the hamlets of Rampur.

03:19:50.100 --> 03:19:54.820
[Amit Varma]: For generations, the labors of women within the hamlets of rural Rampur were hidden. Women were

03:19:54.820 --> 03:20:00.260
[Amit Varma]: engaged in farming homestead plots and animal rearing as unpaid family helpers. This was in

03:20:00.260 --> 03:20:04.740
[Amit Varma]: keeping with the way agriculture was organized in Western Uttar Pradesh. Jobs within farming

03:20:04.740 --> 03:20:09.860
[Amit Varma]: were neatly segregated by sex. As Manju explained, anything that needs looking at an animal or

03:20:09.860 --> 03:20:14.420
[Amit Varma]: looking down on the ground, we women usually do. Anything that requires looking up at strangers

03:20:14.420 --> 03:20:19.380
[Amit Varma]: or going outside the village, the men do, stop quote, I mean, stop her quote. And you continue,

03:20:19.380 --> 03:20:24.420
[Amit Varma]: weeding and the cleaning and storing of grains were exclusively female chores. The dictates of

03:20:24.420 --> 03:20:28.820
[Amit Varma]: Parda meant that women would only work in their own fields or the fields of their relatives and

03:20:28.820 --> 03:20:35.060
[Amit Varma]: nearest neighbors, stop quote. And obviously, to go deeper into all of your observations, I'd just

03:20:35.060 --> 03:20:40.580
[Amit Varma]: encourage people to buy the book because everyone should read all of it. But just going to your

03:20:40.580 --> 03:20:49.380
[Amit Varma]: experience of covering all of this one, you know, the book is a combination of memoir, reportage,

03:20:49.940 --> 03:20:55.700
[Amit Varma]: and sort of analysis backed by data. So there is a certain amount of going out there and talking

03:20:55.700 --> 03:21:00.340
[Amit Varma]: to people. And as you earlier mentioned, you're an introvert, not in so many words, but you don't,

03:21:00.340 --> 03:21:04.340
[Amit Varma]: you're not, you would agree with me what in my agreement of what Sartre said, hell is other

03:21:04.340 --> 03:21:09.620
[Amit Varma]: people. But you actually went out and you spoke to all of these people and kind of made them

03:21:09.620 --> 03:21:15.700
[Amit Varma]: comfortable with you and all of that. And so what was that experience like, like, you know,

03:21:15.700 --> 03:21:21.380
[Amit Varma]: was it easy for you at first? And also, did you change in the process of doing all of this? Did

03:21:21.380 --> 03:21:25.300
[Amit Varma]: you change the way you look at them and the way you look to the world? You know, Amit, actually,

03:21:25.300 --> 03:21:31.140
[Guest]: this book happened by accident. So in fact, when and I mentioned this in the book, which is when I

03:21:31.140 --> 03:21:37.700
[Guest]: went to Ahmedabad, to Bapunagar and to Rampur, I was in my early 20s, I was supposed to be doing

03:21:37.700 --> 03:21:43.460
[Guest]: a survey of women who are working in home based sectors, right, be it embroidery or making incense

03:21:43.460 --> 03:21:48.820
[Guest]: sticks at home. And when I started asking them the standard survey questions of wages and working

03:21:48.820 --> 03:21:53.060
[Guest]: conditions, these women were just so bored because they were dealing with their economic realities

03:21:53.060 --> 03:21:57.380
[Guest]: themselves. And I think to take a break, then we started talking about Mr. Khan. And then that led

03:21:57.380 --> 03:22:02.420
[Guest]: me suddenly I, the tone and tenor of these conversations just opened up. And I think what

03:22:02.420 --> 03:22:07.780
[Guest]: really helped and I am a recluse is difficult for me. But I think what really helped was that shift

03:22:07.780 --> 03:22:12.900
[Guest]: in energy, that suddenly you had all these people who were so bored of, you know, this girl from

03:22:12.900 --> 03:22:18.820
[Guest]: Delhi was like wearing kajal with her khadi kurta has come and they've seen now versions of me

03:22:18.820 --> 03:22:23.140
[Guest]: multiple times, you know, and there's jokes about that. And I mentioned that in the book, one of

03:22:23.140 --> 03:22:27.380
[Guest]: the characters, Manju, she says to me, what you Delhi girls find about being here, I don't

03:22:27.380 --> 03:22:36.500
[Guest]: understand. I just love the shift in and suddenly, we all wanted to talk. And it was a very moving

03:22:36.500 --> 03:22:40.980
[Guest]: experience for me. And maybe this is why very early on in 2006, I decided I would write this

03:22:40.980 --> 03:22:45.940
[Guest]: book because what was moving about it is in a country where I'm always told that I have nothing

03:22:45.940 --> 03:22:50.580
[Guest]: in common with my neighbor, we are so different, there are all these lines of division, identity,

03:22:50.580 --> 03:22:58.180
[Guest]: so on and so forth. Suddenly, we all had this one person to talk about. And we talked about him in

03:22:58.180 --> 03:23:03.060
[Guest]: equal way. How what do you think about Shah Rukh? Let me tell you what I think about Shah Rukh,

03:23:03.060 --> 03:23:08.420
[Guest]: right? Suddenly, all those very narrow divisions of identity very briefly, I mean, just disappeared.

03:23:08.420 --> 03:23:13.620
[Guest]: And it was just a very exhilarating moment for a young person, young foolish person as myself. So

03:23:13.620 --> 03:23:20.020
[Guest]: I changed in that I think those conversations made me a lot more thoughtful about what unites us as

03:23:20.020 --> 03:23:24.020
[Guest]: opposed to just the standard scripts of you know, what social science teaches you, right? You should

03:23:24.020 --> 03:23:31.460
[Guest]: of course, be mindful of difference. But I don't only see difference. And the experience of the

03:23:31.460 --> 03:23:37.940
[Guest]: research was really complicated. Because I often actually say that this was not standard research,

03:23:37.940 --> 03:23:42.340
[Guest]: because it's not like I had, you know, specific schedules saying, Okay, I'll come back in six

03:23:42.340 --> 03:23:47.620
[Guest]: months or four months. And I followed these women for more than a decade. But each time Mr. Khan had

03:23:47.620 --> 03:23:52.900
[Guest]: a release, each time he had a film, then there were festivals, we would talk some of these women

03:23:52.900 --> 03:23:58.580
[Guest]: didn't have mobile phones, but I try and reach them. Sometime in 2013, I did lose touch because

03:23:58.580 --> 03:24:03.220
[Guest]: I went off to study in Boston, I was not fully in contact with everyone, I came back and when I

03:24:03.220 --> 03:24:08.340
[Guest]: decided the book was going to take a certain shape, I needed to go back to seek permissions

03:24:08.340 --> 03:24:13.300
[Guest]: catch up on their lives. And in fact, going back, I discovered one woman had run away from her home,

03:24:13.300 --> 03:24:19.060
[Guest]: and there was all this churn going on in their lives as well. And so it was very complicated.

03:24:19.060 --> 03:24:23.380
[Guest]: And it felt sometimes like it really wasn't research, it was just, you know, I was following

03:24:23.380 --> 03:24:26.740
[Guest]: up with friends, if I were trying to meet Shruti, for instance, our common friend,

03:24:26.740 --> 03:24:30.580
[Guest]: and she was no longer where she was. And I was trying to find her where she was. It just it was

03:24:30.580 --> 03:24:37.380
[Guest]: like that it was just life. And in a way, I think I was just bobbing along these women's lives,

03:24:37.380 --> 03:24:44.340
[Guest]: I don't think I was participating in the standard way, an anthropologist or a researcher would.

03:24:45.140 --> 03:24:50.260
[Guest]: But then as a consequence, there is a lightness in the way we were speaking to each other,

03:24:50.260 --> 03:24:57.060
[Guest]: because it was very open. The process changed me in making me much more aware of our unity,

03:24:57.060 --> 03:25:03.540
[Guest]: as opposed to our divisions. It also made me much more appreciative of how precarious people's

03:25:03.540 --> 03:25:07.860
[Guest]: lives are. I mean, I knew the data on precarity, I know that our lives are precarious, but there's

03:25:07.860 --> 03:25:13.940
[Guest]: something, you know, when you go to meet someone, and she's crying, and she tells you that I'm going

03:25:13.940 --> 03:25:18.340
[Guest]: to have to go back to the husband that I do not love at all, because I cannot be somewhere on my

03:25:18.340 --> 03:25:25.140
[Guest]: own, and you've held this person's hand. It just changes the way you think about people's lives.

03:25:25.140 --> 03:25:29.380
[Guest]: So it's made me very considerate. In fact, a lot of people who meet me, it's going to sound

03:25:29.380 --> 03:25:33.620
[Guest]: really strange, but they think that I'm a little too considerate, like I'm a pushover. But it's

03:25:33.620 --> 03:25:38.740
[Guest]: okay, I'm happy to be a pushover, because I've now realized that I think we are so privileged,

03:25:38.740 --> 03:25:42.580
[Guest]: and people's lives are so precarious, mostly in our country, that you should have some patience

03:25:42.580 --> 03:25:45.700
[Guest]: and tolerance for what people are going through. And I think it's really taught me that.

03:25:46.660 --> 03:25:50.900
[Guest]: And I think the third thing it's taught me, which I've mentioned time and time again,

03:25:50.900 --> 03:25:56.820
[Guest]: is that the power of culture, and the power of popular culture, not just, you know, sort of

03:25:56.820 --> 03:26:04.340
[Guest]: niche culture, which is sort of highbrow, but mass culture, because had it not been for Mr. Khan,

03:26:05.380 --> 03:26:09.380
[Guest]: the relationships that were sustained between myself and many of the women in the book

03:26:09.380 --> 03:26:14.820
[Guest]: just wouldn't have occurred. And I'm very grateful for that, the sheer power of that

03:26:14.820 --> 03:26:20.500
[Guest]: popular Hindi film and his icon. And the last thing I'm struck by is how difficult it is to

03:26:20.500 --> 03:26:25.060
[Guest]: do research on women's lives, Amit, because none of them ever had time to talk to me.

03:26:25.060 --> 03:26:29.060
[Guest]: So even if I wanted to be a standard researcher, and set up a time for an interview,

03:26:29.620 --> 03:26:34.100
[Guest]: suddenly you're called, these women are called to deal with kids, something you have to go do

03:26:34.100 --> 03:26:39.380
[Guest]: something in the field, irrespective of your class background, this was true across time poverty

03:26:39.380 --> 03:26:43.620
[Guest]: meant that it was so difficult for women to just find time to do what they wanted to do, let alone

03:26:43.620 --> 03:26:52.900
[Guest]: answer my questions, that I, I really appreciate that when we as privileged women can do whatever

03:26:52.900 --> 03:26:58.900
[Guest]: we can with our time. We are I mean, a we're such a minority, and it makes me appreciate my own time

03:26:58.900 --> 03:27:04.340
[Guest]: much more because I've seen that it's a true luxury in our country, just having time to yourself.

03:27:04.340 --> 03:27:08.500
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, and time poverty was a phrase I first came across in this book. So to my shame,

03:27:08.500 --> 03:27:14.420
[Amit Varma]: and it's such a lovely phrase. It says so much. Yeah. So I now want to ask a question about

03:27:15.220 --> 03:27:20.340
[Amit Varma]: language. You make an observation in the book where at one point when you're talking about Manju

03:27:20.340 --> 03:27:26.020
[Amit Varma]: in your in your chapter on Manju, you talk about the link between language and agency and you say,

03:27:26.020 --> 03:27:31.620
[Amit Varma]: quote, so marriage happened to Manju that year at the disputed age of 20. Those were her words.

03:27:31.620 --> 03:27:36.580
[Amit Varma]: She wasn't getting married. Marriage was happening to her. She was simply along for the ride,

03:27:36.580 --> 03:27:41.460
[Amit Varma]: a spectator with a front row seat, a stop code. And this reminds me of something Jackson Katz

03:27:41.460 --> 03:27:46.580
[Amit Varma]: once said, where he said, quote, we talked about how many women were raped last year,

03:27:46.580 --> 03:27:51.060
[Amit Varma]: not about how many men rape women. We talk about how many girls in a school district were harassed

03:27:51.060 --> 03:27:55.780
[Amit Varma]: last year, not about how many boys harassed girls. We talk about how many teenage girls

03:27:55.780 --> 03:28:00.580
[Amit Varma]: got pregnant in the state of Vermont last year, rather than how many men and teenage boys got

03:28:00.580 --> 03:28:05.780
[Amit Varma]: girls pregnant. So you can see how the use of this passive voice has a political effect.

03:28:05.780 --> 03:28:11.940
[Amit Varma]: It shifts the focus of men and boys and on to girls and women. Even the term violence against

03:28:11.940 --> 03:28:17.460
[Amit Varma]: women is problematic. It's a passive construction. There is no active agent in the sentence. It's a

03:28:17.460 --> 03:28:21.540
[Amit Varma]: bad thing that happens to women. It's a bad thing that happens to women. But when you look at that

03:28:21.540 --> 03:28:26.820
[Amit Varma]: term violence against women, no one is doing it to them. It just happens. Men aren't even a part

03:28:26.820 --> 03:28:31.780
[Amit Varma]: of it. Stop quote. And you know, that link of Jackson Katz was shared with me on Twitter by

03:28:31.780 --> 03:28:36.260
[Amit Varma]: one of my writing students. And I'll link that tweet from the show notes. And the discussion

03:28:36.260 --> 03:28:42.020
[Amit Varma]: that this kind of led to was the role that language plays, the insidious role that language

03:28:42.020 --> 03:28:47.620
[Amit Varma]: plays that when you use language in these ways, you know, you're denying women agency and choice.

03:28:47.620 --> 03:28:52.740
[Amit Varma]: And equally, it is as if shit just happened, shit happens, you know, it's not somebody's fault.

03:28:52.740 --> 03:28:57.140
[Amit Varma]: How much of this did you, you know, did you notice a lot of this? What are your thoughts on this?

03:28:57.140 --> 03:29:02.100
[Amit Varma]: Because, you know, you pointed this out and about Manju saying that marriage was happening to her,

03:29:02.100 --> 03:29:07.380
[Amit Varma]: she wasn't getting married. How much of this did you see? And is this something that there is some

03:29:07.380 --> 03:29:13.540
[Amit Varma]: kind of class distinction to also? Or do you feel all women are equally likely to think along these

03:29:13.540 --> 03:29:18.100
[Guest]: lines? How does one think about this? I mean, I think it depends on the phenomena that we're

03:29:18.100 --> 03:29:23.300
[Guest]: talking about. When we talk about marriage, there's certainly a sense. So what she said was

03:29:23.300 --> 03:29:30.260
[Guest]: meri shadi ho rahi hai. And it's not like the shadi is happening to me. And that is actually

03:29:30.260 --> 03:29:33.540
[Guest]: a way some other people would talk about it. And I noticed that that was actually the way many of

03:29:33.540 --> 03:29:38.500
[Guest]: her friends, so many people I knew would would say that shadi ho rahi hai. It's not something

03:29:38.500 --> 03:29:43.060
[Guest]: that is happening to me. But that's because marriage happens to all women. It's not that

03:29:43.700 --> 03:29:48.900
[Guest]: in a world where only 5% of women are choosing their own partners. Marriage is happening to

03:29:48.900 --> 03:29:55.060
[Guest]: everyone. It's you are not actively participating necessarily in that process. You may be but

03:29:55.060 --> 03:30:01.140
[Guest]: it's obfuscated. It's a marriage arranged market. And I think around marriage, that use of language

03:30:01.140 --> 03:30:06.260
[Guest]: was very passive for women, where, in a way, you realize that this is a rite of passage,

03:30:06.260 --> 03:30:10.180
[Guest]: you need to go through this to be able to, as we talked in the beginning to access the world

03:30:10.180 --> 03:30:13.620
[Guest]: to do what you want to do, as long as your husband is okay with it, but you need a husband,

03:30:13.620 --> 03:30:18.660
[Guest]: he'll confer status and you will be appropriate then. So marriage, I noticed was something that

03:30:18.660 --> 03:30:23.860
[Guest]: everybody sort of said it happens, you know, amongst particularly middle class, low income

03:30:23.860 --> 03:30:28.660
[Guest]: women, even the way some elite women would talk about their marriages. It was something you were

03:30:28.660 --> 03:30:32.500
[Guest]: succumbing to. And I and there's a Rajput woman in the book who comes from a very well to do

03:30:32.500 --> 03:30:36.660
[Guest]: background, but she married someone because her father's in debt, and she has to to conform to

03:30:36.660 --> 03:30:40.980
[Guest]: what her family expects of her. And it's not a particularly loving marriage. But even the way

03:30:40.980 --> 03:30:44.660
[Guest]: she would talk about her marriage, and she's quite posh, the way she would talk about her marriage

03:30:44.660 --> 03:30:50.420
[Guest]: was very much as if it was a something she had succumbed to she had given into. So I think this

03:30:50.420 --> 03:30:59.140
[Guest]: is true of marriage, everything else, be it Mr. Khan, be it trying to earn money, be it. In fact,

03:30:59.140 --> 03:31:05.220
[Guest]: there I noticed, particularly amongst sort of women living very harsh economic lives,

03:31:06.180 --> 03:31:13.860
[Guest]: there was this great delight in using the active voice, life is boring, boredom, the word boredom

03:31:13.860 --> 03:31:21.860
[Guest]: and boring, I heard more than even I heard the word Mr. Khan, Shah Rukh, because it felt like

03:31:21.860 --> 03:31:28.340
[Guest]: inequality was being almost expressed through boredom. Because what was happening was men had

03:31:28.340 --> 03:31:33.060
[Guest]: access to public space, men had access to money, so they could go out and have fun. Whereas women

03:31:33.060 --> 03:31:37.220
[Guest]: were expected to stay at home and life was boring. And some of the women who are first generation

03:31:37.220 --> 03:31:40.740
[Guest]: English speakers, they learned the word boring, and then they spread it around in their villages.

03:31:40.740 --> 03:31:44.820
[Guest]: And everybody was talking about how women were boring. And I actually see that inequality was

03:31:44.820 --> 03:31:49.620
[Guest]: experienced as boredom for these women. And they were very active in the way they use these phrases

03:31:49.620 --> 03:31:53.940
[Guest]: and words, they were the active being this was not something boredom was not happening to them,

03:31:53.940 --> 03:31:59.380
[Guest]: they knew that their lives were boring, because boys had more freedom. And they said that we don't

03:31:59.380 --> 03:32:06.500
[Guest]: want our lives to be boring. And I think when it came to cultural practices, when it came to fun,

03:32:06.500 --> 03:32:14.660
[Guest]: when it came to economic freedoms, the language that was used tended to be far more individualistic

03:32:14.660 --> 03:32:19.620
[Guest]: in a in a strange way, because they were keeping themselves and their selfhood at the centre of

03:32:19.620 --> 03:32:23.300
[Guest]: what they were trying to say. So it was always I want to watch a movie or I want to do this,

03:32:23.300 --> 03:32:29.460
[Guest]: because I quote actually a WH Auden line, which is as long as the self can say I will always rebel.

03:32:29.460 --> 03:32:34.260
[Guest]: And I think these were women, first generation women and their families were saying I you know,

03:32:34.260 --> 03:32:39.140
[Guest]: I want this and I want that. And this was a part of a new self that they were constructing.

03:32:39.140 --> 03:32:43.380
[Guest]: Whereas their mothers were much more their sense of identity was much more based on family and

03:32:43.380 --> 03:32:48.020
[Guest]: community. They were always a we. Whereas these girls I noticed, they would always say I

03:32:48.020 --> 03:32:51.540
[Guest]: mujhe karna hai, mujhe jaana hai, mujhe mall jaana hai, mujhe shadi karni nahi hai. You know,

03:32:51.540 --> 03:32:56.340
[Guest]: there was always either mujhe, mujhe, mujhe. It was very popular and various versions of that in

03:32:56.340 --> 03:33:01.540
[Guest]: Bangla as well. But marriage was the place where I noticed that when you think of the language,

03:33:01.540 --> 03:33:05.940
[Guest]: which is why I mentioned it the way she did, which is that ho rahi hai, it's not like I am

03:33:05.940 --> 03:33:10.420
[Guest]: getting married, you are not, you're complicit, but you're complicit in something that's just

03:33:10.420 --> 03:33:15.780
[Amit Varma]: happening to you. Yeah, I think there's a poignant moment where one of the people you meet, I think

03:33:15.780 --> 03:33:21.140
[Amit Varma]: maybe Gold, where her marriage is fixed up. And I think a song from DDLJ is playing and she starts

03:33:21.140 --> 03:33:25.620
[Amit Varma]: crying. And her mother and sister tell her that listen, listen, we know how you feel. But yeah,

03:33:25.620 --> 03:33:29.780
[Guest]: the real world is different. Yeah, yeah, that marriage is not going to always be adventure and

03:33:29.780 --> 03:33:34.900
[Guest]: travel. And so many of I think the women in the book think that marriage will be the path to fun,

03:33:34.900 --> 03:33:40.100
[Guest]: then access unadulterated fun in the way you want. You can watch TV, you can do whatever you can.

03:33:40.100 --> 03:33:44.580
[Guest]: And in Gold's case, she realizes that she's actually being married off to a guy who is

03:33:44.580 --> 03:33:50.180
[Guest]: extremely conservative will be very, he will regulate her movement, she realizes that.

03:33:50.820 --> 03:33:57.380
[Guest]: And then suddenly she sees Shah Rukh on in London and holding on to Kajol and serenading her

03:33:57.380 --> 03:34:02.180
[Guest]: in a city that at that time, Gold thought she wasn't ever going to be able to see. She does,

03:34:02.180 --> 03:34:06.340
[Guest]: this is giving it away for the reader. And you should read the book to know how it was a very

03:34:06.340 --> 03:34:11.140
[Guest]: sad moment. And in fact, there are moments like this a lot. So even the Rajput woman who I talked

03:34:11.140 --> 03:34:16.500
[Guest]: about who's posh, marry someone she doesn't want to. And she says to me, each time her favorite

03:34:16.500 --> 03:34:22.740
[Guest]: film is Kal Ho Na Hoon. And she says each time Shah Rukh dies in that film. I remember when I

03:34:22.740 --> 03:34:26.020
[Guest]: was told that I was going to get married, and I feel like I'm dying with him. Because I think

03:34:26.020 --> 03:34:29.780
[Guest]: that movie came out around the time that she was supposed to get married. And so it's salient for

03:34:29.780 --> 03:34:35.620
[Guest]: her. And so I think people just see his image and the contrast of that, or maybe the mirroring of

03:34:35.620 --> 03:34:41.220
[Guest]: that in some cases, with their own lives, it's quite poignant for them. And they react to that.

03:34:41.220 --> 03:34:43.380
[Amit Varma]: Neurons that fire together, wire together.

03:34:43.380 --> 03:34:43.880
[Amit Varma]: Yes.

03:34:44.580 --> 03:34:50.420
[Amit Varma]: Isn't it? Yeah. I'm also like, you've looked at sort of the loneliness of Indian women through

03:34:50.420 --> 03:34:56.340
[Amit Varma]: the prism of Shah Rukh Khan in a sense. And a larger theme, of course, is how films reflect

03:34:56.340 --> 03:35:01.060
[Amit Varma]: society. Like at one point, you write, quote, if India's employment rate helps us track our

03:35:01.060 --> 03:35:06.100
[Amit Varma]: economic transformation, popular Hindi film extravaganzas, track our moral transformation,

03:35:06.100 --> 03:35:12.100
[Amit Varma]: stop quote. And later on, you talk about how films teach so many women about love, sex and

03:35:12.100 --> 03:35:17.380
[Amit Varma]: the world like at one point, even just how someone touches someone, where, you know, you quote a

03:35:17.380 --> 03:35:22.100
[Amit Varma]: young lady, a garment worker, say to you, quote, I wish someone could talk to me or touch me the

03:35:22.100 --> 03:35:26.740
[Amit Varma]: way he does with Kajol in Kabhi Khushi Kabhi Gum, but it's never going to happen. Stop quote.

03:35:26.740 --> 03:35:32.820
[Amit Varma]: How do you think films have kind of changed to reflect whatever change there might be? Like

03:35:32.820 --> 03:35:37.380
[Amit Varma]: at one level, like, you know, there is this constant argument, what shapes what? And obviously,

03:35:37.380 --> 03:35:42.740
[Amit Varma]: you know, the causation doesn't go one way. But there is a certain kind of cinema being made by

03:35:42.740 --> 03:35:47.060
[Amit Varma]: vocal elites that doesn't really come from society that is perhaps a little more progressive and all

03:35:47.060 --> 03:35:54.020
[Amit Varma]: of that. But otherwise, when you look at films, where do you see those sort of reflections of

03:35:54.020 --> 03:35:59.860
[Amit Varma]: change happening? An additional kind of sideways question that is there a chance that someone

03:35:59.860 --> 03:36:06.260
[Amit Varma]: looking for an icon like SRK to write about 30 years later, will not be looking at an actor like

03:36:06.260 --> 03:36:11.300
[Amit Varma]: Shah Rukh Khan, but a role model who is a young woman who can live alone and doesn't need men

03:36:11.300 --> 03:36:15.540
[Guest]: to help with. Yeah, yeah, no, I absolutely yes. Let me first the answer to your second question

03:36:15.540 --> 03:36:21.140
[Guest]: is yes. In fact, already now, I have a line in the book and so many women would say this to me

03:36:21.140 --> 03:36:26.020
[Guest]: in different ways, which is, you know, Shah Rukh represented their idea of a benevolent patriarch,

03:36:26.020 --> 03:36:30.100
[Guest]: you know, a man who would care for them, love them a certain way. But Priyanka Chopra and Deepika

03:36:30.100 --> 03:36:35.220
[Guest]: Padukone represent women who love themselves and can love themselves, despite with or without men.

03:36:35.220 --> 03:36:39.140
[Guest]: And you know, they've openly so talked about their private lives, and they're so successful.

03:36:39.140 --> 03:36:43.300
[Guest]: And so I think that's already happening. I think that shift is very much underway. I think on

03:36:43.300 --> 03:36:51.380
[Guest]: cinema and love, there's so much said and written about this, I will essentially focus on two

03:36:51.380 --> 03:36:58.100
[Guest]: themes. I think one is, if you look at the way love and I'm thinking about the recent films,

03:36:59.220 --> 03:37:04.660
[Guest]: romance films no longer are like the big stay of Bollywood, right? I mean, if you even look at the

03:37:04.660 --> 03:37:10.660
[Guest]: multiplex movies that tend to do well, it's no longer love stories. These are all now gritty

03:37:10.660 --> 03:37:16.740
[Guest]: scripts about gritty realities. And I actually say in the book that most of the films that we're

03:37:16.740 --> 03:37:21.860
[Guest]: seeing are just sympathetic stories of capitalism's male losers, you know, like sperm donors,

03:37:21.860 --> 03:37:27.780
[Guest]: unemployed men, all of that. And I think, in fact, I feel that many of the younger actors,

03:37:27.780 --> 03:37:31.300
[Guest]: they are not matinee idols, I think the scripts that are given to them are so terrific,

03:37:31.300 --> 03:37:37.140
[Guest]: that it's actually the script that is the new matinee idol in India. Now, in that world,

03:37:37.140 --> 03:37:41.940
[Guest]: love is a very small element. And in fact, if you measure and I have measured how much women

03:37:41.940 --> 03:37:46.340
[Guest]: speak in these films, they don't speak very much. And these are like big multiplex hits,

03:37:46.340 --> 03:37:49.380
[Guest]: you know, you could think of a Gangs of Wasseypur, or you could think of, you know,

03:37:49.380 --> 03:37:53.140
[Guest]: many of the movies recently that have come out, Pink or any of the others. Actually,

03:37:53.140 --> 03:37:58.660
[Guest]: female dialogue is not that significant. And female dialogue on terms of intimacy,

03:37:58.660 --> 03:38:03.540
[Guest]: talking about love, talking about sex, trying to decode the sex and love that you're feeling

03:38:03.540 --> 03:38:08.740
[Guest]: or having. That's just not part of many of these new multiplex films. They're not interested in

03:38:08.740 --> 03:38:14.580
[Guest]: that project anymore. The gangster story barely have any of those scripts. Usually the women are

03:38:14.580 --> 03:38:18.660
[Guest]: just quiet, supportive characters or quiet, bewitching characters, you know, who trigger

03:38:18.660 --> 03:38:22.660
[Guest]: all kinds of trouble. So I haven't said that they're like the bitch, the bichari or the

03:38:22.660 --> 03:38:29.300
[Guest]: beauty. I mean, it's sort of the three, right? And you don't necessarily see much deviation from

03:38:29.300 --> 03:38:39.140
[Guest]: that. Now, go back in time to the 1990s. And to Mr. Khan's films, they may seem very regressive

03:38:39.140 --> 03:38:45.220
[Guest]: and soppy in a certain gaze. But actually, each one of them have women who are writing poetry

03:38:45.220 --> 03:38:49.780
[Guest]: about the kind of man they want their own freedoms. I mean, DDLJ actually starts we should

03:38:49.780 --> 03:38:55.300
[Guest]: we should always keep reinforcing this DDLJ actually starts with Simran. She holds the

03:38:55.300 --> 03:39:00.180
[Guest]: agency because she is defining the man that she wants to meet an unknown stranger.

03:39:02.100 --> 03:39:07.620
[Guest]: She's written a poem for herself. And that first scene, then you see Shah Rukh in the film,

03:39:07.620 --> 03:39:13.300
[Guest]: it's actually first you, the audience is introduced to her fantasy. And then you meet

03:39:13.300 --> 03:39:17.460
[Amit Varma]: Shah Rukh who essentially concretizes that fantasy. But then it ends when her dad gives

03:39:17.460 --> 03:39:24.420
[Guest]: her permission to go. I agree. And I think there I think reams and I get into sort of

03:39:24.420 --> 03:39:28.180
[Guest]: how different people see that scene so differently, right? And I see that but

03:39:28.740 --> 03:39:34.180
[Guest]: but we should recognize that in these films, women had agency to define love relationships.

03:39:34.180 --> 03:39:38.820
[Guest]: Madhuri Dixit keeps a diary and listens to music on her own in Dil Toh Pagal Hai.

03:39:38.820 --> 03:39:43.620
[Guest]: Karishma Kapoor has this beautiful scene with Shah Rukh where she's so upset in Dil Toh Pagal Hai

03:39:43.620 --> 03:39:49.220
[Guest]: that he's not choosing her. And they have this very awkward conversation about romantic rejection.

03:39:49.220 --> 03:39:53.300
[Guest]: Shah Rukh is being rejected in Kabhi Haan Kabhi Naan. He's talking about what it feels like to

03:39:53.300 --> 03:39:58.820
[Guest]: be romantically rejected. We're not seeing other than in Ae Dil Hai Mushkil, which is a thing that

03:39:58.820 --> 03:40:06.260
[Guest]: came out in 2016. Right? I don't think we've seen those kinds of scripts too much in films anymore.

03:40:06.260 --> 03:40:10.820
[Guest]: And so if we're looking to films, and I have an Andy Warhol quote, they're saying that I didn't

03:40:10.820 --> 03:40:15.300
[Guest]: know what to do about love. And I wanted to learn about love. So I went to the movies to learn about

03:40:15.300 --> 03:40:20.100
[Guest]: love. If young kids are trying to learn about love now, amongst the elite, they can watch,

03:40:20.100 --> 03:40:25.300
[Guest]: you know, K dramas, they can watch foreign shows, they can watch Netflix. But amongst working class

03:40:25.300 --> 03:40:29.620
[Guest]: communities and low income communities, I don't know where a lot of that is going to come from.

03:40:29.620 --> 03:40:35.300
[Guest]: I mean, it's probably social media, I'm not sure. But the films are no longer necessarily interested

03:40:35.300 --> 03:40:39.540
[Guest]: in that big project of explaining love or demonstrating love. I think that time seems

03:40:39.540 --> 03:40:43.700
[Guest]: to have passed. And maybe it'll come back again. But we'll see. Because the scripts now are very

03:40:43.700 --> 03:40:51.940
[Guest]: different. So that's one. Now, the second is, if you think about the terms that are being portrayed

03:40:51.940 --> 03:40:58.820
[Guest]: of the love and sex that we see in film, you know, one is still if you look at the big blockbusters,

03:40:58.820 --> 03:41:02.980
[Guest]: the mass films, right, and even to some extent, the multiplex films, but certainly in the mass

03:41:02.980 --> 03:41:10.900
[Guest]: films, female words and women's voices when it comes to expectations of partners, expectations

03:41:10.900 --> 03:41:16.260
[Guest]: of men, and men engaging with those expectations. Other than that one scene I mentioned,

03:41:17.140 --> 03:41:22.100
[Guest]: I don't really know very many big box office hits that were pan national box office hits that do

03:41:22.100 --> 03:41:27.140
[Guest]: that. I actually think you'll see much more of this in regional cinema. You don't see it in popular

03:41:27.140 --> 03:41:34.980
[Guest]: Hindi film anymore. And sex increasingly, and I mentioned this is sort of while earlier love led

03:41:34.980 --> 03:41:39.860
[Guest]: to sex. So I think the one thing that has changed now is that sex has been liberated from love in

03:41:39.860 --> 03:41:45.300
[Guest]: film. And so you have, you know, the traditional Imran Hashmi film where, you know, sex is always

03:41:45.300 --> 03:41:50.420
[Guest]: a way for people to manipulate each other, the sex is consensual, but it's a way for people to

03:41:50.420 --> 03:41:55.300
[Guest]: get something to profit from something to trick somebody, you know, all there are all these

03:41:55.300 --> 03:42:01.940
[Guest]: stories. And then you have this one depiction of sex, which I really think started with this

03:42:01.940 --> 03:42:07.300
[Guest]: film cocktail with Deepika Padukone, where essentially you have people, women who have

03:42:07.300 --> 03:42:14.020
[Guest]: casual sex as a shorthand to show how modern or hip or cool she is. But even in that film,

03:42:14.020 --> 03:42:17.700
[Guest]: and as many people have pointed out, she's punished for it because you know,

03:42:17.700 --> 03:42:23.220
[Guest]: she has a car crash, the boy doesn't eventually choose her, all of that, right. And so I think

03:42:23.220 --> 03:42:29.220
[Guest]: if you look at the depictions of love and sex was interesting is while now I think love largely has

03:42:29.220 --> 03:42:34.420
[Guest]: is no longer dominant in the stories that we tell in big popular Hindi cinema, I think it's moved to

03:42:34.420 --> 03:42:39.380
[Guest]: OTT and it's moved to other platforms. Sex, which is now liberated from love,

03:42:40.100 --> 03:42:48.020
[Guest]: is still shown in this extremely transactional way. And then what's even worse is that while

03:42:48.020 --> 03:42:54.740
[Guest]: people are having sex, you can show people having sex, any conversation about sex is still taboo,

03:42:54.740 --> 03:42:58.100
[Guest]: which is why again, I keep mentioning that scene in Ae Dil Hai Mushkil because I really do think

03:42:58.100 --> 03:43:02.980
[Guest]: credit to Karan Johar for, you know, what he did, because in a way that film is one of those very

03:43:02.980 --> 03:43:07.780
[Guest]: rare films where people are actually talking about, well, we hooked up and what does that mean? And so

03:43:07.780 --> 03:43:12.020
[Guest]: many young people find themselves nowadays in that dilemma, right? Like they're trying to decode what

03:43:12.020 --> 03:43:18.260
[Guest]: their encounters are meaning, where is this going? What is it leading to? And they do rely on scripts

03:43:18.260 --> 03:43:23.140
[Guest]: of films to sort of mirror for them how to negotiate and have these conversations. But

03:43:23.140 --> 03:43:28.340
[Guest]: there's very little talk of that. And while so while we see this proliferation of casual sex

03:43:28.340 --> 03:43:32.100
[Guest]: in cinema, there's very little conversation, which actually I don't know what's causing what,

03:43:32.100 --> 03:43:36.180
[Guest]: but it's mirroring what's happening in society, because people are having casual sex, and then

03:43:36.180 --> 03:43:40.820
[Guest]: men ghost you or girls will ghost and nobody really talks about it. Because any talk about

03:43:40.820 --> 03:43:47.620
[Guest]: sex or the sex that is being had, or the terms of love is apparently going to scare men away. And

03:43:47.620 --> 03:43:53.620
[Guest]: all of that will happen. And so I think that there's a very strange silence around love right

03:43:53.620 --> 03:43:57.460
[Guest]: now in cinema. And I think which is why many of the women that I know in the book are looking to

03:43:57.460 --> 03:44:01.460
[Guest]: Shah Rukh Khan's films, because those were films that at least they were talking about some of

03:44:01.460 --> 03:44:06.020
[Guest]: these things, they were seeing all of that happen. But that age of big, soppy, romantic dramas is

03:44:06.020 --> 03:44:10.420
[Amit Varma]: now gone. So it's almost four hours. And I feel like that's, you know, we could talk for another

03:44:10.420 --> 03:44:14.660
[Amit Varma]: four hours. I've so much to talk about. We haven't even discussed any of the individual stories,

03:44:14.660 --> 03:44:20.340
[Amit Varma]: which I so wanted to do. But I'll end with a couple of last kind of questions. And one of

03:44:20.340 --> 03:44:26.100
[Amit Varma]: them is not really connected with your book per se. It's just sort of a, you know, love is something

03:44:26.100 --> 03:44:31.860
[Amit Varma]: that you've sort of looked at deeply, and especially the instrumental nature of love in

03:44:31.860 --> 03:44:36.820
[Amit Varma]: this. And I love this quote by, I love this quote by, I love this quote by Iris Murdoch, where she

03:44:36.820 --> 03:44:41.620
[Amit Varma]: says, quote, love is the extremely difficult realization that something other than oneself is

03:44:41.620 --> 03:44:47.780
[Amit Varma]: real. Yeah, stop quote. And it's so lovely. And it also speaks to Kant's, that's not Amitabh Kant's,

03:44:47.780 --> 03:44:54.100
[Amit Varma]: Immanuel Kant's second categorical imperative, that always treat every other person as an end

03:44:54.100 --> 03:44:59.300
[Amit Varma]: in themselves and not as a means to an end, right? So not as instrumental, not as transactional,

03:44:59.300 --> 03:45:05.540
[Amit Varma]: something other than oneself is real. I feel that I need to remind myself of this time and time

03:45:05.540 --> 03:45:12.980
[Amit Varma]: again, because I think all of us are most of the time, really living out a play in our heads,

03:45:12.980 --> 03:45:17.540
[Amit Varma]: where we are the central character and everyone else is instrumental. And we get different things

03:45:17.540 --> 03:45:24.260
[Amit Varma]: from them, friendship, companionship, sex, whatever, A, B, C, D. And it seems to me that one

03:45:24.260 --> 03:45:30.180
[Amit Varma]: way out of this, one way of realizing that we are caught in the Chakra view, as it were, is just

03:45:31.300 --> 03:45:37.460
[Amit Varma]: awareness of oneself and awareness of others, where you just sit back, listen to them,

03:45:37.460 --> 03:45:43.620
[Amit Varma]: get into their lives, empathize. And you've been doing a lot of that in the process of writing

03:45:43.620 --> 03:45:49.780
[Amit Varma]: this. So is this a subject you have any thoughts on? And as a corollary to that, do you feel that

03:45:49.780 --> 03:45:54.020
[Amit Varma]: the process of writing a book like this changed you? Do you think you would be a different person

03:45:54.020 --> 03:45:59.460
[Amit Varma]: if you were just doing important economics papers, which are elite males everywhere?

03:45:59.460 --> 03:46:03.620
[Guest]: I would be a very selfish person. I'm sure I'm still a selfish person. But I think my selfishness

03:46:03.620 --> 03:46:09.940
[Guest]: is a bit more in check because of this book. I do think that. I think that I realize through

03:46:09.940 --> 03:46:14.820
[Guest]: the lives of the love lives of others in particular, and just the struggles to find

03:46:14.820 --> 03:46:21.140
[Guest]: things that are very easy for me, that, as you say, life is complex, it's messy. And I think

03:46:21.140 --> 03:46:25.700
[Guest]: these stories just reminded me of that every day through the process of writing it through

03:46:25.700 --> 03:46:32.420
[Guest]: the process of engaging with it. And I think it's made me less transactional in my dealings with

03:46:32.420 --> 03:46:37.780
[Guest]: people, I'd like to believe. And that's something that I'm I keep holding myself accountable to

03:46:37.780 --> 03:46:44.980
[Guest]: part of my adulthood. And I also think that what the book has done is, I have to be honest,

03:46:44.980 --> 03:46:50.180
[Guest]: I mean, there are lots of grudges that I was carrying about, you know, feeling ignored,

03:46:50.740 --> 03:46:55.300
[Guest]: dismissed, not being treated well by a certain type of person. And I think I just poured all

03:46:55.300 --> 03:47:00.580
[Guest]: my grudges as well into this book. And now I emerged somewhat cleansed for I don't know,

03:47:00.580 --> 03:47:05.380
[Guest]: the next set of grudges, I don't know that I might I might tackle but but but on a serious

03:47:05.380 --> 03:47:09.780
[Guest]: note, I think what I'm trying to say essentially, is that I think it's been a process of,

03:47:10.740 --> 03:47:17.620
[Guest]: of letting go of a lot of preconceived notions of a lot of concerns about how will people see me?

03:47:17.620 --> 03:47:21.940
[Guest]: And will this be a serious book? And I had to just let all of that go to actually write the

03:47:21.940 --> 03:47:26.820
[Guest]: book that I really wanted to write. And I think it's been a process of that kind of transformation

03:47:26.820 --> 03:47:31.620
[Guest]: for me. I would like to believe that even for the women who participated in the book, I think the

03:47:31.620 --> 03:47:36.100
[Guest]: reason they participated in the book, I often joke, one is, of course, pity for me, because

03:47:36.100 --> 03:47:39.700
[Guest]: they felt that no one was marrying me. So they should at least participate in this project to

03:47:39.700 --> 03:47:44.820
[Guest]: help me out, you know, so that so that my life wouldn't seem as useless and lonely as someone

03:47:44.820 --> 03:47:51.460
[Guest]: who's unmarried, their lives are. But the other reason is that I think we co created just, you

03:47:51.460 --> 03:47:56.820
[Guest]: know, a set of frameworks and stories around Mr. Khan that I think many of us are very interested

03:47:56.820 --> 03:48:00.740
[Guest]: in. I really hope the book is translated because actually many of the conversations, as you can

03:48:00.740 --> 03:48:06.020
[Guest]: imagine, Amit happened in Hindi, I would like more younger people who actually, you know, speak the

03:48:06.020 --> 03:48:10.340
[Guest]: language of the larger part of the country, especially where the stories are situated,

03:48:10.340 --> 03:48:14.660
[Guest]: where Hindi is actually a dominant language for that Hindi and Bangla. I really hope that happens.

03:48:15.380 --> 03:48:21.220
[Guest]: And so I think it's changed me in that it's just I'm a calmer, more less transactional and a bit

03:48:21.220 --> 03:48:26.740
[Guest]: less selfish. I mean, I'd like to believe that. And on the question that you asked about

03:48:26.740 --> 03:48:31.220
[Guest]: transactions, I mean, in the book, and we talked about this, I think some time ago, I describe it

03:48:31.220 --> 03:48:37.620
[Guest]: as a disease. It's the disease of laveria. It is a transactional hustling of love, love in its

03:48:37.620 --> 03:48:43.860
[Guest]: truest form, looking at, be it religion, the good parts of religion, be it reading Eric Fromm, be

03:48:43.860 --> 03:48:50.180
[Guest]: it Mr. Khan's films, is making peace with the romantic injustice of the world, the world is

03:48:50.180 --> 03:48:55.780
[Guest]: unfair, and you will never, you know, find the mate that you want, maybe you're lucky and you do,

03:48:55.780 --> 03:49:00.180
[Guest]: maybe you won't always be as desired as you want to be. I think there's this beautiful quote,

03:49:00.180 --> 03:49:05.780
[Guest]: I think it was Pico Ayer who said that all pain in life happens when people don't see you the way

03:49:05.780 --> 03:49:11.780
[Guest]: you see yourself. And I think love is being okay with that realization that people will never see

03:49:11.780 --> 03:49:17.700
[Guest]: you the way you really want to be seen. And loving yourself as well as loving the world in general

03:49:17.700 --> 03:49:22.740
[Guest]: is an attitude of generosity where you say, well, that's okay, that I may not be the most desired,

03:49:22.740 --> 03:49:28.660
[Guest]: I may not find my heart's desire. But much like Mr. Khan in Kabhi Haan Kabhi Naan, which I believe

03:49:28.660 --> 03:49:34.340
[Guest]: is his best film, you just have to hold yourself, do what you need to do and find the small joys

03:49:34.340 --> 03:49:38.820
[Guest]: and delights in the world. And to me, I think that is love. That is, I think the exit out of

03:49:38.820 --> 03:49:45.140
[Guest]: this transactional hustle culture of love, which is to accept that there is injustice in the world,

03:49:45.140 --> 03:49:49.540
[Guest]: there are some injustices you can try and do something about. And then there are some which

03:49:49.540 --> 03:49:53.860
[Guest]: seem unfair in the interpersonal domain. And sadly, we all have to make our peace with it

03:49:53.860 --> 03:49:58.740
[Guest]: and perhaps create art out of it and make sense of it in our own ways as we can.

03:49:58.740 --> 03:50:02.580
[Amit Varma]: Yeah. And if it's any consolation in the end, it doesn't matter because we're all going to die.

03:50:02.580 --> 03:50:02.980
[Unknown]: No.

03:50:02.980 --> 03:50:08.820
[Amit Varma]: So that's my, yeah, repudiating the optimist that suddenly emerged a while back.

03:50:08.820 --> 03:50:12.820
[Guest]: We should leave it at an optimistic note, which is to say that, well, even if you die,

03:50:12.820 --> 03:50:16.980
[Guest]: there are these memories and there is something that you've left behind for someone or the other.

03:50:16.980 --> 03:50:21.700
[Amit Varma]: Right. Right. So before I go on to my last question, I just like one aspect of the book,

03:50:21.700 --> 03:50:25.460
[Amit Varma]: which I haven't spoken about at all, which we should speak about some other time,

03:50:26.020 --> 03:50:29.700
[Amit Varma]: is the writing, because I think the writing is so good, so entertaining.

03:50:29.700 --> 03:50:33.060
[Amit Varma]: You've been so vicious to so many people. It's lovely, you know.

03:50:33.060 --> 03:50:34.340
[Guest]: But kind to others as well.

03:50:34.340 --> 03:50:38.420
[Unknown]: Kind to others as well. You've been kind to the good people. You've been vicious to the bad people.

03:50:38.420 --> 03:50:39.940
[Guest]: You enjoyed the viciousness.

03:50:39.940 --> 03:50:44.660
[Amit Varma]: I love the viciousness. You were vicious to economists, to academics. And one hidden part

03:50:44.660 --> 03:50:49.060
[Amit Varma]: of it is how often you were alliterating so naturally, like, you know, you begin with

03:50:49.060 --> 03:50:54.180
[Amit Varma]: heteronormative hell. Then earlier you said, beech bechari beauty. And the book is full

03:50:54.180 --> 03:50:58.260
[Amit Varma]: of these really subtle, I mean, it just sounds so good if you read parts of it out.

03:50:58.260 --> 03:51:01.860
[Amit Varma]: So if some, you know, there's an audio book of it one day, I'm sure it'll sound good.

03:51:01.860 --> 03:51:05.220
[Amit Varma]: And I noted down a whole freaking page of great sentences from this.

03:51:05.220 --> 03:51:08.420
[Amit Varma]: I'm just going to read a couple of them out because I want listeners to

03:51:08.420 --> 03:51:12.420
[Amit Varma]: kind of pick up your book because it is not a serious, serious read.

03:51:12.420 --> 03:51:16.260
[Amit Varma]: The content is serious, but the journey going through it is so much fun.

03:51:16.260 --> 03:51:20.020
[Amit Varma]: And these two lines, especially I love one where you quote a friend saying,

03:51:20.020 --> 03:51:24.420
[Amit Varma]: in real life, men are sex crazed robots who can barely express themselves.

03:51:24.420 --> 03:51:27.780
[Amit Varma]: Stop quote. And this goes to your earlier thing about man childs.

03:51:27.780 --> 03:51:32.980
[Amit Varma]: But my favorite line is, quote, in Delhi, it is the truth universally acknowledged

03:51:32.980 --> 03:51:37.220
[Amit Varma]: that a single man in possession of a good fortune must be busy building his harem.

03:51:37.220 --> 03:51:37.860
[Amit Varma]: Stop quote.

03:51:37.860 --> 03:51:44.580
[Guest]: That's my hat tip to Jane Austen. And I think that sadly, this still holds to be true.

03:51:45.220 --> 03:51:49.460
[Guest]: I'm convinced, Amit, that my next book will be a drawing room theater of Delhi.

03:51:50.260 --> 03:51:54.260
[Guest]: And I will labor in service of that. But thank you for enjoying the book.

03:51:54.260 --> 03:51:58.420
[Amit Varma]: So my final question is this, and you will feel that you're not competent to answer it.

03:51:58.420 --> 03:52:01.140
[Amit Varma]: I already know that. And you will feel the imposter syndrome.

03:52:01.140 --> 03:52:05.140
[Amit Varma]: I think it would be very useful coming from you, which is for young people

03:52:05.140 --> 03:52:10.100
[Amit Varma]: who are listening to this podcast, whether they are just whether they are on the one hand,

03:52:10.100 --> 03:52:12.180
[Amit Varma]: in fact, let's make it a two part question.

03:52:12.180 --> 03:52:15.140
[Amit Varma]: On the one hand, if there are young women in India,

03:52:15.140 --> 03:52:19.060
[Amit Varma]: who are having trouble negotiating the realities of everyday life and

03:52:19.700 --> 03:52:22.580
[Amit Varma]: everything, what advice would you have for them? That's number one.

03:52:22.580 --> 03:52:26.020
[Amit Varma]: And number two, if there are young academics and researchers,

03:52:26.020 --> 03:52:28.420
[Amit Varma]: or even people who are not academics or researchers,

03:52:28.420 --> 03:52:33.860
[Amit Varma]: but who are interested in diving deep into this world to understand it better.

03:52:33.860 --> 03:52:36.340
[Amit Varma]: And by this world, I just mean Indian society in general,

03:52:36.340 --> 03:52:38.900
[Amit Varma]: to understand it better, what advice would you have for them?

03:52:39.700 --> 03:52:44.420
[Guest]: So I'll start with the advice for people who want to delve deep into this world.

03:52:44.420 --> 03:52:45.940
[Guest]: Get out. Don't be online.

03:52:49.140 --> 03:52:54.100
[Guest]: I sound like such a stuffy traditionalist, but I am a stuffy traditionalist.

03:52:54.100 --> 03:52:56.260
[Guest]: Don't spend time on Instagram.

03:52:56.260 --> 03:53:01.140
[Guest]: Don't think that self presentation on the internet is actually what's going to help

03:53:01.140 --> 03:53:06.260
[Guest]: you delve deep into our society and do not believe that seeing how others are

03:53:06.260 --> 03:53:11.780
[Guest]: representing themselves online is a way to better understand us.

03:53:11.780 --> 03:53:14.740
[Guest]: I'm sure it tells us something about aesthetics and presentation,

03:53:14.740 --> 03:53:19.060
[Guest]: but that I don't think is there's no reality. It's a hollow reality to me.

03:53:19.700 --> 03:53:21.860
[Guest]: So I think the main advice I would have is,

03:53:22.660 --> 03:53:25.060
[Guest]: don't be on the internet and don't always be looking at your phone,

03:53:25.060 --> 03:53:29.700
[Guest]: because it programs your brain in a way to stymie a kind of creativity and curiosity.

03:53:29.700 --> 03:53:36.100
[Guest]: And the second thing I would say to them is, read. Find a reader with you.

03:53:36.100 --> 03:53:38.980
[Guest]: Because I found, for me, Amit, I have to say,

03:53:39.780 --> 03:53:44.980
[Guest]: the sheer joy of this book and to read was actually to discuss these things with people

03:53:44.980 --> 03:53:48.500
[Guest]: who you can create a community around, right? That is the joy of this.

03:53:48.500 --> 03:53:50.740
[Guest]: And this is one of the small joys of life.

03:53:50.740 --> 03:53:54.420
[Guest]: And so I would say, find a community that will read with you,

03:53:54.420 --> 03:53:58.260
[Guest]: that will investigate with you, that will co-create this process with you.

03:53:58.260 --> 03:54:00.420
[Guest]: And I think there's a sense of solidarity in that.

03:54:00.420 --> 03:54:04.260
[Guest]: So I think I have very simple advice for people who are curious about the world,

03:54:04.260 --> 03:54:07.620
[Guest]: don't be online, find solidarity networks, find a community.

03:54:07.620 --> 03:54:10.900
[Guest]: I think that can be anything, whatever you'd like.

03:54:10.900 --> 03:54:14.180
[Guest]: The question on women is a bit hard.

03:54:14.180 --> 03:54:17.460
[Guest]: I would say two things, and I've actually thought about this

03:54:17.460 --> 03:54:20.260
[Guest]: actually a fair amount as I was writing about the book,

03:54:20.260 --> 03:54:23.220
[Guest]: not as advice, but just even for my own self.

03:54:23.220 --> 03:54:28.260
[Guest]: I think, number one, stop giving premium to a kind of love

03:54:28.260 --> 03:54:30.260
[Guest]: that you've been told to give premium to.

03:54:30.260 --> 03:54:33.780
[Guest]: So it's fine if the boy that, and I have to just,

03:54:33.780 --> 03:54:36.740
[Guest]: it's sad that I think so much of women's realities are just,

03:54:36.740 --> 03:54:39.860
[Guest]: especially young women's realities are so dictated by this thing about,

03:54:39.860 --> 03:54:42.340
[Guest]: you know, the boyfriend Olympics is what I call it.

03:54:43.060 --> 03:54:45.620
[Guest]: It's fine if it doesn't work out and it's okay.

03:54:45.620 --> 03:54:49.140
[Guest]: There's no shame in it, that it does not mean you're unworthy,

03:54:49.140 --> 03:54:50.500
[Guest]: unbeautiful, all of those things.

03:54:50.500 --> 03:54:53.940
[Guest]: I think it's okay to deviate from those scripts, and so I think that's one.

03:54:54.580 --> 03:54:57.700
[Guest]: The second thing I would say to women who are really struggling

03:54:57.700 --> 03:55:02.500
[Guest]: to just actuate their ambitions is find art.

03:55:02.500 --> 03:55:07.300
[Guest]: And I don't just mean art in the sense of something you do,

03:55:07.300 --> 03:55:09.540
[Guest]: but something you consume, something you participate in.

03:55:10.180 --> 03:55:13.140
[Guest]: Just being able to access something that's outside of your own reality

03:55:13.140 --> 03:55:16.260
[Guest]: and outside of your own milieu, I find that very helpful.

03:55:16.260 --> 03:55:20.340
[Guest]: It saved me at a time when I was really going through a very rough time,

03:55:20.340 --> 03:55:24.100
[Guest]: and I have to confess that had it not been for the books I was reading

03:55:24.100 --> 03:55:26.180
[Guest]: and had it not been for Mr. Khan, I think I would be

03:55:26.740 --> 03:55:29.620
[Guest]: a very different kind of wreck, a conformist wreck perhaps.

03:55:29.620 --> 03:55:33.060
[Guest]: And I have him and various feminists and books to,

03:55:33.060 --> 03:55:36.420
[Guest]: and economists to thank because I was reading their wonderful works.

03:55:36.420 --> 03:55:39.300
[Guest]: So I would say try and lose yourself a little bit in something else.

03:55:39.940 --> 03:55:42.260
[Guest]: And ideally this links to that whole notion of delight,

03:55:42.260 --> 03:55:44.820
[Guest]: that I think women are told that you should just do things that are,

03:55:44.820 --> 03:55:46.740
[Guest]: that have drudgery.

03:55:46.740 --> 03:55:49.380
[Guest]: No, you should find something that you truly enjoy,

03:55:50.020 --> 03:55:51.060
[Guest]: spend some time on it.

03:55:51.060 --> 03:55:53.620
[Guest]: And I think through that, you may actually surprise yourself

03:55:53.620 --> 03:55:57.060
[Guest]: that internally, psychologically navigating your life,

03:55:57.060 --> 03:56:00.420
[Guest]: you might find instruction in those moments of delight for yourself.

03:56:00.980 --> 03:56:03.620
[Guest]: And so I think to young women, I would say,

03:56:04.820 --> 03:56:06.820
[Guest]: retire a little bit from the boyfriend Olympics.

03:56:06.820 --> 03:56:08.020
[Guest]: If it doesn't work out, it's fine.

03:56:08.020 --> 03:56:08.980
[Guest]: If it works out, it's fine.

03:56:08.980 --> 03:56:11.780
[Guest]: Don't take it as seriously as I know girls in their early 20s

03:56:11.780 --> 03:56:13.540
[Guest]: and in their teens do, please don't.

03:56:13.540 --> 03:56:15.860
[Guest]: If they're watching this or they're listening to this,

03:56:15.860 --> 03:56:17.620
[Guest]: or if their mothers are.

03:56:17.620 --> 03:56:19.060
[Guest]: And the second is just find delight.

03:56:19.060 --> 03:56:22.500
[Guest]: Find delight in art or find delight in whatever you like.

03:56:22.500 --> 03:56:24.100
[Guest]: But I think delight is politics.

03:56:24.100 --> 03:56:25.860
[Guest]: I really believe that that helps.

03:56:25.860 --> 03:56:26.660
[Amit Varma]: That's lovely advice.

03:56:26.660 --> 03:56:30.100
[Amit Varma]: I've learned so much from reading your book and from this conversation.

03:56:30.100 --> 03:56:31.220
[Amit Varma]: So thank you for writing the book

03:56:31.220 --> 03:56:33.460
[Amit Varma]: and thank you for giving me four hours of your time.

03:56:33.460 --> 03:56:34.420
[Amit Varma]: Thank you so much, Amit.

03:56:34.420 --> 03:56:35.220
[Guest]: It was such a pleasure.

03:56:35.220 --> 03:56:38.260
[Guest]: I'm such a, I think, you know, I'm a fan and I love the show

03:56:38.260 --> 03:56:40.260
[Guest]: and more power to you and what you're trying to do.

03:56:40.260 --> 03:56:42.260
[Guest]: It was just a delight to be here.

03:56:42.260 --> 03:56:42.820
[Guest]: Thank you.

03:56:42.820 --> 03:56:43.700
[Amit Varma]: Thank you. Thank you.

03:57:13.140 --> 03:57:14.740
[Amit Varma]: at scene unseen.in

03:57:14.740 --> 03:57:35.940
[Amit Varma]: Thank you for listening.

